 Archives Nationales de France]. (Perth: Western Australian Museum, 1998)\n* Pearson, Michael: ''Great Southern Land: The Maritime Exploration of [[Terra Australis]]''. (Canberra: Department of Environment and Heritage, 2005)\n* Quanchi, Max; Robson, John: ''Historical Dictionary of the Discovery and [[Exploration of the Pacific|Exploration of the Pacific Islands]]''. (Lanham, MD and Oxford: Scarecrow Press, 2005)\n* Richards, Michael; O'Connor, Maura (eds.): ''Changing Coastlines: Putting Australia on the World Map, 1493\u20131993''. (Canberra: National Library of Australia, 1993)\n* Robert, Willem C. H.: ''The Explorations, 1696\u20131697, of Australia by [[Willem de Vlamingh]]. Extracts from Two Log-Books Concerning the Voyage to and Explorations on the Coast of Western Australia and from Other Documents Relating to this Voyage''. [Original Dutch texts]. (Amsterdam: Philo Press, 1972)\n* Robert, Willem C. H.: ''The Dutch Explorations, 1605\u20131756, of the North and Northwest Coast of Australia. Extracts from Journals, Log-books and Other Documents Relating to These Voyages''. [Original Dutch texts]. (Amsterdam: Philo Press, 1973)\n* Ryan, Simon: ''The Cartographic Eye: How Explorers Saw Australia''. (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1996)\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter: ''Australia Unveiled: The Share of the Dutch Navigators in the Discovery of Australia''. Translated from the German by Olaf Richter. (Amsterdam: Theatrum Orbis Terrarum, 1976)\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter: ''Voyage to the [[Great South Land]], Willem de Vlamingh, 1696\u20131697''. Translated by C. de Heer. (Sydney: Royal Australian Historical Society, 1985)\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter: ''In the Steps of Tasman and De Vlamingh. An Important Cartographic Document for the Discovery of Australia''. (Amsterdam: Nico Israel, 1988)\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter; Kok, Hans: ''Sailing for the East: History and Catalogue of Manuscript Charts on Vellum of the Dutch East India Company (VOC), 1602\u20131799''. (BRILL, 2010, {{ISBN|9789061942603}})\n* Sharp, Andrew: ''The Discovery of Australia''. (New York: Oxford University Press, 1963)\n* Sharp, Andrew: ''The Voyages of Abel Janszoon Tasman''. (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1968)\n* Shaw, Lindsey; Wilkins, Wendy (eds.): ''Dutch Connections: 400 Years of Australian-Dutch Maritime Links, 1606\u20132006''. (Sydney: Australian National Maritime Museum, 2006)\n* Sigmond, J. P.; Zuiderbaan, L. H.: ''Dutch Discoveries of Australia: Shipwrecks, Treasures and Early Voyages off the West Coast''. (Adelaide: Rigby, 1979)\n* Sigmond, J. P.; Zuiderbaan, L. H.: ''Nederlanders ontdekken Australi\u00eb: Scheepsarcheologische vondsten op het Zuidland''. (Amsterdam: De Bataafsche Leeuw, 1988) [in Dutch]\n* Stapel, F.W.: ''De Oostindische Compagnie en Australi\u00eb''. (Amsterdam: Van Kampen, 1937) [in Dutch]\n* Stein, Stephen K.: ''The Sea in World History: Exploration, Travel, and Trade''. (Santa Barbara, California: ABC-CLIO, 2017)\n* Su\u00e1rez, Thomas: ''[[Exploration of the Pacific|Early Mapping of the Pacific]]: The Epic Story of Seafarers, Adventurers, and Cartographers Who Mapped the Earth's Greatest Ocean''. (Singapore: Periplus Editions, 2004)\n* [[Abel Tasman|Tasman, Abel]]: ''The Journal of Abel Jansz Tasman, 1642; with Documents Relating to His Exploration of Australia in 1644''. Edited by G.H. Kenihan. (Adelaide: Australian Heritage Press, 1960)\n* Tasman, Abel: ''Het Journaal van Abel Tasman, 1642\u20131643''. [eds.: Vibeke Roeper & Diederick Wilderman]. (The Hague: Nationaal Archief, 2006) [in Dutch]\n* Van Duivenvoorde, Wendy: ''The Batavia Shipwreck: An Archaeological Study of an Early Seventeenth-Century [[:Category:Ships of the Dutch East India Company|Dutch East Indiaman]]''. (Ph.D. diss., [[Texas A&M University]], Dept of Anthropology, 2008) \n* Van Zanden, Henry: ''[[Janszoon voyage of 1605\u201306|1606]]: Discovery of Australia''. (Perth: Rio Bay Enterprises, 1997)\n* Veth, Peter; Sutton, Peter; Neale, Margo: ''Strangers on the Shore: Early Coastal Contacts in Australia''. (Canberra: National Museum of Australia Press, 2008, {{ISBN|9781876944636}})\n* Walker, James Backhouse: ''Abel Janszoon Tasman: His Life and Voyages, and The Discovery of [[Van Diemen's Land]] in 1642''. (Hobart: Government Printer, 1896)\n{{refend}}\n\n=====Journal articles, scholarly papers, essays=====\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* Broomhall, Susan (2014), 'Emotional Encounters: Indigenous Peoples in the Dutch East India Company's Interactions with the South Lands,'. Australian Historical Studies 45(3): pp.&nbsp;350\u2013367\n* [[Susan Broomhall|Broomhall, Susan]] (2015), '\"Quite indifferent to these things\": The Role of Emotions and Conversion in the Dutch East India Company's Interactions with the South Lands,'. Journal of Religious History 39(4): 524\u201344. {{doi|10.1111/1467-9809.12267}}\n* Broomhall, Susan (2016), 'Dishes, Coins and Pipes: The Epistemological and Emotional Power of VOC Material Culture in Australia,'. In ''The Global Lives of Things: The Material Culture of Connections in the Early Modern World'', edited by Anne Gerritsen & Giorgio Riello. (London: Routledge, 2016), pp.&nbsp;145\u201361\n* Broomhall, Susan (2017), 'Fire, Smoke and Ashes: Communications of Power and Emotions by Dutch East India Company Crews on the Australian Continent,'. In ''Fire Stories'', edited by G. Moore. (New York: Punctum Books, 2017)\n* Broomhall, Susan (2017), 'Shipwrecks, Sorrow, Shame and the Great Southland: The Use of Emotions in Seventeenth-Century Dutch East India Company Communicative Ritual,'. In ''Emotion, Ritual and Power in Europe, 1200\u20131920: Family, State and Church'', edited by M. Bailey and K. Barclay. (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2017), pp.&nbsp;83\u2013103\n* Broomhall, Susan (2018), 'Dirk Hartog's Sea Chest: An Affective Archaeology of VOC Objects in Australia,'; in ''Feeling Things: Objects and Emotions through History'', edited by Stephanie Downes, Sally Holloway and Sarah Randles. (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2018), pp.&nbsp;175\u201391\n* Donaldson, Bruce (2006), 'The Dutch Contribution to the European Discovery of Australia,'. In Nonja Peters (ed.), ''The Dutch [[Down Under]], 1606\u20132006''. (Crawley: University of Western Australia Press, 2006)\n* Gaastra, Femme (1997), 'The Dutch East India Company: A Reluctant Discoverer,'. Great Circle \u2013 Journal of the Australian Association for Maritime History 19(2): 109\u2013123 \n* Gentelli, Liesel (2016), 'Provenance Determination of Silver Artefacts from the 1629 VOC Wreck Batavia using LA-ICP-MS,'. Journal of Archaeological Science [Reports] 9: 536\u2013542. {{doi|10.1016/j.jasrep.2016.08.044}}\n* [[Rupert Gerritsen|Gerritsen, Rupert]] (2006), 'The evidence for cohabitation between Indigenous Australians, marooned Dutch mariners and VOC passengers,'; in Nonja Peters (ed.), ''The Dutch Down Under: 1606\u20132006''. (University of WA Press, Sydney, 2006), pp.&nbsp;38\u201355\n* Gerritsen, Rupert (2008), 'The landing site debate: Where were Australia's first European residents marooned in 1629?', pp.&nbsp;105\u2013129; in P. Hornsby & J. Maschke (eds.) ''Hydro 2007 Conference Proceedings: Focus on Asia''. (International Federation of Hydrographic Societies, Belrose)\n* Gerritsen, Rupert (2009), 'The Batavia Mutiny: Australia's first military conflict in 1629,'. Sabretache: Journal and Proceedings of the Military Historical Society of Australia 50(4): 5\u201310\n* Gerritsen, Rupert (2011), 'Australia's First Criminal Prosecutions in 1629'. (Canberra: Batavia Online Publishing)\n* Gibbs, Martin (2002), 'Maritime Archaeology and Behavior during Crisis: The Wreck of the VOC Ship Batavia (1629),'; in John Grattan & Robin Torrence (eds.), ''Natural Disasters and Cultural Change''. (New York: Routledge, 2002), pp.&nbsp;66\u201386\n* Green, Jeremy N. (1975), 'The VOC ship Batavia wrecked in 1629 on the Houtman Abrolhos, Western Australia,'. International Journal of Nautical Archaeology 4(1): 43\u201363. {{doi|10.1111/j.1095-9270.1975.tb00902.x}}\n* Green, Jeremy N. (2006), 'The Dutch Down Under: Sailing Blunders,'. In Nonja Peters (ed.), ''The Dutch Down Under, 1606\u20132006''. (Crawley: University of Western Australia Press, 2006)\n* Guy, Richard (2015), 'Calamitous Voyages: the social space of shipwreck and mutiny narratives in the Dutch East India Company,'. Itinerario 39(1): 117\u2013140. {{doi|10.1017/S0165115315000157}}\n* Ketelaar, Eric (2008), 'Exploration of the Archived World: From [[Hartog Plate|De Vlamingh's Plate]] to Digital Realities,'. Archives and Manuscripts 36(2): 13\u201333\n* McCarthy, M. (2006), '[[Australian places with Dutch names|Dutch place names in Australia]],'. In Nonja Peters (ed.), ''The Dutch Down Under, 1606\u20132006''. (Crawley: University of Western Australia Press, 2006)\n* McCarthy, M. (2006), 'The Dutch on Australian shores: The Zuytdorp tragedy \u2013 unfinished business,'. In L. Shaw & W. Wilkins (eds.), ''Dutch Connections: 400 Years of Australian\u2013Dutch Maritime Links, 1606\u20132006'' (Sydney: Australian National Maritime Museum, 2006), pp.&nbsp;94\u2013109\n* Mutch, T. D. (1942), 'The First Discovery of Australia with an Account of the Voyages of the Duyfken and the Career of [[Willem Janszoon|William Jansz.]],'. JRAHS 28(5): 303\u2013352\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter (1976), 'Organisation and Evolution of the Dutch East India Company's Hydrographic Office in the Seventeenth Century,'. Imago Mundi 28: 61\u201378\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter (1988), '[[New Holland (Australia)|New Holland]]: The Dutch Discoveries,'; in Glyndwr Williams and Alan Frost (eds.), ''Terra Australis to Australia''. (Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1988), pp.&nbsp;83\u2013115\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter (1984), 'The Dutch Conception of New Holland in the Seventeenth and Early Eighteenth Centuries,'. The Globe: Journal of the Australian Map Circle 22: 38\u201346\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter (1989), 'From Secret to Common Knowledge \u2013 The Dutch Discoveries,'; in John Hardy and Alan Frost (eds.), ''Studies from Terra Australis to Australia''. (Canberra, 1989)\n* Schilder, G\u00fcnter (1993), 'A Continent Takes Shape: The [[Dutch mapping of Australia|Dutch Mapping of Australia]],'; in ''Changing Coastlines'', edited by Michael Richards & Maura O'Connor. (Canberra: National Library of Australia, 1993), pp.&nbsp;10\u201316\n* Sheehan, Colin (2008), 'Strangers and Servants of the Company: The United East India Company and the [[European maritime exploration of Australia|Dutch Voyages to Australia]],'; in Peter Veth, Margo Neale, et al. (eds.), ''Strangers on the Shore: Early Coastal Contacts in Australia''. (Canberra: National Museum of Australia Press, {{ISBN|9781876944636}})\n* Sigmond, Peter (2006), 'Cultural Heritage and [[Hartog Plate|a Piece of Pewter]],\u2019; in L. Shaw & W. Wilkins (eds.), ''Dutch Connections: 400 Years of Australian\u2013Dutch Maritime Links, 1606\u20132006''. (Sydney: Australian National Maritime Museum, 2006)\n* Van Duivenvoorde, Wendy; Kaiser, Bruce; Megens, Luc; van Bronswijk, Wilhelm (2015), 'Pigments from the Zuiddorp (Zuytdorp) ship sculpture: red, white and blue?,'. Post-Medieval Archaeology 49(2): 268\u2013290\n* Yahya, Padillah; Gaudieri, Silvana; Franklin, Daniel (2010), '[[DNA Analysis]] of Human Skeletal Remains Associated with the Batavia Mutiny of 1629,'. Records of the Western Australian Museum 26: 98\u2013108\n{{refend}}\n\n===Primary sources===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* Clark, C.M.H. ed. ''Select documents in Australian history'' (2 vol. 1950)\n* Kemp, Rod, and Marion Stanton, eds. ''Speaking for Australia: Parliamentary Speeches That Shaped Our Nation'' Allen & Unwin, 2004 [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=110168653 online edition]\n* Crowley, Frank, ed. ''A documentary history of Australia'' (5 vol. Melbourne: Wren, 1973); ''v.1. Colonial Australia, 1788\u20131840 \u2013 v.2. Colonial Australia, 1841\u20131874 -v.3. Colonial Australia, 1875\u20131900 -v.4. Modern Australia, 1901\u20131939 -v.5. Modern Australia, 1939\u20131970''\n* Daniels, Kay, ed. ''Australia's women, a documentary history: from a selection of personal letters, diary entries, pamphlets, official records, government and police reports, speeches, and radio talks'' (2nd ed. U of Queensland Press, 1989) 335pp. The first edition was entitled '' Uphill all the way : a documentary history of women in Australia'' (1980).\n* Teale, Ruth, ed. ''Colonial Eve: sources on women in Australia, 1788\u20131914'' (Melbourne : Oxford University Press, 1978)\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{main|Bibliography of Australian history}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks|Australian History}}\n{{Commons category|History of Australia}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090115211903/http://www.themonthly.com.au/tm/node/781 ''Australia: The Official History''], by John Hirst, February 2008, ''[[The Monthly]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060917170600/http://www.atmitchell.com/journeys/history/ History of the Australian nation \u2013 State Library of NSW]\n*The [http://gutenberg.net.au/aust-history.html Australian History] page at [http://gutenberg.net.au Project Gutenberg of Australia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080113105115/http://www.bushpoetry.org.au/ Bush Poetry a source of Australian History]\n* [http://www.tandfonline.com/toc/rahs20/current ''Australian Historical Studies''], a scholarly journal\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150519152401/http://uow.libguides.com/content.php?pid=131840&sid=1130480 ''Historical Primary Sources'']\n* [http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/discover_collections/index.html \"State Library of New South Wales Online Collections\"]\n* [http://www.awm.gov.au/database/ \"Australian War Memorial Collections\"]\n* [https://www.scribd.com/doc/4859766/Some-Inspirational-People-profiled-by-Laurence-MacDonald-Muir/ \"Some Inspirational (Australian) People\"] Profiled by [[Sir Laurence Muir|Laurence MacDonald Muir]].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120228222213/http://australianempire.webs.com/ \"The Australian Empire\"] by Rob Robinson, 2009\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080903131313/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/discover_collections/history_nation/terra_australis/index.html From Terra Australis to Australia], State Library of New South Wales\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110216230554/http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/australianhistory/ European discovery and the colonisation of Australia \u2013 Australian Government]\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/local/audio/2010/05/14/2899543.htm Looking For Blackfellas Point] History of European settlement and relations with Aboriginal people of South Eastern Australia, Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n* [http://www.rahs.org.au Royal Australian Historical Society]\n\n{{Australia topic|title=History of Australia|prefix=History of|VI=Victoria}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list ={{History by continent}}\n{{History of Oceania}}\n{{Coord|25|21|S|131|14|E|source:ruwiki|display=title}}\n}}\n\n{{Australia topics}}\n{{Convicts in Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Australia}}\n[[Category:History of Australia| ]]\n", "name_user": "83.241.181.4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Railways in Melbourne", "text_new": "{{about|the Melbourne rail network, including stations and infrastructure|operator of suburban passenger services in Melbourne|Metro Trains Melbourne}}\n{{short description|Railway network in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit\n| box_width = \n| name = Melbourne railway network\n| image = Melbourne train logo.svg\n| alt = Metropolitan Melbourne train network logo\n| imagesize = 100px\n| caption = \n| image2 = 1_flinders_st_station_melb.jpg\n| alt2 = \n| imagesize2 = \n| caption2 = Flinders Street railway station in 2010\n| native_name = <!-- use {{lang}} -->\n| owner = [[VicTrack]]\n| area served = \n| locale = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]<br />[[Australia]]\n| transit_type = [[Commuter rail]]\n| lines = 16\n| line_number = \n| start = \n| end = \n| stations = 220\n| daily_ridership = \n| annual_ridership = {{increase}} 243.2 million {{small|(2018-19)}}\n| chief_executive = \n| headquarters = \n| website = \n| began_operation = {{start date and age|1854|09|12|df=yes}}\n| ended_operation = <!-- {{end date and age|yyyy|mm|dd|df=yes}} -->\n| operator = [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]<br>[[V/Line]]\n| marks = \n| host = \n| character = At-grade with elevated and underground sections\n| vehicles = 224 six-car sets {{small|(October 2018)}}\n| train_length = \n| headway = \n| system_length = {{cvt|405|km|mi}}\n| notrack = \n| track_gauge = {{Track gauge|victorian|allk=on}}\n| ogauge = Various\n| minimum_radius_of_curvature = <!-- {{convert|0|ft|0|in|mm|0}} -->\n| el = 1500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[Overhead line|overhead]] (excluding Stony Point, which is not electrified)\n| average_speed = <!-- {{convert|0|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} -->\n| top_speed = <!-- {{convert|0|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} -->\n| map = {{Melbourne commuter rail route diagram|inline=yes}}\n| map_name = \n| map_state = collapsed\n}}\n{{Melbourne railway lines}}\n \nThe '''Melbourne rail network''' is a passenger and freight train system in the city of [[Melbourne]], Australia. It is the core of the larger [[Railways in Victoria|Victorian railway network]], with links to both intrastate and interstate systems. A large suburban passenger network centred on the [[Melbourne CBD|CBD]] also operates, with a limited degree of segregation from longer-distance passenger and freight trains.\n\nThe first steam train in Australia commenced service in Melbourne in 1854, with the network having grown over the last two centuries to consist of 220 stations across 16 lines, serving a yearly ridership of 243.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/assets/default-site/footer/data-and-reporting/annual-report/6b8c2cff5a/PTVH4043-Annual_Report_2019-A4-v1_ONLINE.pdf|title=Public Transport Victoria Annual Report 2018-2019|date=September 2019|website=static.ptv.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> [[Metro Trains Melbourne]] operates the Melbourne suburban railway network under [[franchising|franchise]] from the [[States and territories of Australia|State]] [[State Government of Victoria|Government of Victoria]], whilst the [[government-owned]] entity [[V/Line]] operates trains from Melbourne across [[Rail transport in Victoria|regional Victoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/victorias-public-transport-network/public-transport-partnership-agreements/|title=Public transport partnership agreements|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe suburban network is a [[commuter rail]] system designed to transport passengers from Melbourne's suburbs into the [[Melbourne city centre|Central Business District]] (CBD) and associated [[City Loop|city loop]] stations, with the main [[Transport hub|hub]] at [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street station]]. An underground line is currently under construction as part of the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]], which aims to unlock network capacity and provide Melbourne with a turn-up-and-go metro-like service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/melbourne-on-track-for-tokyos-turn-up-and-go-network/|title=Melbourne on Track For Tokyo's Turn Up And Go Network|date=2016-09-26|work=Premier of Victoria|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nA total length of 405&nbsp;km of track is owned by [[VicTrack]] and leased to train operators through [[Public Transport Victoria]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://classic.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/data-and-reports/research-and-statistics/|title=Research and statistics |website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English |access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> The railway network is primarily at ground level, with smaller underground and [[Elevated railway|elevated]] sections.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ptua.org.au/2009/09/02/cross-out-level-crossings/ |title=Cross out Melbourne\u2019s level crossings \u2013 Public Transport Users Association (Victoria, Australia)|website=www.ptua.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> There were more than 170 [[level crossing]]s before the [[Level Crossing Removal Authority|Level Crossing Removal Project]] commenced in 2015 to grade separate 75 of the busiest crossings and ease associated road congestion.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/about|title=About {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Authority|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> The suburban network operates primarily between 5:00&nbsp;a.m. and midnight, with 24-hour services from Friday to Sunday.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/all-night-public-transport-on-weekends-here-to-stay/|title=All Night Public Transport on Weekends Here To Stay|date=2017-04-22 |work=Premier of Victoria|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Some tracks are also used by [[Freight railways in Melbourne|freight trains]] and [[V/Line]] [[List of regional railway stations in Victoria|regional services]].\n\nIn addition to the primary commuter and freight railway networks, Melbourne also features heritage railways such as [[Puffing Billy Railway|Puffing Billy]] and has the world's largest urban [[Trams in Melbourne|tram network]].\n\n== History ==\n=== First railway ===\nOn 7 September 1851 a public meeting called for the construction of Australia's first railway to linking Melbourne and Sandridge (now known as [[Port Melbourne]]), which led to the establishment of the privately owned [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] in 1853.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://collections.museumvictoria.com.au/articles/2215|title=Melbourne & Hobson's Bay Railway Co., Melbourne, Victoria|work=Museums Victoria Collections|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://infrastructure.gov.au/rail/trains/history.aspx|title=History of Rail in Australia|website=infrastructure.gov.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 1853 the Government also approved the establishment of the [[Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company]] and the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]]. Work began in March 1853 on the Sandridge railway line, stretching {{convert|4|km}} from the Melbourne (or City) terminus (on the site of modern-day [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street station]]) to Sandridge. The line was owned and operated by Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company, opening in 1854.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austehc.unimelb.edu.au/tia/836.html|title=Technology in Australia 1788-1988, Chapter 12, page 836|last=Centre|first=Australian Science and Technology Heritage|website=www.austehc.unimelb.edu.au|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1855 the Government conducted enquiries and carried out surveys into country railways. On 1 April 1856, the [[Victorian Railways|Railway Department]] was established as part of the Board of Land and Works with [[George Christian Darbyshire]] being appointed Engineer in Chief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/90654|title=Parliament of Victoria Record 90654|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> On 23 May of that year the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]] was taken over by the Government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=National Trust Masonry Bridges Study Gary Vines|publisher=National Trust of Australia (Victoria)|year=2010}}</ref>\n\nTrains were ordered from Robert Stephenson and Company of the [[United Kingdom]]. The first train was locally built by [[Robertson, Martin & Smith]], however, owing to delays in shipping. Australia's first steam locomotive was built in ten weeks and cost [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,700. Forming the first [[Locomotive#Steam|steam train]] to travel in Australia, it made its maiden trip on 12 September 1854.<ref>Although horse-drawn \"trains\" debuted on a [[Victor Harbor railway line|railway between Goolwa and Port Elliot]] in [[South Australia]] on 18 May of that year, Melbourne hosted the first mechanical railway.</ref>\n\nThe opening of the line occurred during the period of the [[Victorian gold rush]]\u2014a time when both Melbourne and Victoria undertook massive capital works, each with its own gala opening. The inaugural journey on the Sandridge line was no exception. According to the [[The Argus (Australia)|Argus]] [[newspaper]]'s report of the next day: \"''Long before the hour appointed . . . a great crowd assembled round the station at the Melbourne terminus, lining the whole of [[Flinders Street, Melbourne|Flinders Street]]''\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/rosstown-springvale-cemetery-kew-melbournes-phantom-railway-lines/news-story/1fff2d2be277ede00fb41886c7b19e6b|title=Rosstown, Springvale Cemetery, Kew: Melbourne's phantom railway lines|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> [[Governors of Victoria|Lieutenant-Governor]] [[Charles Hotham|Sir Charles Hotham]] and Lady Hotham were aboard the train\u2014which consisted of two [[First class travel|first class]] carriages and one second class\u2014and were presented with [[satin]] copies of the railway's [[Public transport timetable|timetable]] and [[bylaw]]s.\n\nThe trip took 10 minutes, none of the later stations along the line having been built yet. On arriving at [[Station Pier]] (onto which the tracks extended), it was hailed with gun-salutes by the warships [[HMS Electra (1837)|HMS ''Electra'']] and [[HMS Fantome (1839)|HMS ''Fantome'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://twistedhistory.net.au/wordpress/2017/09/12/australias-first-train-makes-its-maiden-voyage-melbourne-2/|title=Australia\u2019s first train makes its maiden voyage \u2013 Melbourne|date=2017-09-11|work=Twisted History (Limelight Tours)|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nBy March 1855, the four engines ordered from the UK were all in service, with trains running every half-hour. They were named ''Melbourne'', ''Sandridge'', ''Victoria'', and ''Yarra'' (after the [[Yarra River]] over which the line crossed).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1839-1899|title=Victorian Railways History 1839 - 1899|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=29 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Early private companies ===\n[[File:Melbourne-steam-hauled-suburban.jpg|thumb|Steam-hauled suburban train departing North Melbourne station for Sunshine]]\n[[File:Old Flinders Street Station.jpg|thumb|The pre 1910 [[Flinders Street railway station]] building on [[Swanston Street]]]]\n\nThe [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] opened Melbourne's second railway on 13 May 1857, a 4.5&nbsp;km line from the Melbourne (or City) Terminus to [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]]. The line was later extended by the [[St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company]], which opened a line from St Kilda to [[Middle Brighton railway station|Brighton]] in 1857.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe first country line opened in 1857, when the [[Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company]] started services on its line from [[Geelong]] to [[Newport railway station, Melbourne|Newport]]. In 1859, the government-owned [[Victorian Railways]] [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown line]] opened, connecting [[Williamstown railway station|Williamstown]] and Geelong to [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMore country lines followed in 1859 when the Victorian Railways opened a line from [[Footscray railway station|Footscray]], on the Williamstown line, to [[Sunbury railway station, Melbourne|Sunbury]]. The Victorian Railways had taken over construction from the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]], established in 1853 to build a railway to [[Echuca, Victoria|Echuca]], but which had failed to make any progress.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe first line to Melbourne's south-eastern suburbs was opened in 1859 by the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]], running from [[Princes Bridge railway station]] to [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Punt Road]] (Richmond), [[South Yarra railway station|South Yarra]], and [[Prahran railway station|Prahran]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=449&gall=453|title=Melbourne & Suburban Railway Co. - Victorian Railways, Museum Victoria, Australia|website=museumsvictoria.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> That line was extended to [[Windsor railway station, Melbourne|Windsor]] in 1860, connecting with the St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company line from St Kilda. The new line replaced the indirect [[St Kilda - Windsor railway line|St Kilda and Windsor line]] to the city, which was closed in 1867.\n\nAnother suburban line was built by the [[Melbourne and Essendon Railway Company]] in 1860, running from [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]] to [[Essendon railway station|Essendon]], with a branch line from [[Newmarket railway station, Melbourne|Newmarket]] to [[Flemington Racecourse railway station|Flemington Racecourse]], which opened in 1861. On the eastern side of the city, the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]] opened a branch line from Richmond to [[Burnley railway station|Burnley]] and [[Hawthorn railway station, Melbourne|Hawthorn]] in 1861.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/mileposts_vr_history.pdf|title=Mileposts in Victorian Railway History 1839-1964|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy that point, the railways of Melbourne were a disjointed group of city-centric lines, with various companies operating from three unconnected city terminals\u2014[[Princes Bridge railway station|Princes Bridge]], [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]], and [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street]] stations.\n\nThe smaller companies quickly encountered financial problems. The [[St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company]] and [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]] were absorbed by the [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] in 1865, forming the [[Melbourne and Hobsons Bay United Railway Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hstm-index.com/index/melbourne-suburban-railway-company-32.html|title=HSTM Historic Stocks Market Index {{!}} Melbourne & Suburban Railway Company|website=www.hstm-index.com|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> The [[Melbourne and Essendon Railway Company]] was taken over by the Victorian Government in 1867. The Melbourne and Hobsons Bay United Railway Company was not taken over by the [[Victorian Government]] until 1878.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/88980|title=Melbourne and Hobson's Bay United Railway Railway : return to an Order of the Legislative Assembly dated 16th July 1878 for a return showing the Agreement made between the Directors of the Melbourne and Hobson's Bay United Railway Company and the Government for the purchase of the undertaking of the Company|last=Parliamentary Papers Database|first=Parliament of Victoria|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nThe terminals themselves were linked in 1879, when track was built at street level along the southern side of Flinders Street, connecting with [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]], although the track was only used at night, for freight traffic. It was not until 1889 that the two-track [[Flinders Street Viaduct]] was built between the two city terminus stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/location/Viaduct-Junction|title=VICSIG Infrastructure|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOutward expansion also continued, with major trunk lines being opened in rural Victoria. The Victorian Railways extended its line to [[Broadmeadows railway station, Melbourne|Broadmeadows]] in 1872, as part of the line to [[Seymour railway station|Seymour]] and [[Albury railway station|Albury]]-[[Wodonga railway station|Wodonga]]. In 1879, the [[Gippsland Railway|Gippsland line]] was opened from South Yarra to [[Caulfield railway station, Melbourne|Caulfield]], [[Pakenham railway station|Pakenham]] and [[Bairnsdale, Victoria|Bairnsdale]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Land boom lines ===\n[[File:Camberwell Station 1.jpg|thumb|Connex train arriving at [[Camberwell railway station, Melbourne|Camberwell]] railway station]]\n[[File:Alameinstation.jpg|thumb|Train at [[Alamein railway station]]]]\n\nThe 1870s and 1880s were a time of great growth and prosperity in Melbourne. Land speculation companies were formed, to buy up outer suburban land cheaply, and to agitate for suburban railways to be built or extended to serve these land holdings and increase land values. By 1880 the \"Land Boom\" was in full swing in Victoria, with the passing of the [[Railway Construction Act 1884]], later known as the ''Octopus Act'' for the 66 lines across the state that were authorised in it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/onthisday/decade.cfm?d=1880 |title=On These Days - Parliament of Victoria |publisher=parliament.vic.gov.au |accessdate=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815114743/http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/onthisday/decade.cfm?d=1880 |archivedate=15 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] began with the opening of a line from Caulfield to [[Mordialloc railway station|Mordialloc]] in 1881, reaching the terminus in 1882.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhistory.kingston.vic.gov.au/htm/article/329.htm|title=Events in the Past: Establishing a Railway Line to Mordialloc|last=Historical Website|first=City of Kingston|website=localhistory.kingston.vic.gov.au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> A second new suburban railway line was opened from Spencer Street Station to [[Coburg railway station|Coburg]] in 1884, and extended to [[Somerton, Victoria|Somerton]] in 1889, meeting the main line from Spencer Street to Wodonga.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alburywodongaaustralia.com.au/info/history/|title=Albury Wodonga History - Albury Wodonga Australia|website=www.alburywodongaaustralia.com.au|language=en-au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> Land developers opened a private railway from Newport to [[Altona railway station|Altona]] in 1888, but it was closed in 1890, due to lack of demand.\n\nThe line from Hawthorn was extended, to [[Camberwell railway station, Melbourne|Camberwell]] in 1882, [[Lilydale railway station|Lilydale]] in 1883, and [[Healesville railway station|Healesville]] in 1889.<ref name=\":3\" /> In addition, a branch line (now known as the [[Belgrave railway line|Belgrave line]]) was opened from [[Ringwood railway station, Melbourne|Ringwood]] to [[Upper Ferntree Gully railway station|Upper Ferntree Gully]] in 1889.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maroondah.vic.gov.au/Explore/About-our-city/History-of-Maroondah/History-of-Ringwood|title=History of Ringwood|website=www.maroondah.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> A short branch two station was also opened from Hawthorn to [[Kew railway line|Kew]] in 1887. The Brighton Beach line was also extended to [[Sandringham railway station|Sandringham]] in 1887.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianplaces.com.au/sandringham|title=Sandringham {{!}} Victorian Places|website=www.victorianplaces.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1888, railways came to the north eastern suburbs with the opening of the [[Inner Circle railway line|Inner Circle]] line from [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]] via [[Royal Park railway station, Melbourne|Royal Park]] station to what is now [[Victoria Park railway station, Melbourne|Victoria Park]] station, and then on to [[Heidelberg railway station|Heidelberg]]. A branch was also opened off the Inner Circle in [[Fitzroy North, Victoria|Fitzroy North]], to [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] and [[Whittlesea railway station, Melbourne|Whittlesea]] in 1888 and 1889.<ref name=\":2\" /> Trains between Spencer Street and Heidelberg reversed at Victoria Park until a link was opened between Victoria Park and [[Princes Bridge railway station|Princes Bridge]] in 1901.\n\nThe [[Outer Circle railway line|Outer Circle]] line opened in 1890, linking [[Oakleigh railway station|Oakleigh]] (on the [[Pakenham railway line|Gippsland line]]) to [[Riversdale railway station|Riversdale]] (with a branch to Camberwell on the [[Lilydale railway line|Lilydale line]]) and [[Fairfield railway station, Melbourne|Fairfield]] (on the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Heidelberg line]]). Originally envisaged to link the [[Gippsland Railway|Gippsland line]] with [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]] in the 1870s, this reason disappeared with the building of a direct link via South Yarra before the line had even opened. The line saw little traffic as it traversed empty paddocks, and with no through traffic, the Outer Circle was closed in sections between 1893 and 1897. The [[Alamein railway line|Camberwell to Ashburton]] stretch of the Outer Circle re-opened in 1899, then in 1900, part of the northern section of the Outer Circle reopened as a shuttle service between [[East Camberwell railway station|East Camberwell]] and [[Deepdene railway station, Melbourne|Deepdene station]]. This line closed in 1927.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outercircleline.com.au/about-me.html|title=The Outer Circle - Melbourne's Forgotten Railway|website=outercircleline.com.au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the same time as the Outer Circle, a railway was opened from Burnley to [[Darling railway station|Darling]] and a junction with the Outer Circle at [[Waverley Road railway station|Waverley Road]] (near the modern [[East Malvern railway station|East Malvern]]). A stub of the future Glen Waverley line, it was cut back to Darling in 1895.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8594287|title=THE GLEN IRIS LINE.|date=1890-03-13|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2018-05-12|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nThe land boom railway building hit a peak with the construction of the [[Rosstown Railway]] between Elsternwick and Oakleigh. Built by [[William Murry Ross]], the line was planned from the 1870s to serve a sugar beet mill near Caulfield. Construction commenced in 1883, followed by rebuilding in 1888. Ross's debt grew, and he attempted to sell the line many times without success. The line never opened to traffic and was later dismantled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/files/assets/public/document-resources/recreation/rosstown_rail_trail.pdf|title=Rosstown Rail Trail|website=Glen Eira City Council|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe stock market crash of 1891 lead to an extended period of economic depression, and put an end to railway construction until the next decade.\n\nBy the 1900s, the driving force for new railway lines were the farmers in what is now Melbourne's outer suburbs. In the [[Dandenong Ranges]] a narrow gauge [[Narrow gauge lines of the Victorian Railways|762 mm line]] was opened from Upper Ferntree Gully to [[Belgrave railway station|Belgrave]] and [[Gembrook railway station|Gembrook]] in 1900 to serve the local farming and timber community. In the [[Yarra Valley]] a branch was opened from Lilydale to [[Yarra Junction railway station|Yarra Junction]] and [[Warburton railway station|Warburton]] in 1901. Part of this line is now listed on the [[Victorian Heritage Register]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vhd.heritagecouncil.vic.gov.au/places/115471/download-report|title=Victorian Heritage Database Report: Lilydale - Warburton Railway|website=Victorian Heritage Council|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, in preparation for the occasion of a royal visit by the [[Duke of York]], the first Australian [[royal train]] was assembled in Melbourne.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1900-1949|title=Victorian Railway Histories 1900 - 1949|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hurstbridge railway line|Heidelberg line]] was extended to [[Eltham railway station, Melbourne|Eltham]] in 1902 and [[Hurstbridge railway station|Hurstbridge]] in 1912. The freight only [[Mont Park railway line|Mont Park line]] was also opened in 1911, branching from [[Macleod railway station|Macleod]]. Finally on the [[Mornington Peninsula]], a branch was built from [[Bittern railway station|Bittern]] to [[Red Hill railway line|Red Hill]] in 1921.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Electrification ===\n[[File:DDE750.jpg|thumb|First set of [[Tait (train)|Tait]] suburban passenger carriages hauled by steam locomotive [[Victorian Railways Dd class|Dde 750]], 1913]]\n[[File:Springvalecemeterystation.jpg|thumb|Four car Tait train at the [[Spring Vale Cemetery railway station|Spring Vale Cemetery]] platform]]\n\nPlanning for electrification was started by [[Victorian Railways]] chairman [[Thomas James Tait]], who engaged [[United Kingdom|English]] engineer [[Charles Hesterman Merz]] to deliver a report on the electrification of the Melbourne suburban network. His first report in 1908 recommended a three-stage plan over 2 years, covering 200 route km of existing lines and almost 500 suburban carriages (approximately 80 trains).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-489878788|title=Report upon the Application of electric traction to the Melbourne suburban railway system|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The report was considered by the Government and the Railway Commissioners, and Merz was engaged to deliver a second report based on their feedback.\n\nDelivered in 1912, this second report recommended an expanded system of electrification to 240 route km. of existing lines (463 track km), and almost 800 suburban carriages (approximately 130 trains).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ehive.com/collections/6420/objects/778129/report-of-mr-thos-tait-as-to-his-inquiries-in-connexion-with-electrification-of-melbourne-suburban-|title=Report of Mr. Thos. Tait as to his inquiries in connexion with electrification o... on eHive|website=eHive|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The works were approved by the State Government in December 1912.<ref name=\":4\" /> It was envisaged that the first electric trains would be running by 1915, and the project would be completed by 1917. However, progress fell behind because [[World War I]] restrictions prevented electrical equipment being imported from the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=505&gall=693|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains (Newport Power Station)|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nRolling stock construction continued, with a number of older suburban carriages converted for electric use as the [[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]] trains, while the first of the [[Tait (train)|Tait]] trains were introduced as steam hauled carriages. Track expansion was also carried out, with four tracks being provided between South Yarra and Caulfield, as well as grade separation from roads. Victorian Railways in 1918 opened the [[Newport Power Station, Victoria|Newport power station]], the largest power station in the urban area, to supply electricity as part of the electrification project.<ref name=Newport>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/big-expansion-planned-for-newport/2006/11/12/1163266412333.html|title=Big expansion planned for Newport|publisher=Fairfax Digital, The Age|accessdate=2008-10-05 | location=Melbourne | date=13 November 2006}}</ref> The [[State Electricity Commission of Victoria]] was formed in 1921 but did not take over Newport A power station until 1951.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe first trials did not occur until October 1918 on the [[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse line]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=2&IRN=502|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Driver training continued on this line until 18 May 1919, when the first electric train ran between [[Sandringham railway line|Sandringham]] and [[Craigieburn railway line|Essendon]], simulating revenue services. Electric services started on 28 May 1919 with the first train running to Essendon, then on to Sandringham, with full services started the next day.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Glen Waverley railway line|Burnley\u2013Darling line]], the [[Upfield railway line|Fawkner line]], the reopened branch to Altona, and the [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown line]] followed in 1920.\n\nThe line to Broadmeadows, the [[Mernda railway line|Whittlesea line]] to [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], the [[Sunbury railway line|Bendigo line]] to [[St Albans railway station, Melbourne|St Albans]], and the inner sections of the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]] were electrified in 1921. The [[Pakenham railway line|Gippsland line]] to [[Dandenong railway station|Dandenong]] and Frankston line were electrified in 1922, as was the inner section of the [[Lilydale railway line|Ringwood line]] due to regrading works.\n\nThe original electrification scheme was completed in 1923,<ref name=\":6\" /> but over the next three years a number of short extensions were carried out. The Ashburton line was electrified in 1924, final works on the Lilydale line were completed in 1925, as was electrification on the line to [[Upper Ferntree Gully railway station|Upper Ferntree Gully]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/alamein|title=VICSIG Alamein Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/lilydale|title=VICSIG Lilydale Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/location/Upper-Ferntree-Gully|title=VICSIG Upper Ferntree Gully Station|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Electrification on the outer ends of the Hurstbridge line were completed by 1926, the [[Mernda railway line|Whittlesea line]] to [[Thomastown railway station, Melbourne|Thomastown]] was electrified in 1929, and the Burnley - Darling line was extended to [[Glen Waverley railway station|Glen Waverley]] in 1930 to become the [[Glen Waverley railway line|Glen Waverley line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.vicnet.net.au/~whsvic/railways.htm|title=Waverley Historical Society - Railways and the Waverley Area|website=home.vicnet.net.au|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Post-War rebuilding===\n[[File:Harris795M.jpg|thumb|A retired [[Harris (train)|Harris]] train]]\nRailways experienced increased patronage into the 1940s, but railway improvements recommended in the [[Ashworth Improvement Plan]] were delayed until after [[World War II]].<ref name=lee185>{{cite book |author=Lee, Robert |title=The Railways of Victoria 1854-2004 |publisher=Melbourne University Publishing Ltd |year=2007 |isbn= 978-0-522-85134-2 |page=185}}</ref> It was not until 1950 that the [[Victorian Railways]] were able to put their [[Operation Phoenix (railway)|Operation Phoenix]] rebuilding plan into action.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1950-1974|title=Victorian Railways History 1950 - 1974|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=16 May 2018}}</ref> The delivery of the [[Harris (train)|Harris]] trains, the first steel suburban trains on the network, enabled the retirement of the oldest of the [[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]] trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=502&gall=671|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains (Blue 'Harris' Electric Trains)|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nRailway lines were extended during this period to encompass Melbourne's growing suburban footprint. The [[Alamein railway line|Ashburton line]] was extended along the old Outer Circle track formation to [[Alamein railway station|Alamein station]] in 1948.<ref name=\":7\" /> The Fawkner line to [[Upfield railway station|Upfield]] and the Reservoir line to [[Lalor railway station|Lalor]] were both electrified in 1959, the Epping line reaching [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] in 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/upfield|title=VICSIG Upfield Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> A great deal of track amplification was also undertaken, with a number of single line sections eliminated.<ref>[http://www.smartpassengers.org.au/policy3.html Policy: Track Amplifications (Duplication, Triplication etc)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091024011235/http://www.smartpassengers.org.au/policy3.html |date=24 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Upper Ferntree Gully to Belgrave section of the [[Narrow gauge lines of the Victorian Railways|Gembrook narrow gauge line]] was converted to [[Victorian broad gauge|broad gauge]] and electrified in 1962.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/belgrave|title=VICSIG Belgrave Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The remainder of the line was closed in 1954, but has been progressively reopened by the [[Puffing Billy Railway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://puffingbilly.com.au/en/about-puffing-billy/history-heritage/|title=History & Heritage|website=puffingbilly.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516175032/http://puffingbilly.com.au/en/about-puffing-billy/history-heritage/|archive-date=16 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham line]] was electrified in 1954 as part of the works being carried out on the [[Bairnsdale railway line|Gippsland line]], but suburban services to Pakenham did not start until 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/pakenham|title=VICSIG Pakenham Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring this rebuilding, a number of little used lines were closed on the edges of Melbourne. The Bittern to Red Hill line closed in 1953, the line between Epping and Whittlesea closed in 1959, and the Lilydale to [[Warburton railway station|Warburton]] line closed in 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Red-Hill|title=VICSIG Red Hill Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Whittlesea|title=VICSIG Whittlesea Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Warburton|title=VICSIG Warburton Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The final stages of the rebuilding stretched into the 1970s, with track amplification carried out to [[Footscray railway station|Footscray]], and [[Box Hill railway station, Melbourne|Box Hill]], and the first deliveries of the stainless steel [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=502&gall=672|title=Victorian Railways: Stainless Steel Hitachi Trains|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nDetailed planning for the [[Doncaster railway line|Doncaster line]] also commenced in this period, and by 1972 the route was decided upon. Despite rising costs, the state governments of the period continued to make assurances that the line would be built,<ref name=\"nr42\">{{cite magazine\n |date=February 1998\n | title = Whatever Happened to the Proposed Railway to Doncaster East\n | author = Stephen Cauchi\n |magazine= Newsrail\n | publisher = Australian Railway Historical Society (Victorian Division)\n | volume = 26\n | issue = 2\n | page =42\n }}</ref> but by 1984 land for the line had been sold.<ref name=\"nr42\" />\n\n=== Modernisation ===\n[[File:Melbourne Central Station 2.jpg|thumb|[[Melbourne Central railway station]] in the underground [[City Loop]]]]\n[[File:Comeng-galvin-site.jpg|thumb|[[Comeng (train)|Comeng]] train on the [[Werribee railway line|Werribee line]]]]\n\nBy the 1970s, Melbourne's railway network was run down, with the last major investment on the suburban tracks having taken place nearly fifty years earlier. Sixty-year-old [[Tait (train)|Tait trains]] (known colloquially as \"red rattlers\") were still in operation, and inner city congestion at [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]] led to peak hour delays.<ref name=\":8\" /> In February 1971, the Melbourne Underground Rail Loop Act was passed, establishing the [[Melbourne Underground Rail Loop Authority]] (MURLA) to build a connecting series of tunnels from the major stations along the north, south, east and west extremities of the Melbourne CBD.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/victorias-public-transport-network/history/city-loop-history/|title=City Loop history|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The project ran for over 14 years, opening progressively between 1981 and 1985. The loop was designed and constructed to improve the capacity of Flinders Street and Spencer Street stations to handle suburban trains and to offer easier connections for users.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOther major changes took place in 1976 when the government authority overseeing [[Victorian Railways]] became VicRail and was gradually restructured along corporate lines. Following the restructure, in 1980 the Victorian Transport Study, better known as the [[Lonie Report]], was delivered and called for financial rationalisation. The closure of the Port Melbourne, St. Kilda, Altona, Williamstown, Alamein and Sandringham lines was also recommended, along with their replacement with bus routes instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/45154|title=Parliament of Victoria - Report on Vicrail financial system : ordered by the Legislative Assembly to be printed|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> These recommendations and cuts were not enacted, however many uneconomical branch lines were closed throughout the rest of the state.<ref name=\":10\" /> The line between Lilydale and Healesville was closed in 1980, now used by the [[Yarra Valley Railway]] beyond Yarra Glen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Healesville|title=VICSIG Healesville Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The branch from [[Baxter railway station|Baxter]] to [[Mornington railway station|Mornington]] was closed in 1981, but the line south of [[Moorooduc railway station|Moorooduc]] is now operated by the [[Mornington Railway]] as a tourist route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Mornington|title=VICSIG Mornington Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metrol]] train control centre was opened in 1980 to coordinate trains throughout the network using computer software that remains in use today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/30yearold-railway-computers-take-a-byte-out-of-the-past-20131014-2vitp.html|title=30-year-old railway computers take a byte out of the past|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2013-10-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Public transport in Melbourne was also reorganised, with the [[Metropolitan Transit Authority (Victoria)|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] (MTA) formed in 1983 to coordinate all train, tram and bus services in the city to improve interoperability.<ref name=\":10\" /> With the electrification of the [[Werribee railway line|Werribee line]] in 1983, followed two years later by an extension of the Altona line to [[Laverton railway station, Melbourne|Laverton]], and the City Loop in full operation by 1985, the last major modernisation of Melbourne's train lines in the 20th century was complete.\n\nIsolated from the City Loop, the [[Port Melbourne railway line|Port Melbourne]] and [[St Kilda railway line|St Kilda]] lines were converted to [[standard gauge]] light rail in 1987 to accommodate tram routes 111 (now [[Melbourne tram route 109|route 109]]) and [[Melbourne tram route 96|96]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The route 96 remains one of the world's top 10 tram routes, and Melbourne's busiest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/national/tram-96-travels-tracks-to-glory/2008/03/07/1204780065938.html|title=Tram 96 travels tracks to glory - National - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/style/one-of-melbournes-busiest-trams-has-had-its-peak-hour-services-cut-jfc/|title=One of Melbourne's Busiest Trams Has Had Its Peak Hour Services Cut & JFC - Pedestrian TV|date=2017-04-06|work=Pedestrian TV|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Southern Cross Suburban.JPG|thumb|The modern [[Southern Cross railway station|Southern Cross station]]]]\n[[File:Roxburgh Park railway station, Melbourne.jpg|thumb|[[Roxburgh Park railway station|Roxburgh Park]] station, opened in 2007.]]\n\nThe early 1990s saw further changes, with the MTA reborn as the [[Public Transport Corporation]], trading as \"The Met\".\n\nState Governments of both sides of politics began to push for reform of the railway network, proposing conversion of the Upfield, Williamstown and Alamein lines to light rail.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} These proposals failed, with the Upfield line instead receiving a series of upgrades to replace labour-intensive manual signalling systems. [[Government of Australia|Federal government]] funding was made available for the electrification of the [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne line]], which was completed in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/1995-06-05/0087%22;src1=sm1|title=ParlInfo - GRIEVANCE DEBATE : Corinella|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Rationalisation of the [[Jolimont Yard|Jolimont rail yard]] commenced, enabling the creation and expansion of [[Melbourne Park]] in 1988 and 1996, and the future construction of [[Federation Square]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fedsquare.com/about/history-design|title=History + Design - Federation Square|website=fedsquare.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nUpon the [[Jeff Kennett|Kennett]] Government's election in 1992, a number of controversial reforms to the operation of the railway system were initiated, with guards being abolished from suburban trains and train drivers taking over the task of door operation. Stations were de-manned, and the [[Metcard]] ticketing system was introduced to phase out the old scratch ticketing system.<ref name=\":10\" /> Over this period more than $250 million of operating cost was stripped from the Melbourne network, as the government sought to reign in growing state debt of $32 Billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/publications/research-papers/download/36-research-papers/13691-2011-11dbpublictransportdevelopmentauthority|title=Parliament of Victoria - Transport Legislation Amendment (Public Transport Development Authority) Bill 2011|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/two-decades-on-jeff-kennetts-legacy-lingers-20121002-26xob.html|title=Two decades on, Jeff Kennett's legacy lingers|date=2012-10-02|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Privatisation===\nIn 1997 \"The Met\" was split into two operating units \u2014Hillside Trains and Bayside Trains, each to be franchised to a different private operator. Ownership of land and infrastructure for rail and tram services was transferred to a new Victorian Government agency, [[VicTrack]]. In addition, a statutory office was created in Government\u2014the [[Director of Public Transport]]\u2014with specific responsibility for entering into franchise agreements with public transport operators for the operation of rail and tram services throughout Victoria. By 1999 the [[Privatization|privatisation]] process was complete, with [[Connex Melbourne]] and [[M-Train|M>Train]] each operating half of the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptua.org.au/campaigns/govern/priv-1999/|title=The First Train-Tram Privatisation: 1999 \u2013 Public Transport Users Association (Victoria, Australia)|website=www.ptua.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> In 2003 the parent company of M>Train ([[National Express]]) withdrew from operating public transport in Victoria, and their half of the suburban network was passed to Connex as part of a renegotiated contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/12/16/1039656342711.html|title=Train, tram operator quits - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nThe franchising contracts contained provisions for the new operators to refurbish the Comeng trains, and to replace the older [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains. Connex purchased [[Alstom]] [[X'Trapolis 100|X'Trapolis]] sets, while M>Train chose [[Siemens (train)|Siemens Nexas]] units.<ref name=\"RGI 1 Apr 2002\">{{cite news |title=Hillside EMU shipped to Melbourne |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/hillside-emu-shipped-to-melbourne.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=Railway Gazette International |date=1 April 2002 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005, the State Government commissioned a A$25 million study into the feasibility of a [[Dandenong railway line triplication|third track for the Dandenong line]] to increase capacity for the rapidly growing suburban area. The cost of the triplication process was expected to be as high as A$1 billion, as project activities would have included the organization of corresponding bus services for the rail line, changes to stations and platforms along the line, and the improvement of the signalling system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/state-trains-running-decades-late/2005/10/23/1130006003305.html|title=State trains running decades late|author=Dan Silkstone|date=24 October 2005|newspaper=The Age|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref> This project was ultimately sidelined and not delivered by the Brumby Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/money-doubt-on-third-rail-track-to-dandenong-20070506-ge4tpu.html|title=Money doubt on third rail track to Dandenong|last=Cauchi|first=Stephen|date=2007-05-06|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Professor Paul Mees and a group of academics estimated that privatisation had cost taxpayers $1.2 billion more than if the system had remained both publicly owned and operated. With the franchise extensions in 2009, taxpayers were to pay an estimated $2.1 billion more by 2010.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/12bn-sting-in-the-rail/2006/04/08/1143916767672.html The Age, 4/8/2009]</ref> However, the [[Institute of Public Affairs]] released its own report into Melbourne's privatisation, which assessed it as a modest success and observed that a 37.6% increase in patronage on the metropolitan rail system had reversed years of patronage decline due to poor quality services.<ref name=\"Allsop 2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Allsop |first1=Richard |title=Victoria's public transport: assessing the results of privatisation |journal=IPA Backgrounder |date=April 2007 |volume=19 |issue=1 |url=https://ipa.org.au/wp-content/uploads/archive/ALLSOP_Transport.pdf |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> The Auditor General of Victoria also performed a comprehensive audit report into the franchises and found that \"the franchises represent reasonable value for money\".<ref>Franchising Melbourne's train and tram system (2005:11), The Auditor General of Victoria, {{cite web |url=http://download.audit.vic.gov.au/files/ptfranchising_report.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010154638/http://download.audit.vic.gov.au/files/ptfranchising_report.pdf |archivedate=10 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Ridership boom and Metro Trains Melbourne ===\n[[File:Melbourne Metropolitan Train Patronage 1998 to 2018.png|thumb|Metropolitan train patronage 1998-2018 based on official state government figures.|385x385px]]\nBeginning in the mid-2000s, a rapid increase in patronage of Melbourne's train network occurred. In the three-year period between [[Financial Year|financial year]] 2005 and 2008 rail patronage grew by 35 per cent. Trips grew from 148 million in 2004 to more than 200 million in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptua.org.au/myths/express.shtml|title=Common Urban Myths About Transport|date=2 January 2009|work=Public Transport Users Association|publisher=Public Transport Users Association Inc|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, [[Singapore]]'s [[SMRT Corporation|SMRT]] Transit and [[Hong Kong]]'s [[MTR Corporation Limited]] expressed interest in taking control of Melbourne's suburban rail network from Connex in November 2009, when their contract was to be reviewed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/private-companies-could-boost-rail-tram-expansion/2007/11/25/1195975867985.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Private companies could boost rail, tram expansion | date=26 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June 2009, Connex lost its bid to renew its contract with the Victorian Government. Hong Kong backed and owned [[MTR Corporation]] took over the Melbourne train network on 30 November 2009, operating as a locally themed consortium [[Metro Trains Melbourne]].<ref>Swinburne Institute for Social Research: [http://www.sisr.net/publications/0604transport.pdf Putting the Public Interest back into Public Transport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013092605/http://www.sisr.net/publications/0604transport.pdf |date=13 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/new-train-tram-operators-for-melbourne-20090625-cxgx.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=New train, tram operators for Melbourne | first=Mex | last=Cooper | date=25 June 2009}}</ref> MTR is a non-public railway owner and operator in Hong Kong where it is well known for constructing Transit Oriented Developments (TODS) above and around its stations. Metro began operation on 1 December 2009, promising to draw on its international experience to improve Melbourne's rail operations.<ref name=\"Age 25 Jun 2009\">{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Mex |title=New train, tram operators for Melbourne |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/new-train-tram-operators-for-melbourne-20090625-cxgx.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=25 June 2009 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 30 Nov 2009\">{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Clay |title=Metro plans to stand and deliver |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/metro-plans-to-stand-and-deliver-20091130-k18k.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=30 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nTransport Minister [[Lynne Kosky]] stated that the Government's A$10.5 billion, 10-year major transport plan, announced in May 2006, had significantly underestimated the usage rates of public transport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gridlock choking life out of city|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/gridlock-choking-life-out-of-city/2007/05/26/1179601737298.html|accessdate=7 June 2013|newspaper=The Age|date=27 May 2007|author=Jason Dowling}}</ref> Original assessments had forecast increases of around 3-4%, far short of the 10% seen year-on-year. The State Government responded by purchasing new trains and introduced a new ticketing option that enabled commuters to pay a reduced fare if their journey finished by 7am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/off-peak-fares-to-cut-crush/news-story/f5271a08b1f22ba72526b73b830a203a|title=Off-peak fares to cut crush|date=2007-09-03|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the Brumby Government announced a $14.1 billion [[Victorian Transport Plan]] to augment Melbourne\u2019s rail network. The plan included:\n\n* The [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]], costing more than $4.5 billion, and consisting of an underground train network \u2014the first new underground rail line since the construction of the [[City Loop]] 25 years earlier\u2014 from Dynon to South Yarra. Aimed at \"relieving overcrowding on the busy suburban lines from Melbourne\u2019s west,\" the underground line was also designed to provide direct rail access to Melbourne University, the Women's Hospital and the Royal Children's Hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/airport-link-15-years-off-in-30b-public-transport-plan-20130327-2guqi.html|title=Airport link 15 years off in $30b public transport plan|author=Richard Willingham|date=28 March 2013|newspaper=The Age|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/under-city-rail-plan-to-cut-melbourne-congestion/story-e6frf7jo-1225770794938|title=Under-city rail plan to cut Melbourne congestion|author=Stephen McMahon|date=9 September 2009|newspaper=The Herald Sun|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref> \n* Rolling stock, $2.65 billion for up to 70 new trains, including 32 \"new generation\" trains which will carry 30 per cent more passengers\n* Rail extensions to Cranbourne East and Mernda, and electrification to Melton.\n* Improvements to train operations, at a cost of $200 million\n* Upgrades to metro stations, costing $50 million, and new stations in growth areas at a cost of $220 million\n* A Park & Ride expansion package costing $60 million.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090516031624/http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/minister-for-public-transport/$14.1-billion-investment-to-move-melbourne-to-a-modern-metro-network.html $14.1 b investment plan]</ref>\n*The previously reduced Early Bird ticket was also made free as part of these changes, following a trial on the Frankston and Sydenham lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/national/free-travel-for-earlybirds/2008/03/07/1204780012433.html|title=Early risers travel free on Melbourne's trains - National - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the investment announcement, the plan for the introduction of more than 200 new weekly train services was released to tackle overcrowding on the city's busiest train lines, a problem that had been attributed to a lack of trains and falling reliability.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/train-jam-relief-plan/2008/04/09/1207420443573.html More trains in railway overhaul], [[The Age]], 9 April 2008</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2009 the State Government announced that they had committed $562.3 million in the 2009 State Budget for the extension of the [[Mernda railway line|Epping line]] 3.5 kilometres north to South Morang. Construction started in 2010 and was completed in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.theage.com.au/breaking-news-national/vic-govt-commits-562m-to-rail-extension-20090501-apt1.html|title=Vic govt commits $562m to rail extension|date=1 May 2009|work=The Age|accessdate=1 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Network development and level crossing removals ===\nIn May 2011, operations commenced on a new metropolitan timetable, rewritten for the first time since 1996 with over 600 additional weekday services added.<ref name=\"Age 19 Jan 2011\">{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Clay |last2=Millar |first2=Royce |title='Confusing' timetable will cut services to west |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/confusing-timetable-will-cut-services-to-west-20110119-19woz.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=19 January 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC 9 May 2011\">{{cite news |title=Train timetable changes 'biggest in a decade' |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-05-09/train-timetable-changes-biggest-in-a-decade/2705216 |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=9 May 2011 |language=en-AU}}</ref> In 2012, a Public Transport Development Authority trading as [[Public Transport Victoria]] (PTV) was established to coordinate, plan and regulate the state's public transport services, including the metropolitan rail system.<ref name=\"Age 29 Nov 2012\">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Adam |title=Government public transport group is secretive and compromised, says lobby president |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/government-public-transport-group-is-secretive-and-compromised-says-lobby-president-20121129-2ahdr.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=29 November 2012 |language=en}}</ref> In the same year, the [[Metcard]] ticketing system was discontinued, completing the controversial network-wide roll-out of the new [[Myki|Myki smart card]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/the-end-is-nigh-for-metcard-20120119-1q8f4.html|title=The end is nigh for Metcard|last=Lucas|first=Clay|date=2012-01-19|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> On 27 March 2013, Public Transport Victoria published its [[Network Development Plan Metropolitan Rail]], detailing a 4-stage plan spread over 20 years to redevelop Melbourne's rail system into a 'metro-style' network, by separating train lines and creating point-to-point lines, upgrading to high-capacity signalling and ordering new trains.<ref name=\"Age 26 Mar 2013\">{{cite news |last1=Gough |first1=Deborah |title=Major rail projects expected in 20 years |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/major-rail-projects-expected-in-20-years-20130327-2gt8r.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=26 March 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:New Noble Park railway station February 2018.jpg|alt=New Noble Park station, 2018|thumb|The new elevated [[Noble Park railway station]], rebuilt in 2018 along with four other stations on the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] railway lines by the Level Crossing Removal Project. The plan removed nine level crossing on the corridor using elevated rail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/first-trains-run-on-melbourne-s-sky-rail-20180211-p4yzyn.html|title=First trains run on Melbourne's sky rail|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2018-02-11|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>]]\nA key campaign promise of the [[First Andrews Ministry|Andrews government]] prior to [[2014 Victorian state election|its election in 2014]] was to remove 50 [[level crossing]]s in 8 years, the most intensive such program in Melbourne's history.<ref name=\"Woodcock and Stone 2016 p13\">{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=Ian |last2=Stone |first2=John |title=The benefits of level crossing removals: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience |date=2016 |isbn=9780734052049 |page=13 |url=http://mams.rmit.edu.au/51zakugpfi4ez.pdf |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Because of Melbourne's generally level topography, the suburban rail network was constructed with a large number of level crossings. By 2014, over 170 remained, due to a lack of funding for grade separations after 1918.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woodcock|first=Ian|last2=Stone|first2=John|date=2016|title=The Benefits of Level Crossing Removal: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience|url=https://researchbank.rmit.edu.au/view/rmit:43926|journal=University of Melbourne/RMIT University|pages=13|via=RMIT Researchgate}}</ref> The Government's [[Level Crossing Removal Project]] became a resounding political success, despite concerns it was creating poor value-for-money infrastructure and controversy about the selection of elevated rail as a method for removing some crossings.<ref name=\"ABC 14 Dec 2017\">{{cite news |last1=Willingham |first1=state political reporter Richard |title=Dangerous level crossings being missed in Victoria, watchdog says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-14/level-crossings-selected-for-removal-in-victoria-questioned/9258178 |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=14 December 2017 |language=en-AU}}</ref> By 2018, 29 level crossings had been fully grade separated, well ahead of the government's original schedule, and a further 25 crossings were added to the program to be completed by 2025.<ref name=\"Age 21 October 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Butt |first1=Craig |last2=Towell |first2=Noel |title=Another 25 rail level crossings to go under Labor pledge |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/25-more-rail-level-crossings-to-go-under-labor-pledge-20181021-p50b07.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=21 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The project includes rebuilding or upgrading 27 train stations, such as [[Bentleigh railway station|Bentleigh]] and [[Clayton railway station, Melbourne|Clayton]] railway stations, or laying new track, such as the duplication of 1.2&nbsp;km of single track railway between [[Heidelberg railway station|Heidelberg]] and the rebuilt [[Rosanna railway station|Rosanna]] stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/about|title=About {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Project|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/projects/hurstbridge-rail-line-upgrade|title=Hurstbridge rail line upgrade {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Project|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> Large sections of elevated rail have been built on the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] lines, and further sections are planned for the [[Mernda railway line|Mernda]] and [[Upfield railway line|Upfield]] lines, including a 4&nbsp;km section on the Mernda line in [[Preston, Victoria|Preston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-21/new-melbourne-level-crossing-removals-to-include-sky-rail/10401896|title=Andrews pledges 25 new level crossing removals in Melbourne|last=Longbottom|first=Jessica|date=2018-10-21|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n[[File:Playground under elevated rail at Mernda, Melbourne August 2018.jpg|alt=Elevated rail at Mernda|thumb|323x323px|New elevated rail lines at [[Mernda]] in Melbourne's north, part of an 8&nbsp;km rail extension that opened in August 2018.]]\nThe [[Regional Rail Link]] project, which created a new [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line]] in the city's west with new stations at [[Wyndham Vale railway station|Wyndham Vale]] and [[Tarneit railway station|Tarneit]], as well as adding an additional track pair between [[Sunshine railway station, Melbourne|Sunshine]] and Southern Cross, was completed in mid-2015. Although the project was intended to provide segregated routes for regional trains to Geelong, Ballarat and Bendigo, rapid population growth in areas served by the new line forced these services to perform the role of an outer suburban network, causing significant delays and overcrowding.<ref name=\"Age 10 May 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=Regional Rail Link 'fails' to deliver on extra train services, watchdog says |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/regional-rail-link-fails-to-deliver-all-extra-train-services-promised-watchdog-says-20180510-p4zehc.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=10 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA redesigned network map was released by PTV at the end of 2016, which replaced an emphasis on fare zones with delineation of individual lines and service patterns. The new map also incorporated regional services and was designed to be accessible to passengers with the most common types of [[Color blindness|colour blindness]].<ref name=\"Age 28 Dec 2016\">{{cite news |last1=Dow |first1=Aisha |title=Rainbow revamp for Melbourne's train network map |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/rainbow-revamp-for-melbournes-train-network-map-20161228-gtizab.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=28 December 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMetro's contract to operate the suburban network was renewed in 2017 for a further 7 years. The renegotiated contracts included higher monthly performance targets, which it failed to meet 6 times in the first year of the contract's operation.<ref name=\"ABC 12 Sep 2017\">{{cite news |last1=Willingham |first1=Richard |title=Metro Trains and Yarra Trams win new $7b contracts with tougher targets |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-12/metro-contract-extended-for-melbournes-train-network/8895462 |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=12 September 2017 |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 3 Jan 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=Metro Trains, Yarra Trams awarded millions in bonuses despite late services |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/metro-trains-yarra-trams-awarded-millions-in-bonuses-despite-late-services-20190103-p50pd7.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=3 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of an extension of the South Morang line to [[Mernda]] commenced in 2016 and was completed on 29 August 2018. The project included 8&nbsp;km of new electrified railway, new stations at [[Middle Gorge railway station|Middle Gorge]] and [[Hawkstowe railway station|Hawkstowe]], and a new terminus at a rebuilt [[Mernda railway station|Mernda station]].<ref name=\"Age 1 Apr 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Matilda |title=Mernda train line ahead of schedule |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/mernda-train-line-ahead-of-schedule-20180401-p4z7by.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=1 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 19 Aug 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Webb |first1=Carolyn |title=We did it! Locals board first trains to Mernda in 59 years |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/we-did-it-locals-board-first-trains-to-mernda-in-59-years-20180819-p4zyfb.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=19 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 the Victorian Government announced that Public Transport Victoria would be merged along with [[VicRoads]] into a new Victorian [[Department of Transport (Victoria, 2019\u2013)|Department of Transport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/big-merger-vicroads-and-ptv-to-become-one-mega-agency-20190404-p51arj.html|title=Big merger: VicRoads and PTV to become one mega-agency|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2019-04-04|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Future expansion ==\n[[File:Melbrail former present proposed.svg|320px|thumb|right|Diagram showing Melbourne's passenger rail network, including former and planned lines.]]\n\n=== Metro Tunnel ===\n{{main|Metro Tunnel}}\nIn February 2015, the State Government established the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Authority]] to oversee planning for new twin 9-kilometre rail tunnels through the central city between [[South Kensington railway station|South Kensington station]] and [[South Yarra, Victoria|South Yarra]]. The new Metro Tunnel will have five new underground stations and connect the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] lines with the [[Sunbury railway line|Sunbury]] line, creating a new route through the CBD as an alternative to the [[City Loop]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/faq#|title=Frequently asked questions|website=metrotunnel.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> New underground stations will be created at [[Arden railway station, Melbourne|Arden]], [[Parkville railway station|Parkville]], [[Anzac railway station|Domain]] and two new CBD stations, [[State Library railway station|State Library]] and [[Town Hall railway station, Melbourne|Town Hall]]. Enabling works were underway by 2016 and major construction work on the tunnel and stations began in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/cbd-roads-to-be-closed-for-years-as-melbourne-metro-tunnel-construction-begins-20170116-gts2cp.html|title=CBD roads to be closed for years as Melbourne Metro Tunnel construction begins|last=Lucas|first=Aisha Dow, Clay|date=2017-01-16|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> The project has an estimated cost of $11 billion and is scheduled to be complete by 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-metro-a-year-ahead-of-schedule-premier-says-20180221-p4z12d.html|title=Melbourne Metro a year ahead of schedule, Premier says|last=Jacks|first=Timna|date=2018-02-20|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, the State Government ordered 65 new [[High Capacity Metro Trains]] for delivery from mid-2019, which will eventually become the primary rolling stock used in the Metro Tunnel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/new-2-billion-train-deal-to-create-1000-local-jobs-20160912-gre0wj.html|title=New $2 billion train deal to create 1000 local jobs|last=Willingham|first=Richard|date=2016-09-12|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn April, June and July 2019, multiple rail lines in Melbourne's east were shut down for several weeks to allow construction of the tunnel entrances near Kensington and South Yarra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/commuters-warned-of-may-misery-with-replacement-buses-ready-to-roll-20190430-p51iie.html|title=Commuters warned of May misery with replacement buses ready to roll|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2019-04-30|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/more-transport-misery-to-hit-melbourne-commuters-in-july-and-august-20190705-p524fo.html|title=More transport misery to hit Melbourne commuters in July and August|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2019-07-05|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The first tunnel boring machine began to be assembled in North Melbourne in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/massive-metro-tunnel-boring-machines-coming-together/|title=Massive Metro Tunnel Boring Machines Coming Together|date=2019-06-05|website=Premier of Victoria|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Tunnel boring machine|TBM]] Joan completed the first section of the tunnel from Arden to Kensington,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/news/our-first-tunnel-boring-machine-breakthrough|title=Our first tunnel boring machine breakthrough|date=2020-02-23|website=Metro Tunnel Official|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> travelling 1.2 kilometres and installing 4,200 curved concrete segments to create 700 rings lining the walls of the tunnel. Two months later, [[Tunnel boring machine|TBM]] Meg completed the accompanying tunnel, from Arden to Kensington.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/news/our-first-tunnel-boring-machine-breakthrough|title=First section of tunnel completed|date=2020-04-14|website=Metro Tunnel Official|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Airport rail link ===\n{{main|Melbourne Airport rail link}}\nA rail link to [[Melbourne Airport]] has been proposed repeatedly since the airport's construction, with a variety of routes and service models suggested, but construction has never commenced. In July 2018 the Federal and State Governments each pledged A$5 billion (for a total of A$10 billion) to construct a rail link. The Federal Government proposed four preferred routes for the link, with one proposal running via a direct tunnel to [[Highpoint Shopping Centre]] and the others linking to existing stations in Broadmeadows, Flemington or Sunshine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-11/melbourne-airport-rail-link-gets-$5bn-from-federal-government/9643054|title=Turnbull announces $5b funding for Melbourne Airport-CBD rail link|date=2018-04-11|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref> An assessment of the four preferred routes conducted by [[Rail Projects Victoria]] culminated in the route via Sunshine station being selected, with a detailed business case expected by 2020. Construction is expected to start prior to the [[2022 Victorian state election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-22/melbourne-airport-rail-construction-set-to-start-by-2022/10022642|title=Melbourne Airport rail construction set to start by 2022|date=2018-07-22|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n=== Suburban Rail Loop ===\n{{main|Suburban Rail Loop}}\nIn August 2018, in the run-up to the [[2018 Victorian state election]], the State Government pledged $300 million to complete a business case and secure funding to construct a new railway through suburban Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/aug/28/massive-melbourne-suburban-train-loop-pledged-by-victorian-government|title=Massive Melbourne suburban train loop pledged by Victorian government|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|date=2018-08-28|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref> The project is designed to link major activity centres and amenities such as hospitals, shopping centres, universities, and Melbourne Airport. The proposal would connect most existing railway lines through middle suburbs and enable easier intra-suburban travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-28/melbourne-suburban-train-loop-promised-by-labor/10172184|title=Melbourne's $50b rail loop the 'biggest public transport project in history'|date=2018-08-28|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nThe Suburban Rail Loop (SRL) would connect the existing station at [[Cheltenham railway station, Melbourne|Cheltenham]] with other existing stations at [[Clayton railway station, Melbourne|Clayton]], [[Glen Waverley railway station|Glen Waverley]], Box Hill, Heidelberg, [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], Fawkner, Broadmeadows, Sunshine and Werribee. It will also link to new stations to be built in areas that have long been promised rail connections, including [[Monash University, Clayton campus|Monash University]], Burwood, Doncaster, Bundoora and Melbourne Airport. Construction is scheduled to begin on the first stage from Cheltenham to Box Hill by 2022 with other sections progressively opening until the full line is operational by 2050.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-what-readers-think-20180828-p5006z.html|title=Melbourne suburban rail loop: What readers think|last=Koob|first=Simone Fox|date=2018-08-28|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-29/victorian-rail-suburban-loop-plan-divides-experts/10179340|title='A mega project on steroids': Experts divided on Melbourne rail loop plan|date=2018-08-29|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n=== Other planned extensions ===\n{{Main|Proposed Melbourne rail extensions}}\nThe State Government is currently preparing a business case for electrification and extension of the [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] to [[Baxter railway station|Baxter]] in Melbourne's South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://transport.vic.gov.au:443/getting-around/public-transport/baxter-electrification-business-case|title=Baxter electrification business case|last=Department of Economic Development|first=Jobs|website=transport.vic.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> The Federal Government committed $225 million towards the project in its 2017-2018 budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/guy-turnbull-all-aboard-the-450-million-baxter-rail-link-20180716-p4zrsw.html|title=Guy, Turnbull all aboard the $450 million Baxter rail link|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2018-07-16|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018 Victorian state election, the State Government also announced its Western Rail Plan, which would quadruplicate and electrify the rail lines to [[Melton railway station, Melbourne|Melton]] and [[Wyndham Vale railway station|Wyndham Vale]], allowing Metro services.<ref name=\"Build\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/western-rail-plan|title=Western Rail Plan|last=Build|first=Victoria's Big|date=2018-11-01|website=bigbuild.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> Under this plan, Metro and [[V/Line|V/Line regional services]] would be separated, allowing for higher speed trains to be introduced to [[Geelong V/Line rail service|Geelong]] and [[Ballarat V/Line rail service|Ballarat]]. A new connection between Sunshine and Southern Cross Station to be built as part of the Airport rail link could add extra capacity for regional and metro lines.<ref name=\"Build\"/> According to the Government, these lines could be fully electrified to Geelong and Ballarat and run at speeds of up to 250&nbsp;km/h, significantly above the 160&nbsp;km/h limit of current [[V/Line VLocity|V/Line VLocity trains]].<ref name=\"Jacks\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/geelong-to-melbourne-in-45-minutes-under-labor-s-regional-rail-plan-20181016-p509uu.html|title=Geelong to Melbourne in 45 minutes under Labor's regional rail plan|last=Jacks|first=Timna|date=2018-10-15|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> Planning for the fast rail and electrification of the lines to Melton and Wyndham Vale will occur alongside planning for the Airport rail link, with construction set to start by 2022.<ref name=\"Jacks\"/>\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n\n=== Railway ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; clear: right; width: 400px\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Route length of Melbourne rail network in km (2012)<ref name=\"BITRE urban rail\">{{cite book |title=Understanding Australia's urban railways |date=2012 |publisher=Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics |location=Canberra |page=4 |url=https://bitre.gov.au/publications/2012/files/report_131.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019 |ref={{sfnref|BITRE|2012}}}}</ref>\n|-\n| Passenger only\n| 234\n|-\n| Freight only\n| 66\n|-\n| Shared passenger and freight\n| 196\n|-\n|\n|\n|-\n| Electrified\n| 359\n|-\n| Not electrified\n| 137\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Total\n| 496\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<!-- Don't attempt to combine these figures; that would be original research. --> {{small|Since 2012, the [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line|Deer Park\u2013West Werribee line]] (27 km) has opened to traffic and the former South Morang line has been extended to [[Mernda railway station]] (8 km).<ref name=\"Trainline 6\">{{cite book |title=Trainline 6 |date=2018 |publisher=Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics |page=125 |url=https://bitre.gov.au/publications/2018/files/train_006.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n|}\nThe rail network within the Melbourne metropolitan area includes dedicated passenger lines, dedicated freight lines, and lines shared by the two types of traffic. Nearly all passenger traffic and some intrastate freight operates on {{track gauge|victorian|allk=on}}, while all interstate and much intrastate freight traffic operates on {{track gauge|sg|allk=on}}. As a consequence, freight and passenger operations are almost completely segregated in the metropolitan area.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=34}}\n\nMost suburban passenger lines operated by the metropolitan rail franchisee, currently [[Metro Trains Melbourne]], are [[Electrification (rail)|electrified]] with 1500 [[volt|V]] [[direct current|DC]] [[overhead catenary]]. Many of the suburban lines share tracks with regional passenger trains operated by [[V/Line]], and some V/Line services provide \"peri-urban\" service to areas of Melbourne not reached by the electrified network.<ref name=\"VAGO 2017\">{{cite book |title=V/Line Passenger Services |date=August 2017 |publisher=Victorian Auditor-General's Office |location=Melbourne |page=37 |url=https://www.audit.vic.gov.au/sites/default/files/2017-08/20170809-VLine-Passenger-Services.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Metro also operates an isolated section of unelectrified passenger line between [[Frankston railway station|Frankston]] and [[Stony Point railway station|Stony Point]].{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=36}}\n\nThe network is centred on Flinders Street and Southern Cross stations in the CBD, which are joined directly by a six-track viaduct and indirectly by the underground four-track [[City Loop]]. From this central core, nearly all tracks pass through the three major junction stations of [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]], [[Jolimont railway station|Jolimont]], and [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Richmond]]; and from there extend outwards to the west, north-east and east of the city respectively. There are few connections between the radial lines outside of the central city.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=35}} Capital investment in the network since 1990 has focused on relieving \"bottlenecks\" near the central core caused by the large number of lines converging, most significantly with the [[Regional Rail Link]] project which provided additional capacity between [[Sunshine railway station, Melbourne|Sunshine]] and the city.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|pp=36\u201337}}\n\n[[File:Melbourne-signalling-stanchions.jpg|thumb|Quadruple track near [[Caulfield railway station|Caulfield station]], showing [[railway signalling|signalling]] and [[overhead lines#Overhead catenary|overhead wiring]]]]\nMuch of the metropolitan network is [[Double-track railway|double track]] or multiple pairs of tracks. There are small sections of [[Triple-track railway|triple track]], which are used to allow express trains to overtake stopping trains in peak hour. Nearly the entirety of the [[Altona railway line, Melbourne|Altona]], [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] and Stony Point branches are single track, and many of the outer suburban passenger lines also have sections of single track, usually where demand for frequent services is low.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=36}}\n\nThe metropolitan network has a large number of [[level crossings]]. Many have been gradually removed by [[grade separation|grade separating]] road and rail traffic: by 2016, some 228 grade separations had been undertaken in the Melbourne area, leaving 170 level crossings, although very few projects of this nature had been undertaken in the latter half of the 20th century. The [[Level Crossing Removal Project]], which began in 2014, aimed to increase the rate of level crossing removals to over 6 each year for at least 8 years, and the project was later extended for a further four years.<ref name=\"Woodcock and Stone 2016\">{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=Ian |last2=Stone |first2=John |title=The benefits of level crossing removals: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience |date=2016 |page=13 |url=http://mams.rmit.edu.au/51zakugpfi4ez.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stations ===\n{{main|List of railway stations in Melbourne}}\nThere are 218 stations in Melbourne, operated by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]].\n\n==== Passenger information ====\n{{anchor|PRIDE}}\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Pridebox-Melbourne.jpg|PRIDE Talking Box panel at [[East Camberwell railway station|East Camberwell]] station\nFile:2 Line PID Boards Metlink.png|A diagram of a two-line LED {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}\nFile:CRT TV Information Metlink.png|A diagram of a CRT {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}} screen pair\nFile:PRIDE II Talking Box Next Trains Announcement at Ginifer.ogg|PRIDE II Talking Box, detailing departures from [[Ginifer railway station|Ginifer]] station\nFile:Network status board.jpg|A network status board at [[Highett railway station|Highett station]]\n</gallery>\n\nTimetable information is available to passengers at stations through the '''PRIDE II''' system, which is an [[Electronics|electronic]] [[Public transport timetable|timetable]] and announcement system, and stands for Passenger Real-time Information Dissemination Equipment. The system consists of:\n* The control system, situated at [[Metrol, Melbourne rail network|Metrol]].\n* Control stations, at which staff update information, and announcements and CCTV recordings are dealt with for nearby stations.\n* [[Public address]] systems at each station on the network. The PRIDE system automatically announces when a train is due soon, delayed, or cancelled; this is done via the rail telephone network.\n* PRIDE \"talking boxes\" installed on each platform of all stations.\n* Electronic information displays.\n\nControl data comes from two locations: Metrol, and control stations. Next train data and times are automatically updated by the train control systems, with manual overrides also possible.\n\nAll stations are provided with \"talking boxes\" which have two buttons and a small [[loudspeaker|speaker]].\nThe green button, when pressed, contacts the PRIDE controller over the rail telephone network, identifying itself by the [[dual-tone multi-frequency|DTMF]] tones that correspond to the ID number assigned to the box. The system then reads out times and destinations for the next two services to depart that platform (or, in the case of stations with a single island platform with departures either side, both platforms). The red button when pressed, gives the user two way communication with the closest control station.\n\nBusy stations are often provided with an electronic [[light-emitting diode|LED]] {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}s, which indicate the destination, time, stopping pattern summary, and minutes to departure for the next train on the platform.\n\nStations on the [[City Loop]], in addition to [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]], [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Richmond]], and [[Box Hill railway station, Melbourne|Box Hill]] stations, have [[cathode ray tube|CRT]] screen {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}s, although some of these have recently been replaced by [[widescreen]] [[liquid crystal display|LCD]] screens. These displays show in detail the destination, scheduled and actual departure time, and all stations the next train stops at. Also shown is the destination and time of the following train, and the system is capable of providing suggested connections and warn of service interruptions.\n\nOn Sunday, 26 September 2010, the PRIDE system was upgraded with new voice announcements. The voice is now female, and now advises to touch on and off when using Myki.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metro Trains go female|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tgr0STnslIA|work=Video|accessdate=28 September 2010}}{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the Bayside Rail Upgrade, stations on the [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] will receive new \"network status boards\". These LCD screens provide travel information on all of Melbournes 16 railway lines as well as tram & bus services, including delays, replacement services or planned disruptions.<ref>[http://ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/bayside-rail-project/network-status-boards/ Network Status Boards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915072650/http://ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/bayside-rail-project/network-status-boards/ |date=15 September 2014 }} Public Transport Victoria</ref>\n\n=== Safeworking ===\n[[File:Signal-and-train-stop-melbourne.jpg|thumb|A signal with associated train stop in the raised position to the right]]\n\nMost lines in Melbourne operate under an automatic block system of safeworking with three-position power signalling. This permits [[Railway signal|signals]] to operate automatically with the passage of trains, enforcing the distance between them. At junctions signals are manually controlled from [[signal box]]es, with [[interlocking]]s used to ensure conflicting paths are not set. The [[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse line]] has two-position automatic signalling, a variant of the three-position system.\n\nThe outer end of the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]] used to be operated with [[Token (railway signalling)|token based systems]] and two-position manual signalling, where access to the line is based upon possession of a token. It was dismantled in 2013.\n\n[[Train stop]]s are used to enforce stop indications on signals\u2014should a train pass a signal, the train's brakes will automatically be applied. Trains are also fitted with [[pilot valve]]s, a form of [[dead man's switch]] that applies the brakes should the driver fail to maintain a foot or hand pilot valve in a set position.<ref name=\"safe\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.doi.vic.gov.au/Doi/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/0C6245228F9F50A3CA2570AE0012723F?OpenDocument\n |title       = Rail system safety\n |work        = Department of Infrastructure website\n |accessdate  = 22 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090520043834/http://www.doi.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/0C6245228F9F50A3CA2570AE0012723F?OpenDocument\n |archivedate = 20 May 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The \"VICERS\" [[Dead-man's vigilance device|vigilance control]] and [[event recorder]] system is also being currently fitted to suburban trains to provide an additional level of safety.<ref name=\"safe\" />\n\n=== Train control ===\nThe main control room for the rail network is [[Metrol, Melbourne rail network|Metrol]]. Located in the Melbourne CBD, it controls [[railway signalling|signals]] in the inner suburbs, tracking the location of all trains, as well as the handling the distribution of real time passenger information, and manages disruptions to the timetable. Additional signal boxes are located throughout the network, and in direct communication with Metrol.\n\n===Terminology===\nThe railways in Melbourne generally use British-derived terminology. For example:\n* '''Up''' refers to the direction \"towards Melbourne\".\n* '''Down''' refers to the direction \"away from Melbourne\", or \"towards the country\".\n* '''Points''' refers to what are known as [[railroad switch]]es, or crossovers in American English.\n* '''Signal box''' refers to the signal control installation ('''tower''' in American terminology).\n* '''Gunzel''' termanology for a railway enthusiast\n\n==Suburban services==\n{{main|Metro Trains Melbourne}}\n\n{{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-lat=-37.8115\n|frame-long=144.9685\n|frame-width=800\n|frame-height=600\n|frame-align=center\n|text=Interactive map showing suburban lines of the Melbourne metropolitan rail network, including the under construction [[Metro Tunnel]] in grey.\n|zoom=12\n\n|type=line\n|id=Q4787948\n|stroke-colour=#7F7F7F\n|stroke-width=5\n|title=Metro Tunnel (under construction)\n\n|type2=line\n|id2=Q7567980\n|stroke-colour2=#E42B23\n|stroke-width2=5\n|title2=Mernda line\n\n|type3=line\n|id3=Q16927215\n|stroke-colour3=#E42B23\n|stroke-width3=5\n|title3=Hurstbridge line\n\n|type4=line\n|id4=Q6548623\n|stroke-colour4=#094B8D\n|stroke-width4=5\n|title4=Lilydale line\n\n|type5=line\n|id5=Q4705897\n|stroke-colour5=#094B8D\n|stroke-width5=5\n|title5=Alamein line\n\n|type6=line\n|id6=Q4882690\n|stroke-colour6=#094B8D\n|stroke-width6=5\n|title6=Belgrave line\n\n|type7=line\n|id7=Q5568092\n|stroke-colour7=#094B8D\n|stroke-width7=5\n|title7=Glen Waverley line\n\n|type8=line\n|id8=Q5492274\n|stroke-colour8=#149943\n|stroke-width8=5\n|title8=Frankston line\n\n|type9=line\n|id9=Q7125454\n|stroke-colour9=#16B4E8\n|stroke-width9=5\n|title9=Pakenham line\n\n|type10=line\n|id10=Q5181939\n|stroke-colour10=#16B4E8\n|stroke-width10=5\n|title10=Cranbourne line\n\n|type11=line\n|id11=Q7416840\n|stroke-colour11=#FC7EBB\n|stroke-width11=5\n|title11=Sandringham line\n\n|type12=line\n|id12=Q7983583\n|stroke-colour12=#149943\n|stroke-width12=5\n|title12=Werribee line\n\n|type13=line\n|id13=Q8021313\n|stroke-colour13=#149943\n|stroke-width13=5\n|title13=Williamstown line\n\n|type14=line\n|id14=Q7639008\n|stroke-colour14=#FFB531\n|stroke-width14=5\n|title14=Sunbury line\n\n|type15=line\n|id15=Q7898275\n|stroke-colour15=#FFB531\n|stroke-width15=5\n|title15=Upfield line\n\n|type16=line\n|id16=Q5181702\n|stroke-colour16=#FFB531\n|stroke-width16=5\n|title16=Craigieburn line\n\n}}\n\n===Operations===\nDespite initially being constructed and operated as private railways in the 1850s, following the establishment of the government-owned [[Victorian Railways]] in 1858 Melbourne's suburban railway system has been state operated for the majority of its existence. In the 1920s Victorian Railways was the operator of the world's busiest train station ([[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]]) and one of the world's busiest railway networks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4717137|title=WORLD'S BUSIEST STATION.|date=1922-01-11|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2018-04-28|pages=15}}</ref> Following several high-profile collisions in the early 20th century, a number of network safety processes were implemented by the operator to improve passenger safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=2&IRN=508|title=Victorian Railways, Museum Victoria, Australia|last=Victoria|first=Museum|website=museumsvictoria.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe agency name was shortened to [[Victorian Railways|VicRail]] in the early 1980s and then, later in the decade, the metropolitan system became known as Metropolitan Transit ('[[Metlink|The Met]]') and the regional system became known as V/Line. In preparation for privatisation the suburban system was split into Bayside Trains and Hillside Trains by the [[Kennett Ministry]] in 1997. Privatisation was completed in 1999 and [[M-Train]] and [[Connex Melbourne]] won the tender to operate Bayside, and Hillside trains, respectively. Following M>Train's inability to renegotiate financial arrangements, in 2004 Connex Melbourne assumed responsibility for the entire network. Current operations are provided by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]], an [[MTR Corporation]] joint venture.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/component/content/article/2-general/32-railway-history-in-victoria-1950-now|title=Victorian Railways History 1975 - 1999|date=2017|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Operator Timelines'''\n*'''1854\u20131860''' - Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company\n*'''1854\u20131878''' - Melbourne and Hobsons Bay Railway Company\n*'''1857\u20131862''' - Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company\n*'''1858\u20131983''' - [[Victorian Railways]] ('VicRail')\n*'''1983\u20131997''' - Metropolitan Transit ('The Met')\n*'''1997\u20131999''' - Bayside Trains (Caulfield and Northern groups) and Hillside Trains (Clifton Hill and Burnley groups, Showgrounds services)\n*'''1999\u20132004''' - [[M-Train|M>Train]] (formerly Bayside Trains) and [[Connex Melbourne]] (formerly Hillside Trains)\n*'''2004\u20132009''' - Connex Melbourne \n*'''2009\u2013present''' - [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]\n\n=== Fleet ===\n\n==== Current fleet ====\nThe majority of the current suburban train fleet in Melbourne is owned by [[VicTrack]], with the train operator (currently [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]) responsible for maintaining the fleet.<ref name=\"doiwho\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/B324F53A00F987B9CA2571F50007F1BB?OpenDocument|title=Department of Transport: Who's who in Victoria's public transport network|publisher=Department of Transport, State Government of Victoria, Australia|accessdate=14 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523081606/http://www.transport.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/B324F53A00F987B9CA2571F50007F1BB?OpenDocument|archive-date=23 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> All trains on the Melbourne suburban network are electric and driver-only operated. Guards on suburban trains were discontinued between 1993 and 1995.<ref name=\"vrhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/history.html|title=VR History|publisher=victorianrailways.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530050949/http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/history.html|archivedate=30 May 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nAll trains are fitted with power-operated sliding doors which are closed by the driver, but opened by passengers. The doors of newer model [[X'Trapolis 100]] and Siemens trains are opened electronically with a button, whilst Comeng trains are slid manually using handles. Trains are fitted with air conditioning, closed-circuit cameras, and emergency intercom systems. Trains are fixed into three car units and may operate alone or in pairs.  All three train types in operation are unable to operate coupled to another type.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vicsig.net/suburban/fleet|title=VICSIG|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref><gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Melboure Comeng 381M Metro.jpg|Comeng train\nFile:Siemens train in Metro Trains Melbourne Livery.jpg|Siemens train\nFile:Metro-liveried-XTrapolis-train-863M.jpg|X'Trapolis 100 train\n</gallery>\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n!Names\n!Alternate names\n!Entered service\n!Number built\n!Key information\n|-\n|[[Comeng (train)|Comeng]]\n|\n|1981-1988\n|95 (6 carriage)\n|Named as a 'Commonwealth Engineering' portmanteau. Refurbished 2000-2003 by [[EDI Rail]] and [[Alstom]]. Feature power operated doors that must be pulled open by hand but are closed automatically by the driver. First trains to feature air conditioning.\n|-\n|[[Siemens Nexas|Siemens]]\n|Siemens Nexas\n|2003-2006\n|72 (3 carriage)\n|Refurbished with seat removals and extra railings since 2016. The first and only openly articulated trains with passengers able to move between carriages without opening any doors. Frequent overrunning caused lawsuits and disruptions to fix alleged braking faults.\n|-\n|[[X'Trapolis 100|X'Trapolis]]\n|\n|2002-2004<br />2009\u2013present\n|180 (3 carriage)<br />+32 under construction\n|Body shells built in France, remaining assembled in Ballarat. Eight separate orders have been lodged for X'Trapolis trains. Remodelled since 2009 with 2+2 seat configurations to increase passenger capacity/flow.\n|-\n|[[High Capacity Metro Trains]]\n|\n|2019\n| +65 under construction\n|For use on Melbourne Metro Rail Project line. Built in [[Changchun]], [[China]] and Victoria using 60% local content. Currently in testing only, due to enter service mid-2020<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/new-2-billion-train-deal-to-create-1000-local-jobs-20160911-gre0wj.html|title=New $2 billion train deal to create 1000 local jobs|date=12 September 2016|newspaper=The Age}}</ref><ref>[http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/1100-jobs-with-65-new-trains-built-in-victoria-for-victoria/ 1,100 Jobs with 65 New Trains Built in Victoria, For Victoria] Premier of Victoria 12 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/evolution-rail-to-supply-melbourne-high-capacity-emus.html Evolution Rail to supply Melbourne high capacity EMUs] ''Railway Gazette International'' 12 September 2016</ref>\n|}\n\n==== Decommissioned fleet ====\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n!Name\n!Alternate names\n!Entered service\n!Retired service\n!Number built\n!Key information\n|-\n|[[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]]\n|Dog Box\n|1887\n|c.1959-1970\n|294\n|Named after the outward swinging carriage doors. Converted to electric traction from 1917.\n|-\n|[[Tait (train)|Tait]]\n|Reds, Red Rattlers\n|1910\n|1974-1984\n|623\n|Named after [[Thomas James Tait|Sir Thomas James Tait]], Chairman of Commissioners of the Victorian Railways. Converted to electric traction from 1919. Banned from the City Loop due to the fire hazard of wooden frames.\n|-\n|[[Harris (train)|Harris]]\n|Blues\n|1956\n|1988-1994\n|436\n|Named after [[Norman Charles Harris]], Chairman of Commissioners of the Victorian Railways. Most contained asbestos and were buried in Clayton in the 1980s; 16 were refurbished, of those 10 were included in the conversion of 59 vehicles to [[V/Line H type carriage|H type carriages]] for shorter distance country services. Four motors preserved; one each original and refurbished as static exhibits at Newport Railway Museum, and two pending restoration at Newport Workshops.\n|-\n|[[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]]\n|Martin & King, Stainless Steel\n|1972\n|2003-2014\n|118&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;3 carriage sets\n|Named due to the design by Hitachi, despite no Hitachi components. The last Melbourne trains not to have air conditioning. Three Hitachi motor carriages form part of the restaurant Easey's in Collingwood.\n|}\n\n==== Classification and configuration ====\n{{Update|date=February 2018|updated=June 2014}}\n<!-- NOTE: The heading of this section is linked to in articles about the different train types, so should not be changed without updating those links.  -->\n\nSince shortly after the introduction of suburban electric trains in Melbourne, their carriages have been classified as follows. All fleet types have used these classifications, with different fleet types using different number ranges for the carriages.\n\n*'''M''' indicates a motorised carriage, with a driving compartment.\n*'''T''' indicates a trailer carriage.\n*'''D''' indicated a trailer carriage with a driving compartment. Only Swing-door, Tait, and Hitachi trains had these.\n*'''G''' indicated a trailer carriage fitted with both gas and electric lighting, for use on country services. Only Tait trains had these.\n*'''BT''' indicated a second class trailer carriage. Prior to the abolition of first class suburban travel in 1958, motorised carriage were generally second class and trailer carriages were generally first class.\n\nAn exception to the above classifications was the [[4D (train)|trial double-deck]] train, which used '''T''' to indicate a trailer carriage with a driving compartment, and '''M''' to indicate a motorised carriage without a driving compartment.\n\nCurrently, all trains are assembled into a symmetrical '''M-T-M''' arrangement. Trains comprise either one or two such units. All peak period services and some off-peak services comprise two units. The now retired [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains operated in fixed two-unit sets.\n\n=== Lines ===\nMelbourne's suburban network includes 16 electrified lines and 1 non-electrified line.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many lines have been lengthened over time, most notably the [[Mernda railway line|Mernda line]] from [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] to [[South Morang railway station|South Morang]] in 2012 and again to [[Mernda railway station|Mernda]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/projects/mernda-rail-extension-project|title=Mernda rail extension project {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Authority|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Lines have also changed terminus or layout, including the forthcoming changes to the Cranbourne, Pakenham and Sunbury lines as part of the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/Works-to-transform-the-Cranbourne-Pakenham-corridor/|title=Works to transform the Cranbourne Pakenham corridor|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Numerous [[Proposed Melbourne rail extensions|proposals for new lines or extensions]] not yet constructed have been made, including the long-outstanding [[Doncaster railway line]] and [[Melbourne Airport rail link]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/apr/12/turnbull-puts-up-5bn-for-melbourne-airport-rail-link|title=Turnbull puts up $5bn for Melbourne airport rail link|last=Davey|first=Melissa|date=2018-04-12|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Electrified lines ====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Alamein railway line]]\n*[[Belgrave railway line]]\n*[[Craigieburn railway line]]\n*[[Cranbourne railway line]]\n*[[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse/Showgrounds railway line]]\n*[[Frankston railway line]]\n*[[Glen Waverley railway line]]\n*[[Hurstbridge railway line]]\n*[[Lilydale railway line]]\n*[[Mernda railway line]]\n*[[Pakenham railway line]]\n*[[Sandringham railway line]]\n*[[Sunbury railway line]]\n*[[Upfield railway line]]\n*[[Werribee railway line]]\n*[[Williamstown railway line]]\n*[[City Loop]] (incorporated into several other lines)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Non-electrified lines ====\n*[[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line]] (non-electrified train service operated by V/Line)\n*[[Melton railway line]] (non-electrified train service operated by V/Line)\n*[[Stony Point railway line]] (non-electrified train service beyond Frankston)\n\n===== Stony Point line and metropolitan V/Line services =====\n[[Stony Point railway line|Stony Point]] line services operate as shuttles from [[Frankston railway station|Frankston]] station with passengers to and from [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]] required to change trains. It is the only non-electrified line operated by Metro Trains, with services being operated using [[V/Line Sprinter|Sprinter]] diesel multiple units leased from [[V/Line]].\n\n[[Melton railway line|Melton (Ballarat line)]] and [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line|Wyndham Vale (Geelong line)]] services are operated by [[V/Line]] and depart from [[Southern Cross railway station|Southern Cross]], but are within the metropolitan ticketing zone. Bacchus Marsh/Melton/Ballarat trains stop at Rockbank, Caroline Springs, Deer Park and Ardeer. Wyndham Vale/Geelong trains also stop at Ardeer and Deer Park, along with Tarneit. Only Wyndham Vale and Ballarat trains stop at Ardeer, not Geelong trains.\n\n5 morning peak and 3 afternoon peak trains operate to and from Wyndham Vale. One weekday morning service and numerous football services operate to Wyndham Vale.\n\nFrequent peak hour trains operate to and from Bacchus Marsh and Melton. Since 2015, weekday hourly trains have also operated to Bacchus Marsh. On top of Ballarat trains stopping here, Bacchus Marsh residents have half hourly services to the city.\n\nOn weekdays, Geelong and Ballarat trains run express after Tarneit and Melton respectively, with Wyndham Vale, Bacchus Marsh and Melton trains stopping between Rockbank and Sunshine. On weekends, these stations are serviced by Ballarat trains.\n\nSunbury services used to also be operated by V/Line until 2012 when the electrical network was extended to Sunbury and these trains also stopped at Diggers Rest; Sunbury passengers can still catch V/Line trains to or from Bendigo. The redundant carriages were moved onto Bacchus Marsh services instead. V/Line trains used to also operate to Donnybrook, stopping at Craigieburn but since the electrical network was extended to Craigieburn in 2007, trains have stopped terminating at Donnybrook.\n\n=== Service patterns ===\n{{main|Metro Trains Melbourne#Service patterns}}\nSuburban services are operated by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]. Railway lines and service patterns are often classified into groups, which are:\n*Burnley group\n**[[Lilydale railway line|Lilydale]], [[Belgrave railway line|Belgrave]], [[Alamein railway line|Alamein]] and [[Glen Waverley railway line|Glen Waverley]] line (blue)\n*Caulfield group\n**[[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] line (light blue)\n**[[Sandringham railway line|Sandringham]] line (pink)\n*Clifton Hill group\n**[[Mernda railway line|Mernda]] and [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge]] line (red)\n*Northern group\n**[[Sunbury railway line|Sunbury]], [[Craigieburn railway line|Craigieburn]] and [[Upfield railway line|Upfield]] line (yellow)\n*Cross-City group\n**[[Frankston railway line|Frankston]], [[Werribee railway line|Werribee]] and [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown]] line (green)\n**[[Stony Point railway line|Stony Point]] line (non-electrified train service beyond Frankston)\n*Special event services\n**[[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse/Showgrounds]]\n\nMost of the above lines travel along the [[City Loop]], and as some trains change to service other lines at their terminus, others may run through the City Loop incidentally. The Frankston line does not travel along the City Loop on off-peak weekdays, but does so during the peak and weekends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/getting-around/maps/metropolitan-trains/view/6/|title=Metropolitan trains|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nMelbourne uses [[clock-face scheduling]] in off-peak periods, but generally not in [[rush hour]], due to the network operating near to infrastructure capacity and having to accommodate single-line sections, flat junctions, and regional diesel-hauled trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/metro-warns-of-capacity-crunch-within-two-years-on-some-train-lines-20170704-gx4giy.html|title=Metro warns of capacity crunch within two years on some train lines|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2017-07-04|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Frequencies vary according to time of day, day of week and by line. In some places, usually [[interchange station]]s, services on two lines combine to provide more frequent services on common sections of tracks. All services become 24-hour from Friday morning to Sunday evening, with at least one departure every hour after 12am.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlong with other Australian railways, Melbourne uses the British terminology of \"[[rail terminology#U|up]]\" and \"[[rail terminology#D|down]]\", with \"up\" being defined as toward Flinders Street station in the CBD.\n\n=== Fares and tickets ===\n{{main|myki}}\n\nThe [[myki]] [[smart card|smart-card]] ticketing system is the main ticketing system currently in use across Melbourne, introduced in 2010. Prior to December 2012 Melbourne also used a magnetic strip [[paper ticket]] system known as the [[Metcard]], first introduced to the railway network in 1996. On 29 December 2012 Metcard was no longer available for use on Melbourne's public transport and completely replaced by myki. Multi-modal tickets were first introduced in Melbourne in 1969 and prior to this train, tram and bus services all had separated ticketing systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/intro.htm|title=Melbourne's Multi-Modal Based Ticketing Systems 1969 to present|website=www.robx1.net|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Host stations and premium stations ===\nHost stations and premium stations are categories of railway stations on the suburban rail network. A premium station is staffed from first train to last, seven days a week, while a host station is staffed only during the morning peak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Melbourne Train Network |url=https://www.metrotrains.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/PTV_M_Train_Network-Map_A4P_JAN_2016_HR.pdf |publisher=Public Transport Victoria |accessdate=2019-12-01}}</ref> Of the 207 stations in [[Melbourne]]'s railway network, there are 82 premium stations, in addition to the five [[City Loop]] stations.\n\nAlthough plans for the premium station program were unveiled in 1991 (under the guise of 'Safe Stations'),<ref name=\"newsrailnov91\">{{cite magazine |date=November 1991 |title=General News |magazine=Newsrail |publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society |page=364}}</ref> the program was commenced in 1994 by the [[Public Transport Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/metcard/html/history.htm |title=Metcard - A brief history |publisher=robx1.net |accessdate=2008-03-27}}</ref> with [[Mount Waverley railway station|Mount Waverley]] being the first station given premium status.<ref name=\"Newsrail\">{{cite magazine |date=October 1997 |title=Upgrading Eltham to a Premium Station |magazine=Newsrail |publisher=Australian Railway Heritage Society (Victorian Division) |page=310}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mount Waverley |url=http://www.vicsig.net/index.php?page=infrastructure&name=Mount%20Waverley |work=VICSIG |accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref> By the end of 1995 the number of staffed stations increased from 35 to 51.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/metcard/html/premium.htm |title=Metcard - Premium stations |publisher=robx1.net |accessdate=2008-03-27}}</ref> It was proposed to upgrade further stations to premium status in the future.\n\nThe host station program was introduced by the [[Government of Victoria (Australia)|Victorian Department of Transport]] in the early 2000s to ensure that over 80% of suburban rail passengers started their journey from a staffed (host or premium) station.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Regional services==\n{{Main|V/Line}}\n[[V/Line]] [[List of regional railway stations in Victoria|regional services]] share tracks with several suburban train lines from the outskirts of Melbourne to the regional railway terminus at Southern Cross station (with the [[Traralgon V/Line rail service]] terminating at Flinders Street station). The Pakenham line has the longest shared track section which is used by V/Line services to the [[Latrobe Valley]]. The Werribee, Sunbury and Craigieburn lines also share lesser sections of track with counterpart suburban lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/opinion/how-decades-of-neglect-ran-the-vline-network-off-the-rails-20160120-gm9td5.html|title=How decades of neglect ran the V/Line network off the rails|last=Morton|first=Tony|date=2016-01-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Regional Rail Link]] project aimed to separate suburban services from all regional trains, except those to the North-East and the Latrobe Valley. A ceremonial start of construction was held in August 2009 and the project was completed in June 2015.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.railgeelong.com/gallery/events/rrl-first-sod\n|title=Regional Rail Link - turning of the first sod\n|work=Rail Geelong - Gallery\n|publisher=railgeelong.com\n|accessdate=29 August 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/premier/construction-starts-on-the-$4.3-billion-regional-rail-link.html\n |title       = CONSTRUCTION STARTS ON THE $4.3 BILLION REGIONAL RAIL LINK\n |work        = Media Release: Premier of Victoria\n |publisher   = premier.vic.gov.au\n |date        = 27 August 2009\n |accessdate  = 29 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090904223051/http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/premier/construction-starts-on-the-$4.3-billion-regional-rail-link.html\n |archivedate = 4 September 2009\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n\n==Freight services==\n[[File:Melbourne-steel-terminal.jpg|thumb|[[NR class]] locomotive at the Melbourne Steel Terminal, off Footscray Road]]\n{{Main|Freight railways in Melbourne}}\n\nMelbourne also has an extensive network of railway lines and yards to serve freight traffic. The lines are of two gauges\u2014{{RailGauge|5ft3in}} [[Victorian broad gauge|broad gauge]] and {{RailGauge|ussg}} [[standard gauge]], and are not electrified. In the inner western suburbs of the city, freight trains operate on dedicated lines, but in other areas freight trains share tracks with the suburban [[Metro Trains Melbourne]] and regional [[V/Line]] passenger services. The majority of freight terminals are located in the inner suburbs around [[Port of Melbourne]], others are located between the Melbourne CBD and Footscray.\n\nUntil the 1980s a number of suburban stations had their own [[rail yard|goods yards]], with freight trains running over the suburban network, often with the [[Victorian Railways E class (electric)|E]] or [[Victorian Railways L class (electric)|L class]] [[electric locomotive]]s.\n\n== Legislation, governance and access ==\n\n=== Key statutes ===\n{{Main|Transport Integration Act}}\n{{See also|Director of Public Transport|V/Line|VicTrack|Transport Act 1983|Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983}}\nThe prime rail statute in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] is the [[Transport Integration Act]].  The Act establishes the [[Department of Transport (Victoria, 2008\u201313)|Department of Transport]] as the integration agency for Victoria's transport system.  The Act also establishes and sets the charters of the state agencies charged with providing public transport rail services and managing network access for freight services, namely the [[Director of Public Transport]] and [[V/Line]].  In addition, the Act creates [[VicTrack]] which owns the public rail network and associated infrastructure.  Another important statute is the Rail Management Act 1996<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt3.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/742548D962C75039CA257761002C52FD/$FILE/96-79a050.pdf Rail Management Act 1996<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which confers powers on rail operators and provides for a rail access scheme for the state's rail network.\n\n=== Safety ===\n\n==== Regulation ====\n{{Main|Rail Safety Act}}\n{{See also|Director, Transport Safety}}\nThe safety of rail operations in [[Melbourne]] is regulated by the [[Rail Safety Act|Rail Safety Act 2006]] which applies to all commercial passenger and freight operations as well as tourist and heritage railways.<ref>Official copy of the [[Rail Safety Act]] from the Victorian Government legislation web site - http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt3.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/6D4190C62DE6207FCA257761002C568A/$FILE/06-9a016.pdf</ref> The Act creates a framework containing safety duties for all rail industry participants and requires rail operators who manage infrastructure and rolling stock to obtain accreditation prior to commencing operations.  Accredited rail operators are also required to have a [[Safety Management Systems|safety management system]] to guide their operations.\n\n[[Sanctions (law)|Sanctions]] applying to the safety scheme established under the [[Rail Safety Act]] are contained in the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983.<ref>See Part 7 of the Act.  Official copy of the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983 from the official Victorian Government legislation site - http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt5.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/7BB774D3E0245B77CA2577CE00030B90/$FILE/83-9921a153.pdf</ref> The safety [[regulatory agency|regulator]] for the rail system in [[Melbourne]] is the [[Director, Transport Safety]] (trading as [[Director, Transport Safety|Transport Safety Victoria]]) whose office is established under the [[Transport Integration Act|Transport Integration Act 2010]].\n\n==== Investigation ====\n{{Main|Chief Investigator, Transport Safety}}\nRail operators in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] can also be the subject of no blame investigations conducted by the [[Chief Investigator, Transport Safety]] or the [[Australian Transport Safety Bureau]](ATSB).  The Chief Investigator is charged by the [[Transport Integration Act]]<ref>[[Transport Integration Act 2010]], Part 7.</ref> with conducting investigations into rail safety matters including incidents and trends.  ATSB, on the other hand, has jusridiction over the same matters where they occur on the Defined Interstate Rail Network.\n\n=== Ticketing and conduct ===\nTicketing requirements for public transport in [[Melbourne]] are mainly contained in the Transport (Ticketing) Regulations 2006<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt5.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/C6D777772BB02CD3CA2577A5007CB77B/$FILE/06-86sr004.pdf Transport (Ticketing) Regulations 2006<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the Victorian Fares and Ticketing Manual.<ref>[http://www.metlinkmelbourne.com.au/fares-tickets/victorian-fares-and-ticketing-manual Victorian Fares and Ticketing Manual - Metlink - Your guide to public transport in Melbourne and Victoria<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514122346/http://www.metlinkmelbourne.com.au/fares-tickets/victorian-fares-and-ticketing-manual/ |date=14 May 2011 }}</ref> Rules about safe and fair conduct on trains and trams in [[Melbourne]] are generally contained in the [[Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983]]<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubLawToday.nsf/a12f6f60fbd56800ca256de500201e54/6ff43affd338ea35ca2577c60082b59c!OpenDocument Victorian Law Today Act<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the Transport (Conduct) Regulations 2005.<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubLawToday.nsf/b12e276826f7c27fca256de50022686b/2e01dcbed2e5778cca2574e20017da2c!OpenDocument Victorian Law Today Statutory Rule<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> If Metro does not reach its Punctuality and Delivery goals they will give out compensation to eligible customers. In the month of December 2014, Metro Trains had a delivery rate of 98.5%, and a Punctuality rate of 93.60%.<ref>http://www.metrotrains.com.au/metro-performance/</ref> In 2014, Metro Trains were accused of not stopping at underpopulated suburbs' stations in order to arrive on time, this practise has been condemned by the general public and the media. They have offered compensation to affected passengers.\n\n=== Tourist and heritage railways ===\n{{Main|Tourist and Heritage Railways Act}}\nTourist and Heritage Railways in [[Melbourne]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] are currently governed by provisions in the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983.  In future, they will be regulated by the recently enacted [[Tourist and Heritage Railways Act|Tourist and Heritage Railways Act 2010]],<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubStatbook.nsf/f932b66241ecf1b7ca256e92000e23be/e2cbeabed816bbcdca2577c1001d6f7a!OpenDocument Victorian Statute Book Act<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which commenced in October 2011.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]\n* [[V/Line]]\n* [[Freight railways in Melbourne]]\n* [[Rail transport in Victoria]]\n* [[Transport Integration Act]]\n* [[Director of Public Transport]]\n* [[Tourist and Heritage Railways Act]]\n* [[Rail Safety Act]]\n* [[Director, Transport Safety]]\n* [[Chief Investigator, Transport Safety]]\n* [[Transport Act 1983]]\n* [[Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading and reviews==\n* ''A review of Melbourne's Rail Franchising reforms'' Currie, Graham (2009) Journeys, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110815213035/http://www.ltaacademy.gov.sg/doc/J09Nov-p36Currie_RailFranchising.pdf Singapore Land Transit Authority Academy]\n* ''Refranchising Melbourne's metropolitan train and tram networks'' Deloitte Touche Thomatsu (2007), [https://web.archive.org/web/20100403021226/http://www.abp.unimelb.edu.au/gamut/pdf/value-assesment.pdf Department of Infrastructure]\n* ''The reliability of Melbourne's trains 1993-2007'' Mees, Dr. Paul (2007); [https://web.archive.org/web/20100403021220/http://www.abp.unimelb.edu.au/gamut/pdf/train-reliability.pdf University of Melbourne Urban Planning Program paper]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/ Public Transport Victoria] - official website of Melbourne's public transport authority\n* [http://www.vicsig.net/ Vicsig] - Victorian railways enthusiast website\n* [http://www.railpage.com.au/ Railpage Australia] - enthusiast website\n* [http://www.vlinecars.com/ V/LineCars.com] - Comprehensive V/Line carriage information & enthusiast website\n\n{{Australian rail}}\n{{MelbournePublicTransport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Railways in Melbourne}}\n[[Category:Public transport in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Victoria (Australia)|Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Melbourne rail network, including stations and infrastructure|operator of suburban passenger services in Melbourne|Metro Trains Melbourne}}\n{{short description|Railway network in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit\n| box_width = \n| name = Melbourne railway network\n| image = Melbourne train logo.svg\n| alt = Metropolitan Melbourne train network logo\n| imagesize = 100px\n| caption = \n| image2 = 1_flinders_st_station_melb.jpg\n| alt2 = \n| imagesize2 = \n| caption2 = Flinders Street railway station in 2010\n| native_name = <!-- use {{lang}} -->\n| owner = [[VicTrack]]\n| area served = \n| locale = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]<br />[[Australia]]\n| transit_type = [[Commuter rail]]\n| lines = 16\n| line_number = \n| start = \n| end = \n| stations = 220\n| daily_ridership = \n| annual_ridership = {{increase}} 243.2 million {{small|(2018-19)}}\n| chief_executive = \n| headquarters = \n| website = \n| began_operation = {{start date and age|1854|09|12|df=yes}}\n| ended_operation = <!-- {{end date and age|yyyy|mm|dd|df=yes}} -->\n| operator = [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]<br>[[V/Line]]\n| marks = \n| host = \n| character = At-grade with elevated and underground sections\n| vehicles = 224 six-car sets {{small|(October 2018)}}\n| train_length = \n| headway = \n| system_length = {{cvt|405|km|mi}}\n| notrack = \n| track_gauge = {{Track gauge|victorian|allk=on}}\n| ogauge = Various\n| minimum_radius_of_curvature = <!-- {{convert|0|ft|0|in|mm|0}} -->\n| el = 1500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[Overhead line|overhead]] (excluding Stony Point, which is not electrified)\n| average_speed = <!-- {{convert|0|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} -->\n| top_speed = <!-- {{convert|0|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} -->\n| map = {{Melbourne commuter rail route diagram|inline=yes}}\n| map_name = \n| map_state = collapsed\n}}\n{{Melbourne railway lines}}\n \nThe '''Melbourne rail network''' is a passenger and freight train system in the city of [[Melbourne]], Australia. It is the core of the larger [[Railways in Victoria|Victorian railway network]], with links to both intrastate and interstate systems. A large suburban passenger network centred on the [[Melbourne CBD|CBD]] also operates, with a limited degree of segregation from longer-distance passenger and freight trains.\n\nThe first steam train in Australia commenced service in Melbourne in 1854, with the network having grown over the last two centuries to consist of 220 stations across 16 lines, serving a yearly ridership of 243.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/assets/default-site/footer/data-and-reporting/annual-report/6b8c2cff5a/PTVH4043-Annual_Report_2019-A4-v1_ONLINE.pdf|title=Public Transport Victoria Annual Report 2018-2019|date=September 2019|website=static.ptv.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> [[Metro Trains Melbourne]] operates the Melbourne suburban railway network under [[franchising|franchise]] from the [[States and territories of Australia|State]] [[State Government of Victoria|Government of Victoria]], whilst the [[government-owned]] entity [[V/Line]] operates trains from Melbourne across [[Rail transport in Victoria|regional Victoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/victorias-public-transport-network/public-transport-partnership-agreements/|title=Public transport partnership agreements|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe suburban network is a [[commuter rail]] system designed to transport passengers from Melbourne's suburbs into the [[Melbourne city centre|Central Business District]] (CBD) and associated [[City Loop|city loop]] stations, with the main [[Transport hub|hub]] at [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street station]]. An underground line is currently under construction as part of the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]], which aims to unlock network capacity and provide Melbourne with a turn-up-and-go metro-like service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/melbourne-on-track-for-tokyos-turn-up-and-go-network/|title=Melbourne on Track For Tokyo's Turn Up And Go Network|date=2016-09-26|work=Premier of Victoria|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nA total length of 405&nbsp;km of track is owned by [[VicTrack]] and leased to train operators through [[Public Transport Victoria]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://classic.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/data-and-reports/research-and-statistics/|title=Research and statistics |website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English |access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> The railway network is primarily at ground level, with smaller underground and [[Elevated railway|elevated]] sections.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ptua.org.au/2009/09/02/cross-out-level-crossings/ |title=Cross out Melbourne\u2019s level crossings \u2013 Public Transport Users Association (Victoria, Australia)|website=www.ptua.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> There were more than 170 [[level crossing]]s before the [[Level Crossing Removal Authority|Level Crossing Removal Project]] commenced in 2015 to grade separate 75 of the busiest crossings and ease associated road congestion.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/about|title=About {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Authority|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> The suburban network operates primarily between 5:00&nbsp;a.m. and midnight, with 24-hour services from Friday to Sunday.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/all-night-public-transport-on-weekends-here-to-stay/|title=All Night Public Transport on Weekends Here To Stay|date=2017-04-22 |work=Premier of Victoria|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Some tracks are also used by [[Freight railways in Melbourne|freight trains]] and [[V/Line]] [[List of regional railway stations in Victoria|regional services]].\n\nIn addition to the primary commuter and freight railway networks, Melbourne also features heritage railways such as [[Puffing Billy Railway|Puffing Billy]] and has the world's largest urban [[Trams in Melbourne|tram network]].\n\n== History ==\n=== First railway ===\nOn 7 September 1851 a public meeting called for the construction of Australia's first railway to linking Melbourne and Sandridge (now known as [[Port Melbourne]]), which led to the establishment of the privately owned [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] in 1853.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://collections.museumvictoria.com.au/articles/2215|title=Melbourne & Hobson's Bay Railway Co., Melbourne, Victoria|work=Museums Victoria Collections|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://infrastructure.gov.au/rail/trains/history.aspx|title=History of Rail in Australia|website=infrastructure.gov.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 1853 the Government also approved the establishment of the [[Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company]] and the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]]. Work began in March 1853 on the Sandridge railway line, stretching {{convert|4|km}} from the Melbourne (or City) terminus (on the site of modern-day [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street station]]) to Sandridge. The line was owned and operated by Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company, opening in 1854.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austehc.unimelb.edu.au/tia/836.html|title=Technology in Australia 1788-1988, Chapter 12, page 836|last=Centre|first=Australian Science and Technology Heritage|website=www.austehc.unimelb.edu.au|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1855 the Government conducted enquiries and carried out surveys into country railways. On 1 April 1856, the [[Victorian Railways|Railway Department]] was established as part of the Board of Land and Works with [[George Christian Darbyshire]] being appointed Engineer in Chief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/90654|title=Parliament of Victoria Record 90654|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> On 23 May of that year the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]] was taken over by the Government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=National Trust Masonry Bridges Study Gary Vines|publisher=National Trust of Australia (Victoria)|year=2010}}</ref>\n\nTrains were ordered from Robert Stephenson and Company of the [[United Kingdom]]. The first train was locally built by [[Robertson, Martin & Smith]], however, owing to delays in shipping. Australia's first steam locomotive was built in ten weeks and cost [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,700. Forming the first [[Locomotive#Steam|steam train]] to travel in Australia, it made its maiden trip on 12 September 1854.<ref>Although horse-drawn \"trains\" debuted on a [[Victor Harbor railway line|railway between Goolwa and Port Elliot]] in [[South Australia]] on 18 May of that year, Melbourne hosted the first mechanical railway.</ref>\n\nThe opening of the line occurred during the period of the [[Victorian gold rush]]\u2014a time when both Melbourne and Victoria undertook massive capital works, each with its own gala opening. The inaugural journey on the Sandridge line was no exception. According to the [[The Argus (Australia)|Argus]] [[newspaper]]'s report of the next day: \"''Long before the hour appointed . . . a great crowd assembled round the station at the Melbourne terminus, lining the whole of [[Flinders Street, Melbourne|Flinders Street]]''\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/rosstown-springvale-cemetery-kew-melbournes-phantom-railway-lines/news-story/1fff2d2be277ede00fb41886c7b19e6b|title=Rosstown, Springvale Cemetery, Kew: Melbourne's phantom railway lines|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> [[Governors of Victoria|Lieutenant-Governor]] [[Charles Hotham|Sir Charles Hotham]] and Lady Hotham were aboard the train\u2014which consisted of two [[First class travel|first class]] carriages and one second class\u2014and were presented with [[satin]] copies of the railway's [[Public transport timetable|timetable]] and [[bylaw]]s.\n\nThe trip took 10 minutes, none of the later stations along the line having been built yet. On arriving at [[Station Pier]] (onto which the tracks extended), it was hailed with gun-salutes by the warships [[HMS Electra (1837)|HMS ''Electra'']] and [[HMS Fantome (1839)|HMS ''Fantome'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://twistedhistory.net.au/wordpress/2017/09/12/australias-first-train-makes-its-maiden-voyage-melbourne-2/|title=Australia\u2019s first train makes its maiden voyage \u2013 Melbourne|date=2017-09-11|work=Twisted History (Limelight Tours)|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nBy March 1855, the four engines ordered from the UK were all in service, with trains running every half-hour. They were named ''Melbourne'', ''Sandridge'', ''Victoria'', and ''Yarra'' (after the [[Yarra River]] over which the line crossed).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1839-1899|title=Victorian Railways History 1839 - 1899|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=29 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Early private companies ===\n[[File:Melbourne-steam-hauled-suburban.jpg|thumb|Steam-hauled suburban train departing North Melbourne station for Sunshine]]\n[[File:Old Flinders Street Station.jpg|thumb|The pre 1910 [[Flinders Street railway station]] building on [[Swanston Street]]]]\n\nThe [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] opened Melbourne's second railway on 13 May 1857, a 4.5&nbsp;km line from the Melbourne (or City) Terminus to [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]]. The line was later extended by the [[St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company]], which opened a line from St Kilda to [[Middle Brighton railway station|Brighton]] in 1857.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe first country line opened in 1857, when the [[Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company]] started services on its line from [[Geelong]] to [[Newport railway station, Melbourne|Newport]]. In 1859, the government-owned [[Victorian Railways]] [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown line]] opened, connecting [[Williamstown railway station|Williamstown]] and Geelong to [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMore country lines followed in 1859 when the Victorian Railways opened a line from [[Footscray railway station|Footscray]], on the Williamstown line, to [[Sunbury railway station, Melbourne|Sunbury]]. The Victorian Railways had taken over construction from the [[Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway Company]], established in 1853 to build a railway to [[Echuca, Victoria|Echuca]], but which had failed to make any progress.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe first line to Melbourne's south-eastern suburbs was opened in 1859 by the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]], running from [[Princes Bridge railway station]] to [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Punt Road]] (Richmond), [[South Yarra railway station|South Yarra]], and [[Prahran railway station|Prahran]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=449&gall=453|title=Melbourne & Suburban Railway Co. - Victorian Railways, Museum Victoria, Australia|website=museumsvictoria.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> That line was extended to [[Windsor railway station, Melbourne|Windsor]] in 1860, connecting with the St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company line from St Kilda. The new line replaced the indirect [[St Kilda - Windsor railway line|St Kilda and Windsor line]] to the city, which was closed in 1867.\n\nAnother suburban line was built by the [[Melbourne and Essendon Railway Company]] in 1860, running from [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]] to [[Essendon railway station|Essendon]], with a branch line from [[Newmarket railway station, Melbourne|Newmarket]] to [[Flemington Racecourse railway station|Flemington Racecourse]], which opened in 1861. On the eastern side of the city, the [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]] opened a branch line from Richmond to [[Burnley railway station|Burnley]] and [[Hawthorn railway station, Melbourne|Hawthorn]] in 1861.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/mileposts_vr_history.pdf|title=Mileposts in Victorian Railway History 1839-1964|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy that point, the railways of Melbourne were a disjointed group of city-centric lines, with various companies operating from three unconnected city terminals\u2014[[Princes Bridge railway station|Princes Bridge]], [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]], and [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street]] stations.\n\nThe smaller companies quickly encountered financial problems. The [[St Kilda and Brighton Railway Company]] and [[Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company]] were absorbed by the [[Melbourne and Hobson's Bay Railway Company]] in 1865, forming the [[Melbourne and Hobsons Bay United Railway Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hstm-index.com/index/melbourne-suburban-railway-company-32.html|title=HSTM Historic Stocks Market Index {{!}} Melbourne & Suburban Railway Company|website=www.hstm-index.com|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> The [[Melbourne and Essendon Railway Company]] was taken over by the Victorian Government in 1867. The Melbourne and Hobsons Bay United Railway Company was not taken over by the [[Victorian Government]] until 1878.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/88980|title=Melbourne and Hobson's Bay United Railway Railway : return to an Order of the Legislative Assembly dated 16th July 1878 for a return showing the Agreement made between the Directors of the Melbourne and Hobson's Bay United Railway Company and the Government for the purchase of the undertaking of the Company|last=Parliamentary Papers Database|first=Parliament of Victoria|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nThe terminals themselves were linked in 1879, when track was built at street level along the southern side of Flinders Street, connecting with [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]], although the track was only used at night, for freight traffic. It was not until 1889 that the two-track [[Flinders Street Viaduct]] was built between the two city terminus stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/location/Viaduct-Junction|title=VICSIG Infrastructure|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOutward expansion also continued, with major trunk lines being opened in rural Victoria. The Victorian Railways extended its line to [[Broadmeadows railway station, Melbourne|Broadmeadows]] in 1872, as part of the line to [[Seymour railway station|Seymour]] and [[Albury railway station|Albury]]-[[Wodonga railway station|Wodonga]]. In 1879, the [[Gippsland Railway|Gippsland line]] was opened from South Yarra to [[Caulfield railway station, Melbourne|Caulfield]], [[Pakenham railway station|Pakenham]] and [[Bairnsdale, Victoria|Bairnsdale]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Land boom lines ===\n[[File:Camberwell Station 1.jpg|thumb|Connex train arriving at [[Camberwell railway station, Melbourne|Camberwell]] railway station]]\n[[File:Alameinstation.jpg|thumb|Train at [[Alamein railway station]]]]\n\nThe 1870s and 1880s were a time of great growth and prosperity in Melbourne. Land speculation companies were formed, to buy up outer suburban land cheaply, and to agitate for suburban railways to be built or extended to serve these land holdings and increase land values. By 1880 the \"Land Boom\" was in full swing in Victoria, with the passing of the [[Railway Construction Act 1884]], later known as the ''Octopus Act'' for the 66 lines across the state that were authorised in it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/onthisday/decade.cfm?d=1880 |title=On These Days - Parliament of Victoria |publisher=parliament.vic.gov.au |accessdate=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815114743/http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/onthisday/decade.cfm?d=1880 |archivedate=15 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] began with the opening of a line from Caulfield to [[Mordialloc railway station|Mordialloc]] in 1881, reaching the terminus in 1882.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhistory.kingston.vic.gov.au/htm/article/329.htm|title=Events in the Past: Establishing a Railway Line to Mordialloc|last=Historical Website|first=City of Kingston|website=localhistory.kingston.vic.gov.au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> A second new suburban railway line was opened from Spencer Street Station to [[Coburg railway station|Coburg]] in 1884, and extended to [[Somerton, Victoria|Somerton]] in 1889, meeting the main line from Spencer Street to Wodonga.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alburywodongaaustralia.com.au/info/history/|title=Albury Wodonga History - Albury Wodonga Australia|website=www.alburywodongaaustralia.com.au|language=en-au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> Land developers opened a private railway from Newport to [[Altona railway station|Altona]] in 1888, but it was closed in 1890, due to lack of demand.\n\nThe line from Hawthorn was extended, to [[Camberwell railway station, Melbourne|Camberwell]] in 1882, [[Lilydale railway station|Lilydale]] in 1883, and [[Healesville railway station|Healesville]] in 1889.<ref name=\":3\" /> In addition, a branch line (now known as the [[Belgrave railway line|Belgrave line]]) was opened from [[Ringwood railway station, Melbourne|Ringwood]] to [[Upper Ferntree Gully railway station|Upper Ferntree Gully]] in 1889.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maroondah.vic.gov.au/Explore/About-our-city/History-of-Maroondah/History-of-Ringwood|title=History of Ringwood|website=www.maroondah.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> A short branch two station was also opened from Hawthorn to [[Kew railway line|Kew]] in 1887. The Brighton Beach line was also extended to [[Sandringham railway station|Sandringham]] in 1887.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianplaces.com.au/sandringham|title=Sandringham {{!}} Victorian Places|website=www.victorianplaces.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1888, railways came to the north eastern suburbs with the opening of the [[Inner Circle railway line|Inner Circle]] line from [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]] via [[Royal Park railway station, Melbourne|Royal Park]] station to what is now [[Victoria Park railway station, Melbourne|Victoria Park]] station, and then on to [[Heidelberg railway station|Heidelberg]]. A branch was also opened off the Inner Circle in [[Fitzroy North, Victoria|Fitzroy North]], to [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] and [[Whittlesea railway station, Melbourne|Whittlesea]] in 1888 and 1889.<ref name=\":2\" /> Trains between Spencer Street and Heidelberg reversed at Victoria Park until a link was opened between Victoria Park and [[Princes Bridge railway station|Princes Bridge]] in 1901.\n\nThe [[Outer Circle railway line|Outer Circle]] line opened in 1890, linking [[Oakleigh railway station|Oakleigh]] (on the [[Pakenham railway line|Gippsland line]]) to [[Riversdale railway station|Riversdale]] (with a branch to Camberwell on the [[Lilydale railway line|Lilydale line]]) and [[Fairfield railway station, Melbourne|Fairfield]] (on the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Heidelberg line]]). Originally envisaged to link the [[Gippsland Railway|Gippsland line]] with [[Southern Cross railway station|Spencer Street station]] in the 1870s, this reason disappeared with the building of a direct link via South Yarra before the line had even opened. The line saw little traffic as it traversed empty paddocks, and with no through traffic, the Outer Circle was closed in sections between 1893 and 1897. The [[Alamein railway line|Camberwell to Ashburton]] stretch of the Outer Circle re-opened in 1899, then in 1900, part of the northern section of the Outer Circle reopened as a shuttle service between [[East Camberwell railway station|East Camberwell]] and [[Deepdene railway station, Melbourne|Deepdene station]]. This line closed in 1927.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outercircleline.com.au/about-me.html|title=The Outer Circle - Melbourne's Forgotten Railway|website=outercircleline.com.au|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the same time as the Outer Circle, a railway was opened from Burnley to [[Darling railway station|Darling]] and a junction with the Outer Circle at [[Waverley Road railway station|Waverley Road]] (near the modern [[East Malvern railway station|East Malvern]]). A stub of the future Glen Waverley line, it was cut back to Darling in 1895.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8594287|title=THE GLEN IRIS LINE.|date=1890-03-13|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2018-05-12|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nThe land boom railway building hit a peak with the construction of the [[Rosstown Railway]] between Elsternwick and Oakleigh. Built by [[William Murry Ross]], the line was planned from the 1870s to serve a sugar beet mill near Caulfield. Construction commenced in 1883, followed by rebuilding in 1888. Ross's debt grew, and he attempted to sell the line many times without success. The line never opened to traffic and was later dismantled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/files/assets/public/document-resources/recreation/rosstown_rail_trail.pdf|title=Rosstown Rail Trail|website=Glen Eira City Council|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe stock market crash of 1891 lead to an extended period of economic depression, and put an end to railway construction until the next decade.\n\nBy the 1900s, the driving force for new railway lines were the farmers in what is now Melbourne's outer suburbs. In the [[Dandenong Ranges]] a narrow gauge [[Narrow gauge lines of the Victorian Railways|762 mm line]] was opened from Upper Ferntree Gully to [[Belgrave railway station|Belgrave]] and [[Gembrook railway station|Gembrook]] in 1900 to serve the local farming and timber community. In the [[Yarra Valley]] a branch was opened from Lilydale to [[Yarra Junction railway station|Yarra Junction]] and [[Warburton railway station|Warburton]] in 1901. Part of this line is now listed on the [[Victorian Heritage Register]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vhd.heritagecouncil.vic.gov.au/places/115471/download-report|title=Victorian Heritage Database Report: Lilydale - Warburton Railway|website=Victorian Heritage Council|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, in preparation for the occasion of a royal visit by the [[Duke of York]], the first Australian [[royal train]] was assembled in Melbourne.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1900-1949|title=Victorian Railway Histories 1900 - 1949|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hurstbridge railway line|Heidelberg line]] was extended to [[Eltham railway station, Melbourne|Eltham]] in 1902 and [[Hurstbridge railway station|Hurstbridge]] in 1912. The freight only [[Mont Park railway line|Mont Park line]] was also opened in 1911, branching from [[Macleod railway station|Macleod]]. Finally on the [[Mornington Peninsula]], a branch was built from [[Bittern railway station|Bittern]] to [[Red Hill railway line|Red Hill]] in 1921.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Electrification ===\n[[File:DDE750.jpg|thumb|First set of [[Tait (train)|Tait]] suburban passenger carriages hauled by steam locomotive [[Victorian Railways Dd class|Dde 750]], 1913]]\n[[File:Springvalecemeterystation.jpg|thumb|Four car Tait train at the [[Spring Vale Cemetery railway station|Spring Vale Cemetery]] platform]]\n\nPlanning for electrification was started by [[Victorian Railways]] chairman [[Thomas James Tait]], who engaged [[United Kingdom|English]] engineer [[Charles Hesterman Merz]] to deliver a report on the electrification of the Melbourne suburban network. His first report in 1908 recommended a three-stage plan over 2 years, covering 200 route km of existing lines and almost 500 suburban carriages (approximately 80 trains).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-489878788|title=Report upon the Application of electric traction to the Melbourne suburban railway system|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The report was considered by the Government and the Railway Commissioners, and Merz was engaged to deliver a second report based on their feedback.\n\nDelivered in 1912, this second report recommended an expanded system of electrification to 240 route km. of existing lines (463 track km), and almost 800 suburban carriages (approximately 130 trains).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ehive.com/collections/6420/objects/778129/report-of-mr-thos-tait-as-to-his-inquiries-in-connexion-with-electrification-of-melbourne-suburban-|title=Report of Mr. Thos. Tait as to his inquiries in connexion with electrification o... on eHive|website=eHive|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The works were approved by the State Government in December 1912.<ref name=\":4\" /> It was envisaged that the first electric trains would be running by 1915, and the project would be completed by 1917. However, progress fell behind because [[World War I]] restrictions prevented electrical equipment being imported from the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=505&gall=693|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains (Newport Power Station)|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nRolling stock construction continued, with a number of older suburban carriages converted for electric use as the [[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]] trains, while the first of the [[Tait (train)|Tait]] trains were introduced as steam hauled carriages. Track expansion was also carried out, with four tracks being provided between South Yarra and Caulfield, as well as grade separation from roads. Victorian Railways in 1918 opened the [[Newport Power Station, Victoria|Newport power station]], the largest power station in the urban area, to supply electricity as part of the electrification project.<ref name=Newport>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/big-expansion-planned-for-newport/2006/11/12/1163266412333.html|title=Big expansion planned for Newport|publisher=Fairfax Digital, The Age|accessdate=2008-10-05 | location=Melbourne | date=13 November 2006}}</ref> The [[State Electricity Commission of Victoria]] was formed in 1921 but did not take over Newport A power station until 1951.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe first trials did not occur until October 1918 on the [[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse line]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=2&IRN=502|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Driver training continued on this line until 18 May 1919, when the first electric train ran between [[Sandringham railway line|Sandringham]] and [[Craigieburn railway line|Essendon]], simulating revenue services. Electric services started on 28 May 1919 with the first train running to Essendon, then on to Sandringham, with full services started the next day.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Glen Waverley railway line|Burnley\u2013Darling line]], the [[Upfield railway line|Fawkner line]], the reopened branch to Altona, and the [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown line]] followed in 1920.\n\nThe line to Broadmeadows, the [[Mernda railway line|Whittlesea line]] to [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], the [[Sunbury railway line|Bendigo line]] to [[St Albans railway station, Melbourne|St Albans]], and the inner sections of the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]] were electrified in 1921. The [[Pakenham railway line|Gippsland line]] to [[Dandenong railway station|Dandenong]] and Frankston line were electrified in 1922, as was the inner section of the [[Lilydale railway line|Ringwood line]] due to regrading works.\n\nThe original electrification scheme was completed in 1923,<ref name=\":6\" /> but over the next three years a number of short extensions were carried out. The Ashburton line was electrified in 1924, final works on the Lilydale line were completed in 1925, as was electrification on the line to [[Upper Ferntree Gully railway station|Upper Ferntree Gully]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/alamein|title=VICSIG Alamein Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/lilydale|title=VICSIG Lilydale Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/location/Upper-Ferntree-Gully|title=VICSIG Upper Ferntree Gully Station|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Electrification on the outer ends of the Hurstbridge line were completed by 1926, the [[Mernda railway line|Whittlesea line]] to [[Thomastown railway station, Melbourne|Thomastown]] was electrified in 1929, and the Burnley - Darling line was extended to [[Glen Waverley railway station|Glen Waverley]] in 1930 to become the [[Glen Waverley railway line|Glen Waverley line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.vicnet.net.au/~whsvic/railways.htm|title=Waverley Historical Society - Railways and the Waverley Area|website=home.vicnet.net.au|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Post-War rebuilding===\n[[File:Harris795M.jpg|thumb|A retired [[Harris (train)|Harris]] train]]\nRailways experienced increased patronage into the 1940s, but railway improvements recommended in the [[Ashworth Improvement Plan]] were delayed until after [[World War II]].<ref name=lee185>{{cite book |author=Lee, Robert |title=The Railways of Victoria 1854-2004 |publisher=Melbourne University Publishing Ltd |year=2007 |isbn= 978-0-522-85134-2 |page=185}}</ref> It was not until 1950 that the [[Victorian Railways]] were able to put their [[Operation Phoenix (railway)|Operation Phoenix]] rebuilding plan into action.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/rail-history/victorian-railways-history-1950-1974|title=Victorian Railways History 1950 - 1974|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=16 May 2018}}</ref> The delivery of the [[Harris (train)|Harris]] trains, the first steel suburban trains on the network, enabled the retirement of the oldest of the [[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]] trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=502&gall=671|title=Victorian Railways: Electric Trains (Blue 'Harris' Electric Trains)|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nRailway lines were extended during this period to encompass Melbourne's growing suburban footprint. The [[Alamein railway line|Ashburton line]] was extended along the old Outer Circle track formation to [[Alamein railway station|Alamein station]] in 1948.<ref name=\":7\" /> The Fawkner line to [[Upfield railway station|Upfield]] and the Reservoir line to [[Lalor railway station|Lalor]] were both electrified in 1959, the Epping line reaching [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] in 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/upfield|title=VICSIG Upfield Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> A great deal of track amplification was also undertaken, with a number of single line sections eliminated.<ref>[http://www.smartpassengers.org.au/policy3.html Policy: Track Amplifications (Duplication, Triplication etc)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091024011235/http://www.smartpassengers.org.au/policy3.html |date=24 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Upper Ferntree Gully to Belgrave section of the [[Narrow gauge lines of the Victorian Railways|Gembrook narrow gauge line]] was converted to [[Victorian broad gauge|broad gauge]] and electrified in 1962.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/belgrave|title=VICSIG Belgrave Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The remainder of the line was closed in 1954, but has been progressively reopened by the [[Puffing Billy Railway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://puffingbilly.com.au/en/about-puffing-billy/history-heritage/|title=History & Heritage|website=puffingbilly.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516175032/http://puffingbilly.com.au/en/about-puffing-billy/history-heritage/|archive-date=16 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham line]] was electrified in 1954 as part of the works being carried out on the [[Bairnsdale railway line|Gippsland line]], but suburban services to Pakenham did not start until 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/pakenham|title=VICSIG Pakenham Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring this rebuilding, a number of little used lines were closed on the edges of Melbourne. The Bittern to Red Hill line closed in 1953, the line between Epping and Whittlesea closed in 1959, and the Lilydale to [[Warburton railway station|Warburton]] line closed in 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Red-Hill|title=VICSIG Red Hill Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Whittlesea|title=VICSIG Whittlesea Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Warburton|title=VICSIG Warburton Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The final stages of the rebuilding stretched into the 1970s, with track amplification carried out to [[Footscray railway station|Footscray]], and [[Box Hill railway station, Melbourne|Box Hill]], and the first deliveries of the stainless steel [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=3&IRN=502&gall=672|title=Victorian Railways: Stainless Steel Hitachi Trains|website=Museums Victoria|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nDetailed planning for the [[Doncaster railway line|Doncaster line]] also commenced in this period, and by 1972 the route was decided upon. Despite rising costs, the state governments of the period continued to make assurances that the line would be built,<ref name=\"nr42\">{{cite magazine\n |date=February 1998\n | title = Whatever Happened to the Proposed Railway to Doncaster East\n | author = Stephen Cauchi\n |magazine= Newsrail\n | publisher = Australian Railway Historical Society (Victorian Division)\n | volume = 26\n | issue = 2\n | page =42\n }}</ref> but by 1984 land for the line had been sold.<ref name=\"nr42\" />\n\n=== Modernisation ===\n[[File:Melbourne Central Station 2.jpg|thumb|[[Melbourne Central railway station]] in the underground [[City Loop]]]]\n[[File:Comeng-galvin-site.jpg|thumb|[[Comeng (train)|Comeng]] train on the [[Werribee railway line|Werribee line]]]]\n\nBy the 1970s, Melbourne's railway network was run down, with the last major investment on the suburban tracks having taken place nearly fifty years earlier. Sixty-year-old [[Tait (train)|Tait trains]] (known colloquially as \"red rattlers\") were still in operation, and inner city congestion at [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]] led to peak hour delays.<ref name=\":8\" /> In February 1971, the Melbourne Underground Rail Loop Act was passed, establishing the [[Melbourne Underground Rail Loop Authority]] (MURLA) to build a connecting series of tunnels from the major stations along the north, south, east and west extremities of the Melbourne CBD.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/about-ptv/victorias-public-transport-network/history/city-loop-history/|title=City Loop history|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The project ran for over 14 years, opening progressively between 1981 and 1985. The loop was designed and constructed to improve the capacity of Flinders Street and Spencer Street stations to handle suburban trains and to offer easier connections for users.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOther major changes took place in 1976 when the government authority overseeing [[Victorian Railways]] became VicRail and was gradually restructured along corporate lines. Following the restructure, in 1980 the Victorian Transport Study, better known as the [[Lonie Report]], was delivered and called for financial rationalisation. The closure of the Port Melbourne, St. Kilda, Altona, Williamstown, Alamein and Sandringham lines was also recommended, along with their replacement with bus routes instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/vufind/Record/45154|title=Parliament of Victoria - Report on Vicrail financial system : ordered by the Legislative Assembly to be printed|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> These recommendations and cuts were not enacted, however many uneconomical branch lines were closed throughout the rest of the state.<ref name=\":10\" /> The line between Lilydale and Healesville was closed in 1980, now used by the [[Yarra Valley Railway]] beyond Yarra Glen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Healesville|title=VICSIG Healesville Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The branch from [[Baxter railway station|Baxter]] to [[Mornington railway station|Mornington]] was closed in 1981, but the line south of [[Moorooduc railway station|Moorooduc]] is now operated by the [[Mornington Railway]] as a tourist route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicsig.net/infrastructure/line/Mornington|title=VICSIG Mornington Line|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metrol]] train control centre was opened in 1980 to coordinate trains throughout the network using computer software that remains in use today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/30yearold-railway-computers-take-a-byte-out-of-the-past-20131014-2vitp.html|title=30-year-old railway computers take a byte out of the past|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2013-10-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Public transport in Melbourne was also reorganised, with the [[Metropolitan Transit Authority (Victoria)|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] (MTA) formed in 1983 to coordinate all train, tram and bus services in the city to improve interoperability.<ref name=\":10\" /> With the electrification of the [[Werribee railway line|Werribee line]] in 1983, followed two years later by an extension of the Altona line to [[Laverton railway station, Melbourne|Laverton]], and the City Loop in full operation by 1985, the last major modernisation of Melbourne's train lines in the 20th century was complete.\n\nIsolated from the City Loop, the [[Port Melbourne railway line|Port Melbourne]] and [[St Kilda railway line|St Kilda]] lines were converted to [[standard gauge]] light rail in 1987 to accommodate tram routes 111 (now [[Melbourne tram route 109|route 109]]) and [[Melbourne tram route 96|96]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The route 96 remains one of the world's top 10 tram routes, and Melbourne's busiest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/national/tram-96-travels-tracks-to-glory/2008/03/07/1204780065938.html|title=Tram 96 travels tracks to glory - National - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/style/one-of-melbournes-busiest-trams-has-had-its-peak-hour-services-cut-jfc/|title=One of Melbourne's Busiest Trams Has Had Its Peak Hour Services Cut & JFC - Pedestrian TV|date=2017-04-06|work=Pedestrian TV|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Southern Cross Suburban.JPG|thumb|The modern [[Southern Cross railway station|Southern Cross station]]]]\n[[File:Roxburgh Park railway station, Melbourne.jpg|thumb|[[Roxburgh Park railway station|Roxburgh Park]] station, opened in 2007.]]\n\nThe early 1990s saw further changes, with the MTA reborn as the [[Public Transport Corporation]], trading as \"The Met\".\n\nState Governments of both sides of politics began to push for reform of the railway network, proposing conversion of the Upfield, Williamstown and Alamein lines to light rail.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} These proposals failed, with the Upfield line instead receiving a series of upgrades to replace labour-intensive manual signalling systems. [[Government of Australia|Federal government]] funding was made available for the electrification of the [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne line]], which was completed in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/1995-06-05/0087%22;src1=sm1|title=ParlInfo - GRIEVANCE DEBATE : Corinella|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Rationalisation of the [[Jolimont Yard|Jolimont rail yard]] commenced, enabling the creation and expansion of [[Melbourne Park]] in 1988 and 1996, and the future construction of [[Federation Square]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fedsquare.com/about/history-design|title=History + Design - Federation Square|website=fedsquare.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nUpon the [[Jeff Kennett|Kennett]] Government's election in 1992, a number of controversial reforms to the operation of the railway system were initiated, with guards being abolished from suburban trains and train drivers taking over the task of door operation. Stations were de-manned, and the [[Metcard]] ticketing system was introduced to phase out the old scratch ticketing system.<ref name=\":10\" /> Over this period more than $250 million of operating cost was stripped from the Melbourne network, as the government sought to reign in growing state debt of $32 Billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/publications/research-papers/download/36-research-papers/13691-2011-11dbpublictransportdevelopmentauthority|title=Parliament of Victoria - Transport Legislation Amendment (Public Transport Development Authority) Bill 2011|website=www.parliament.vic.gov.au|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/two-decades-on-jeff-kennetts-legacy-lingers-20121002-26xob.html|title=Two decades on, Jeff Kennett's legacy lingers|date=2012-10-02|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Privatisation===\nIn 1997 \"The Met\" was split into two operating units \u2014Hillside Trains and Bayside Trains, each to be franchised to a different private operator. Ownership of land and infrastructure for rail and tram services was transferred to a new Victorian Government agency, [[VicTrack]]. In addition, a statutory office was created in Government\u2014the [[Director of Public Transport]]\u2014with specific responsibility for entering into franchise agreements with public transport operators for the operation of rail and tram services throughout Victoria. By 1999 the [[Privatization|privatisation]] process was complete, with [[Connex Melbourne]] and [[M-Train|M>Train]] each operating half of the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptua.org.au/campaigns/govern/priv-1999/|title=The First Train-Tram Privatisation: 1999 \u2013 Public Transport Users Association (Victoria, Australia)|website=www.ptua.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> In 2003 the parent company of M>Train ([[National Express]]) withdrew from operating public transport in Victoria, and their half of the suburban network was passed to Connex as part of a renegotiated contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/12/16/1039656342711.html|title=Train, tram operator quits - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nThe franchising contracts contained provisions for the new operators to refurbish the Comeng trains, and to replace the older [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains. Connex purchased [[Alstom]] [[X'Trapolis 100|X'Trapolis]] sets, while M>Train chose [[Siemens (train)|Siemens Nexas]] units.<ref name=\"RGI 1 Apr 2002\">{{cite news |title=Hillside EMU shipped to Melbourne |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/hillside-emu-shipped-to-melbourne.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=Railway Gazette International |date=1 April 2002 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005, the State Government commissioned a A$25 million study into the feasibility of a [[Dandenong railway line triplication|third track for the Dandenong line]] to increase capacity for the rapidly growing suburban area. The cost of the triplication process was expected to be as high as A$1 billion, as project activities would have included the organization of corresponding bus services for the rail line, changes to stations and platforms along the line, and the improvement of the signalling system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/state-trains-running-decades-late/2005/10/23/1130006003305.html|title=State trains running decades late|author=Dan Silkstone|date=24 October 2005|newspaper=The Age|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref> This project was ultimately sidelined and not delivered by the Brumby Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/money-doubt-on-third-rail-track-to-dandenong-20070506-ge4tpu.html|title=Money doubt on third rail track to Dandenong|last=Cauchi|first=Stephen|date=2007-05-06|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Professor Paul Mees and a group of academics estimated that privatisation had cost taxpayers $1.2 billion more than if the system had remained both publicly owned and operated. With the franchise extensions in 2009, taxpayers were to pay an estimated $2.1 billion more by 2010.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/12bn-sting-in-the-rail/2006/04/08/1143916767672.html The Age, 4/8/2009]</ref> However, the [[Institute of Public Affairs]] released its own report into Melbourne's privatisation, which assessed it as a modest success and observed that a 37.6% increase in patronage on the metropolitan rail system had reversed years of patronage decline due to poor quality services.<ref name=\"Allsop 2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Allsop |first1=Richard |title=Victoria's public transport: assessing the results of privatisation |journal=IPA Backgrounder |date=April 2007 |volume=19 |issue=1 |url=https://ipa.org.au/wp-content/uploads/archive/ALLSOP_Transport.pdf |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> The Auditor General of Victoria also performed a comprehensive audit report into the franchises and found that \"the franchises represent reasonable value for money\".<ref>Franchising Melbourne's train and tram system (2005:11), The Auditor General of Victoria, {{cite web |url=http://download.audit.vic.gov.au/files/ptfranchising_report.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010154638/http://download.audit.vic.gov.au/files/ptfranchising_report.pdf |archivedate=10 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Ridership boom and Metro Trains Melbourne ===\n[[File:Melbourne Metropolitan Train Patronage 1998 to 2018.png|thumb|Metropolitan train patronage 1998-2018 based on official state government figures.|385x385px]]\nBeginning in the mid-2000s, a rapid increase in patronage of Melbourne's train network occurred. In the three-year period between [[Financial Year|financial year]] 2005 and 2008 rail patronage grew by 35 per cent. Trips grew from 148 million in 2004 to more than 200 million in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptua.org.au/myths/express.shtml|title=Common Urban Myths About Transport|date=2 January 2009|work=Public Transport Users Association|publisher=Public Transport Users Association Inc|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, [[Singapore]]'s [[SMRT Corporation|SMRT]] Transit and [[Hong Kong]]'s [[MTR Corporation Limited]] expressed interest in taking control of Melbourne's suburban rail network from Connex in November 2009, when their contract was to be reviewed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/private-companies-could-boost-rail-tram-expansion/2007/11/25/1195975867985.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Private companies could boost rail, tram expansion | date=26 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June 2009, Connex lost its bid to renew its contract with the Victorian Government. Hong Kong backed and owned [[MTR Corporation]] took over the Melbourne train network on 30 November 2009, operating as a locally themed consortium [[Metro Trains Melbourne]].<ref>Swinburne Institute for Social Research: [http://www.sisr.net/publications/0604transport.pdf Putting the Public Interest back into Public Transport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013092605/http://www.sisr.net/publications/0604transport.pdf |date=13 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/new-train-tram-operators-for-melbourne-20090625-cxgx.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=New train, tram operators for Melbourne | first=Mex | last=Cooper | date=25 June 2009}}</ref> MTR is a non-public railway owner and operator in Hong Kong where it is well known for constructing Transit Oriented Developments (TODS) above and around its stations. Metro began operation on 1 December 2009, promising to draw on its international experience to improve Melbourne's rail operations.<ref name=\"Age 25 Jun 2009\">{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Mex |title=New train, tram operators for Melbourne |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/new-train-tram-operators-for-melbourne-20090625-cxgx.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=25 June 2009 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 30 Nov 2009\">{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Clay |title=Metro plans to stand and deliver |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/metro-plans-to-stand-and-deliver-20091130-k18k.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=30 November 2009 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nTransport Minister [[Lynne Kosky]] stated that the Government's A$10.5 billion, 10-year major transport plan, announced in May 2006, had significantly underestimated the usage rates of public transport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gridlock choking life out of city|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/gridlock-choking-life-out-of-city/2007/05/26/1179601737298.html|accessdate=7 June 2013|newspaper=The Age|date=27 May 2007|author=Jason Dowling}}</ref> Original assessments had forecast increases of around 3-4%, far short of the 10% seen year-on-year. The State Government responded by purchasing new trains and introduced a new ticketing option that enabled commuters to pay a reduced fare if their journey finished by 7am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/off-peak-fares-to-cut-crush/news-story/f5271a08b1f22ba72526b73b830a203a|title=Off-peak fares to cut crush|date=2007-09-03|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the Brumby Government announced a $14.1 billion [[Victorian Transport Plan]] to augment Melbourne\u2019s rail network. The plan included:\n\n* The [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]], costing more than $4.5 billion, and consisting of an underground train network \u2014the first new underground rail line since the construction of the [[City Loop]] 25 years earlier\u2014 from Dynon to South Yarra. Aimed at \"relieving overcrowding on the busy suburban lines from Melbourne\u2019s west,\" the underground line was also designed to provide direct rail access to Melbourne University, the Women's Hospital and the Royal Children's Hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/airport-link-15-years-off-in-30b-public-transport-plan-20130327-2guqi.html|title=Airport link 15 years off in $30b public transport plan|author=Richard Willingham|date=28 March 2013|newspaper=The Age|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/under-city-rail-plan-to-cut-melbourne-congestion/story-e6frf7jo-1225770794938|title=Under-city rail plan to cut Melbourne congestion|author=Stephen McMahon|date=9 September 2009|newspaper=The Herald Sun|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref> \n* Rolling stock, $2.65 billion for up to 70 new trains, including 32 \"new generation\" trains which will carry 30 per cent more passengers\n* Rail extensions to Cranbourne East and Mernda, and electrification to Melton.\n* Improvements to train operations, at a cost of $200 million\n* Upgrades to metro stations, costing $50 million, and new stations in growth areas at a cost of $220 million\n* A Park & Ride expansion package costing $60 million.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090516031624/http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/minister-for-public-transport/$14.1-billion-investment-to-move-melbourne-to-a-modern-metro-network.html $14.1 b investment plan]</ref>\n*The previously reduced Early Bird ticket was also made free as part of these changes, following a trial on the Frankston and Sydenham lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/national/free-travel-for-earlybirds/2008/03/07/1204780012433.html|title=Early risers travel free on Melbourne's trains - National - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the investment announcement, the plan for the introduction of more than 200 new weekly train services was released to tackle overcrowding on the city's busiest train lines, a problem that had been attributed to a lack of trains and falling reliability.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/train-jam-relief-plan/2008/04/09/1207420443573.html More trains in railway overhaul], [[The Age]], 9 April 2008</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2009 the State Government announced that they had committed $562.3 million in the 2009 State Budget for the extension of the [[Mernda railway line|Epping line]] 3.5 kilometres north to South Morang. Construction started in 2010 and was completed in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.theage.com.au/breaking-news-national/vic-govt-commits-562m-to-rail-extension-20090501-apt1.html|title=Vic govt commits $562m to rail extension|date=1 May 2009|work=The Age|accessdate=1 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Network development and level crossing removals ===\nIn May 2011, operations commenced on a new metropolitan timetable, rewritten for the first time since 1996 with over 600 additional weekday services added.<ref name=\"Age 19 Jan 2011\">{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Clay |last2=Millar |first2=Royce |title='Confusing' timetable will cut services to west |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/confusing-timetable-will-cut-services-to-west-20110119-19woz.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=19 January 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC 9 May 2011\">{{cite news |title=Train timetable changes 'biggest in a decade' |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-05-09/train-timetable-changes-biggest-in-a-decade/2705216 |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=9 May 2011 |language=en-AU}}</ref> In 2012, a Public Transport Development Authority trading as [[Public Transport Victoria]] (PTV) was established to coordinate, plan and regulate the state's public transport services, including the metropolitan rail system.<ref name=\"Age 29 Nov 2012\">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Adam |title=Government public transport group is secretive and compromised, says lobby president |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/government-public-transport-group-is-secretive-and-compromised-says-lobby-president-20121129-2ahdr.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=29 November 2012 |language=en}}</ref> In the same year, the [[Metcard]] ticketing system was discontinued, completing the controversial network-wide roll-out of the new [[Myki|Myki smart card]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/the-end-is-nigh-for-metcard-20120119-1q8f4.html|title=The end is nigh for Metcard|last=Lucas|first=Clay|date=2012-01-19|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> On 27 March 2013, Public Transport Victoria published its [[Network Development Plan Metropolitan Rail]], detailing a 4-stage plan spread over 20 years to redevelop Melbourne's rail system into a 'metro-style' network, by separating train lines and creating point-to-point lines, upgrading to high-capacity signalling and ordering new trains.<ref name=\"Age 26 Mar 2013\">{{cite news |last1=Gough |first1=Deborah |title=Major rail projects expected in 20 years |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/major-rail-projects-expected-in-20-years-20130327-2gt8r.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=26 March 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:New Noble Park railway station February 2018.jpg|alt=New Noble Park station, 2018|thumb|The new elevated [[Noble Park railway station]], rebuilt in 2018 along with four other stations on the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] railway lines by the Level Crossing Removal Project. The plan removed nine level crossing on the corridor using elevated rail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/first-trains-run-on-melbourne-s-sky-rail-20180211-p4yzyn.html|title=First trains run on Melbourne's sky rail|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2018-02-11|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>]]\nA key campaign promise of the [[First Andrews Ministry|Andrews government]] prior to [[2014 Victorian state election|its election in 2014]] was to remove 50 [[level crossing]]s in 8 years, the most intensive such program in Melbourne's history.<ref name=\"Woodcock and Stone 2016 p13\">{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=Ian |last2=Stone |first2=John |title=The benefits of level crossing removals: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience |date=2016 |isbn=9780734052049 |page=13 |url=http://mams.rmit.edu.au/51zakugpfi4ez.pdf |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Because of Melbourne's generally level topography, the suburban rail network was constructed with a large number of level crossings. By 2014, over 170 remained, due to a lack of funding for grade separations after 1918.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woodcock|first=Ian|last2=Stone|first2=John|date=2016|title=The Benefits of Level Crossing Removal: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience|url=https://researchbank.rmit.edu.au/view/rmit:43926|journal=University of Melbourne/RMIT University|pages=13|via=RMIT Researchgate}}</ref> The Government's [[Level Crossing Removal Project]] became a resounding political success, despite concerns it was creating poor value-for-money infrastructure and controversy about the selection of elevated rail as a method for removing some crossings.<ref name=\"ABC 14 Dec 2017\">{{cite news |last1=Willingham |first1=state political reporter Richard |title=Dangerous level crossings being missed in Victoria, watchdog says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-14/level-crossings-selected-for-removal-in-victoria-questioned/9258178 |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=14 December 2017 |language=en-AU}}</ref> By 2018, 29 level crossings had been fully grade separated, well ahead of the government's original schedule, and a further 25 crossings were added to the program to be completed by 2025.<ref name=\"Age 21 October 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Butt |first1=Craig |last2=Towell |first2=Noel |title=Another 25 rail level crossings to go under Labor pledge |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/25-more-rail-level-crossings-to-go-under-labor-pledge-20181021-p50b07.html |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=21 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The project includes rebuilding or upgrading 27 train stations, such as [[Bentleigh railway station|Bentleigh]] and [[Clayton railway station, Melbourne|Clayton]] railway stations, or laying new track, such as the duplication of 1.2&nbsp;km of single track railway between [[Heidelberg railway station|Heidelberg]] and the rebuilt [[Rosanna railway station|Rosanna]] stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/about|title=About {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Project|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/projects/hurstbridge-rail-line-upgrade|title=Hurstbridge rail line upgrade {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Project|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> Large sections of elevated rail have been built on the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] lines, and further sections are planned for the [[Mernda railway line|Mernda]] and [[Upfield railway line|Upfield]] lines, including a 4&nbsp;km section on the Mernda line in [[Preston, Victoria|Preston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-21/new-melbourne-level-crossing-removals-to-include-sky-rail/10401896|title=Andrews pledges 25 new level crossing removals in Melbourne|last=Longbottom|first=Jessica|date=2018-10-21|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n[[File:Playground under elevated rail at Mernda, Melbourne August 2018.jpg|alt=Elevated rail at Mernda|thumb|323x323px|New elevated rail lines at [[Mernda]] in Melbourne's north, part of an 8&nbsp;km rail extension that opened in August 2018.]]\nThe [[Regional Rail Link]] project, which created a new [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line]] in the city's west with new stations at [[Wyndham Vale railway station|Wyndham Vale]] and [[Tarneit railway station|Tarneit]], as well as adding an additional track pair between [[Sunshine railway station, Melbourne|Sunshine]] and Southern Cross, was completed in mid-2015. Although the project was intended to provide segregated routes for regional trains to Geelong, Ballarat and Bendigo, rapid population growth in areas served by the new line forced these services to perform the role of an outer suburban network, causing significant delays and overcrowding.<ref name=\"Age 10 May 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=Regional Rail Link 'fails' to deliver on extra train services, watchdog says |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/regional-rail-link-fails-to-deliver-all-extra-train-services-promised-watchdog-says-20180510-p4zehc.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=10 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA redesigned network map was released by PTV at the end of 2016, which replaced an emphasis on fare zones with delineation of individual lines and service patterns. The new map also incorporated regional services and was designed to be accessible to passengers with the most common types of [[Color blindness|colour blindness]].<ref name=\"Age 28 Dec 2016\">{{cite news |last1=Dow |first1=Aisha |title=Rainbow revamp for Melbourne's train network map |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/rainbow-revamp-for-melbournes-train-network-map-20161228-gtizab.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=28 December 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMetro's contract to operate the suburban network was renewed in 2017 for a further 7 years. The renegotiated contracts included higher monthly performance targets, which it failed to meet 6 times in the first year of the contract's operation.<ref name=\"ABC 12 Sep 2017\">{{cite news |last1=Willingham |first1=Richard |title=Metro Trains and Yarra Trams win new $7b contracts with tougher targets |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-12/metro-contract-extended-for-melbournes-train-network/8895462 |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=ABC News |date=12 September 2017 |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 3 Jan 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=Metro Trains, Yarra Trams awarded millions in bonuses despite late services |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/metro-trains-yarra-trams-awarded-millions-in-bonuses-despite-late-services-20190103-p50pd7.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=3 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of an extension of the South Morang line to [[Mernda]] commenced in 2016 and was completed on 29 August 2018. The project included 8&nbsp;km of new electrified railway, new stations at [[Middle Gorge railway station|Middle Gorge]] and [[Hawkstowe railway station|Hawkstowe]], and a new terminus at a rebuilt [[Mernda railway station|Mernda station]].<ref name=\"Age 1 Apr 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Matilda |title=Mernda train line ahead of schedule |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/mernda-train-line-ahead-of-schedule-20180401-p4z7by.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=1 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Age 19 Aug 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Webb |first1=Carolyn |title=We did it! Locals board first trains to Mernda in 59 years |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/we-did-it-locals-board-first-trains-to-mernda-in-59-years-20180819-p4zyfb.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=19 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 the Victorian Government announced that Public Transport Victoria would be merged along with [[VicRoads]] into a new Victorian [[Department of Transport (Victoria, 2019\u2013)|Department of Transport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/big-merger-vicroads-and-ptv-to-become-one-mega-agency-20190404-p51arj.html|title=Big merger: VicRoads and PTV to become one mega-agency|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2019-04-04|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Future expansion ==\n[[File:Melbrail former present proposed.svg|320px|thumb|right|Diagram showing Melbourne's passenger rail network, including former and planned lines.]]\n\n=== Metro Tunnel ===\n{{main|Metro Tunnel}}\nIn February 2015, the State Government established the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Authority]] to oversee planning for new twin 9-kilometre rail tunnels through the central city between [[South Kensington railway station|South Kensington station]] and [[South Yarra, Victoria|South Yarra]]. The new Metro Tunnel will have five new underground stations and connect the [[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] lines with the [[Sunbury railway line|Sunbury]] line, creating a new route through the CBD as an alternative to the [[City Loop]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/faq#|title=Frequently asked questions|website=metrotunnel.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> New underground stations will be created at [[Arden railway station, Melbourne|Arden]], [[Parkville railway station|Parkville]], [[Anzac railway station|Domain]] and two new CBD stations, [[State Library railway station|State Library]] and [[Town Hall railway station, Melbourne|Town Hall]]. Enabling works were underway by 2016 and major construction work on the tunnel and stations began in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/cbd-roads-to-be-closed-for-years-as-melbourne-metro-tunnel-construction-begins-20170116-gts2cp.html|title=CBD roads to be closed for years as Melbourne Metro Tunnel construction begins|last=Lucas|first=Aisha Dow, Clay|date=2017-01-16|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> The project has an estimated cost of $11 billion and is scheduled to be complete by 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-metro-a-year-ahead-of-schedule-premier-says-20180221-p4z12d.html|title=Melbourne Metro a year ahead of schedule, Premier says|last=Jacks|first=Timna|date=2018-02-20|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, the State Government ordered 65 new [[High Capacity Metro Trains]] for delivery from mid-2019, which will eventually become the primary rolling stock used in the Metro Tunnel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/new-2-billion-train-deal-to-create-1000-local-jobs-20160912-gre0wj.html|title=New $2 billion train deal to create 1000 local jobs|last=Willingham|first=Richard|date=2016-09-12|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn April, June and July 2019, multiple rail lines in Melbourne's east were shut down for several weeks to allow construction of the tunnel entrances near Kensington and South Yarra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/commuters-warned-of-may-misery-with-replacement-buses-ready-to-roll-20190430-p51iie.html|title=Commuters warned of May misery with replacement buses ready to roll|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2019-04-30|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/more-transport-misery-to-hit-melbourne-commuters-in-july-and-august-20190705-p524fo.html|title=More transport misery to hit Melbourne commuters in July and August|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2019-07-05|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The first tunnel boring machine began to be assembled in North Melbourne in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/massive-metro-tunnel-boring-machines-coming-together/|title=Massive Metro Tunnel Boring Machines Coming Together|date=2019-06-05|website=Premier of Victoria|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Tunnel boring machine|TBM]] Joan completed the first section of the tunnel from Arden to Kensington,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/news/our-first-tunnel-boring-machine-breakthrough|title=Our first tunnel boring machine breakthrough|date=2020-02-23|website=Metro Tunnel Official|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> travelling 1.2 kilometres and installing 4,200 curved concrete segments to create 700 rings lining the walls of the tunnel. Two months later, [[Tunnel boring machine|TBM]] Meg completed the accompanying tunnel, from Arden to Kensington.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://metrotunnel.vic.gov.au/about-the-project/news/our-first-tunnel-boring-machine-breakthrough|title=First section of tunnel completed|date=2020-04-14|website=Metro Tunnel Official|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Airport rail link ===\n{{main|Melbourne Airport rail link}}\nA rail link to [[Melbourne Airport]] has been proposed repeatedly since the airport's construction, with a variety of routes and service models suggested, but construction has never commenced. In July 2018 the Federal and State Governments each pledged A$5 billion (for a total of A$10 billion) to construct a rail link. The Federal Government proposed four preferred routes for the link, with one proposal running via a direct tunnel to [[Highpoint Shopping Centre]] and the others linking to existing stations in Broadmeadows, Flemington or Sunshine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-11/melbourne-airport-rail-link-gets-$5bn-from-federal-government/9643054|title=Turnbull announces $5b funding for Melbourne Airport-CBD rail link|date=2018-04-11|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref> An assessment of the four preferred routes conducted by [[Rail Projects Victoria]] culminated in the route via Sunshine station being selected, with a detailed business case expected by 2020. Construction is expected to start prior to the [[2022 Victorian state election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-22/melbourne-airport-rail-construction-set-to-start-by-2022/10022642|title=Melbourne Airport rail construction set to start by 2022|date=2018-07-22|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n=== Suburban Rail Loop ===\n{{main|Suburban Rail Loop}}\nIn August 2018, in the run-up to the [[2018 Victorian state election]], the State Government pledged $300 million to complete a business case and secure funding to construct a new railway through suburban Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/aug/28/massive-melbourne-suburban-train-loop-pledged-by-victorian-government|title=Massive Melbourne suburban train loop pledged by Victorian government|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|date=2018-08-28|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref> The project is designed to link major activity centres and amenities such as hospitals, shopping centres, universities, and Melbourne Airport. The proposal would connect most existing railway lines through middle suburbs and enable easier intra-suburban travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-28/melbourne-suburban-train-loop-promised-by-labor/10172184|title=Melbourne's $50b rail loop the 'biggest public transport project in history'|date=2018-08-28|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nThe Suburban Rail Loop (SRL) would connect the existing station at [[Cheltenham railway station, Melbourne|Cheltenham]] with other existing stations at [[Clayton railway station, Melbourne|Clayton]], [[Glen Waverley railway station|Glen Waverley]], Box Hill, Heidelberg, [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], Fawkner, Broadmeadows, Sunshine and Werribee. It will also link to new stations to be built in areas that have long been promised rail connections, including [[Monash University, Clayton campus|Monash University]], Burwood, Doncaster, Bundoora and Melbourne Airport. Construction is scheduled to begin on the first stage from Cheltenham to Box Hill by 2022 with other sections progressively opening until the full line is operational by 2050.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-what-readers-think-20180828-p5006z.html|title=Melbourne suburban rail loop: What readers think|last=Koob|first=Simone Fox|date=2018-08-28|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-29/victorian-rail-suburban-loop-plan-divides-experts/10179340|title='A mega project on steroids': Experts divided on Melbourne rail loop plan|date=2018-08-29|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n=== Other planned extensions ===\n{{Main|Proposed Melbourne rail extensions}}\nThe State Government is currently preparing a business case for electrification and extension of the [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] to [[Baxter railway station|Baxter]] in Melbourne's South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://transport.vic.gov.au:443/getting-around/public-transport/baxter-electrification-business-case|title=Baxter electrification business case|last=Department of Economic Development|first=Jobs|website=transport.vic.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> The Federal Government committed $225 million towards the project in its 2017-2018 budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/guy-turnbull-all-aboard-the-450-million-baxter-rail-link-20180716-p4zrsw.html|title=Guy, Turnbull all aboard the $450 million Baxter rail link|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2018-07-16|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018 Victorian state election, the State Government also announced its Western Rail Plan, which would quadruplicate and electrify the rail lines to [[Melton railway station, Melbourne|Melton]] and [[Wyndham Vale railway station|Wyndham Vale]], allowing Metro services.<ref name=\"Build\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/western-rail-plan|title=Western Rail Plan|last=Build|first=Victoria's Big|date=2018-11-01|website=bigbuild.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> Under this plan, Metro and [[V/Line|V/Line regional services]] would be separated, allowing for higher speed trains to be introduced to [[Geelong V/Line rail service|Geelong]] and [[Ballarat V/Line rail service|Ballarat]]. A new connection between Sunshine and Southern Cross Station to be built as part of the Airport rail link could add extra capacity for regional and metro lines.<ref name=\"Build\"/> According to the Government, these lines could be fully electrified to Geelong and Ballarat and run at speeds of up to 250&nbsp;km/h, significantly above the 160&nbsp;km/h limit of current [[V/Line VLocity|V/Line VLocity trains]].<ref name=\"Jacks\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/geelong-to-melbourne-in-45-minutes-under-labor-s-regional-rail-plan-20181016-p509uu.html|title=Geelong to Melbourne in 45 minutes under Labor's regional rail plan|last=Jacks|first=Timna|date=2018-10-15|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> Planning for the fast rail and electrification of the lines to Melton and Wyndham Vale will occur alongside planning for the Airport rail link, with construction set to start by 2022.<ref name=\"Jacks\"/>\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n\n=== Railway ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; clear: right; width: 400px\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Route length of Melbourne rail network in km (2012)<ref name=\"BITRE urban rail\">{{cite book |title=Understanding Australia's urban railways |date=2012 |publisher=Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics |location=Canberra |page=4 |url=https://bitre.gov.au/publications/2012/files/report_131.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019 |ref={{sfnref|BITRE|2012}}}}</ref>\n|-\n| Passenger only\n| 234\n|-\n| Freight only\n| 66\n|-\n| Shared passenger and freight\n| 196\n|-\n|\n|\n|-\n| Electrified\n| 359\n|-\n| Not electrified\n| 137\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Total\n| 496\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<!-- Don't attempt to combine these figures; that would be original research. --> {{small|Since 2012, the [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line|Deer Park\u2013West Werribee line]] (27 km) has opened to traffic and the former South Morang line has been extended to [[Mernda railway station]] (8 km).<ref name=\"Trainline 6\">{{cite book |title=Trainline 6 |date=2018 |publisher=Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics |page=125 |url=https://bitre.gov.au/publications/2018/files/train_006.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n|}\nThe rail network within the Melbourne metropolitan area includes dedicated passenger lines, dedicated freight lines, and lines shared by the two types of traffic. Nearly all passenger traffic and some intrastate freight operates on {{track gauge|victorian|allk=on}}, while all interstate and much intrastate freight traffic operates on {{track gauge|sg|allk=on}}. As a consequence, freight and passenger operations are almost completely segregated in the metropolitan area.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=34}}\n\nMost suburban passenger lines operated by the metropolitan rail franchisee, currently [[Metro Trains Melbourne]], are [[Electrification (rail)|electrified]] with 1500 [[volt|V]] [[direct current|DC]] [[overhead catenary]]. Many of the suburban lines share tracks with regional passenger trains operated by [[V/Line]], and some V/Line services provide \"peri-urban\" service to areas of Melbourne not reached by the electrified network.<ref name=\"VAGO 2017\">{{cite book |title=V/Line Passenger Services |date=August 2017 |publisher=Victorian Auditor-General's Office |location=Melbourne |page=37 |url=https://www.audit.vic.gov.au/sites/default/files/2017-08/20170809-VLine-Passenger-Services.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Metro also operates an isolated section of unelectrified passenger line between [[Frankston railway station|Frankston]] and [[Stony Point railway station|Stony Point]].{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=36}}\n\nThe network is centred on Flinders Street and Southern Cross stations in the CBD, which are joined directly by a six-track viaduct and indirectly by the underground four-track [[City Loop]]. From this central core, nearly all tracks pass through the three major junction stations of [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]], [[Jolimont railway station|Jolimont]], and [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Richmond]]; and from there extend outwards to the west, north-east and east of the city respectively. There are few connections between the radial lines outside of the central city.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=35}} Capital investment in the network since 1990 has focused on relieving \"bottlenecks\" near the central core caused by the large number of lines converging, most significantly with the [[Regional Rail Link]] project which provided additional capacity between [[Sunshine railway station, Melbourne|Sunshine]] and the city.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|pp=36\u201337}}\n\n[[File:Melbourne-signalling-stanchions.jpg|thumb|Quadruple track near [[Caulfield railway station|Caulfield station]], showing [[railway signalling|signalling]] and [[overhead lines#Overhead catenary|overhead wiring]]]]\nMuch of the metropolitan network is [[Double-track railway|double track]] or multiple pairs of tracks. There are small sections of [[Triple-track railway|triple track]], which are used to allow express trains to overtake stopping trains in peak hour. Nearly the entirety of the [[Altona railway line, Melbourne|Altona]], [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] and Stony Point branches are single track, and many of the outer suburban passenger lines also have sections of single track, usually where demand for frequent services is low.{{sfn|BITRE|2012|p=36}}\n\nThe metropolitan network has a large number of [[level crossings]]. Many have been gradually removed by [[grade separation|grade separating]] road and rail traffic: by 2016, some 228 grade separations had been undertaken in the Melbourne area, leaving 170 level crossings, although very few projects of this nature had been undertaken in the latter half of the 20th century. The [[Level Crossing Removal Project]], which began in 2014, aimed to increase the rate of level crossing removals to over 6 each year for at least 8 years, and the project was later extended for a further four years.<ref name=\"Woodcock and Stone 2016\">{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=Ian |last2=Stone |first2=John |title=The benefits of level crossing removals: lessons from Melbourne's historical experience |date=2016 |page=13 |url=http://mams.rmit.edu.au/51zakugpfi4ez.pdf |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stations ===\n{{main|List of railway stations in Melbourne}}\nThere are 218 stations in Melbourne, operated by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]].\n\n==== Passenger information ====\n{{anchor|PRIDE}}\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Pridebox-Melbourne.jpg|PRIDE Talking Box panel at [[East Camberwell railway station|East Camberwell]] station\nFile:2 Line PID Boards Metlink.png|A diagram of a two-line LED {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}\nFile:CRT TV Information Metlink.png|A diagram of a CRT {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}} screen pair\nFile:PRIDE II Talking Box Next Trains Announcement at Ginifer.ogg|PRIDE II Talking Box, detailing departures from [[Ginifer railway station|Ginifer]] station\nFile:Network status board.jpg|A network status board at [[Highett railway station|Highett station]]\n</gallery>\n\nTimetable information is available to passengers at stations through the '''PRIDE II''' system, which is an [[Electronics|electronic]] [[Public transport timetable|timetable]] and announcement system, and stands for Passenger Real-time Information Dissemination Equipment. The system consists of:\n* The control system, situated at [[Metrol, Melbourne rail network|Metrol]].\n* Control stations, at which staff update information, and announcements and CCTV recordings are dealt with for nearby stations.\n* [[Public address]] systems at each station on the network. The PRIDE system automatically announces when a train is due soon, delayed, or cancelled; this is done via the rail telephone network.\n* PRIDE \"talking boxes\" installed on each platform of all stations.\n* Electronic information displays.\n\nControl data comes from two locations: Metrol, and control stations. Next train data and times are automatically updated by the train control systems, with manual overrides also possible.\n\nAll stations are provided with \"talking boxes\" which have two buttons and a small [[loudspeaker|speaker]].\nThe green button, when pressed, contacts the PRIDE controller over the rail telephone network, identifying itself by the [[dual-tone multi-frequency|DTMF]] tones that correspond to the ID number assigned to the box. The system then reads out times and destinations for the next two services to depart that platform (or, in the case of stations with a single island platform with departures either side, both platforms). The red button when pressed, gives the user two way communication with the closest control station.\n\nBusy stations are often provided with an electronic [[light-emitting diode|LED]] {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}s, which indicate the destination, time, stopping pattern summary, and minutes to departure for the next train on the platform.\n\nStations on the [[City Loop]], in addition to [[North Melbourne railway station|North Melbourne]], [[Richmond railway station, Melbourne|Richmond]], and [[Box Hill railway station, Melbourne|Box Hill]] stations, have [[cathode ray tube|CRT]] screen {{Tooltip|PID|Passenger Information Display}}s, although some of these have recently been replaced by [[widescreen]] [[liquid crystal display|LCD]] screens. These displays show in detail the destination, scheduled and actual departure time, and all stations the next train stops at. Also shown is the destination and time of the following train, and the system is capable of providing suggested connections and warn of service interruptions.\n\nOn Sunday, 26 September 2010, the PRIDE system was upgraded with new voice announcements. The voice is now female, and now advises to touch on and off when using Myki.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metro Trains go female|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tgr0STnslIA|work=Video|accessdate=28 September 2010}}{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the Bayside Rail Upgrade, stations on the [[Frankston railway line|Frankston line]] will receive new \"network status boards\". These LCD screens provide travel information on all of Melbournes 16 railway lines as well as tram & bus services, including delays, replacement services or planned disruptions.<ref>[http://ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/bayside-rail-project/network-status-boards/ Network Status Boards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915072650/http://ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/bayside-rail-project/network-status-boards/ |date=15 September 2014 }} Public Transport Victoria</ref>\n\n=== Safeworking ===\n[[File:Signal-and-train-stop-melbourne.jpg|thumb|A signal with associated train stop in the raised position to the right]]\n\nMost lines in Melbourne operate under an automatic block system of safeworking with three-position power signalling. This permits [[Railway signal|signals]] to operate automatically with the passage of trains, enforcing the distance between them. At junctions signals are manually controlled from [[signal box]]es, with [[interlocking]]s used to ensure conflicting paths are not set. The [[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse line]] has two-position automatic signalling, a variant of the three-position system.\n\nThe outer end of the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]] used to be operated with [[Token (railway signalling)|token based systems]] and two-position manual signalling, where access to the line is based upon possession of a token. It was dismantled in 2013.\n\n[[Train stop]]s are used to enforce stop indications on signals\u2014should a train pass a signal, the train's brakes will automatically be applied. Trains are also fitted with [[pilot valve]]s, a form of [[dead man's switch]] that applies the brakes should the driver fail to maintain a foot or hand pilot valve in a set position.<ref name=\"safe\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.doi.vic.gov.au/Doi/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/0C6245228F9F50A3CA2570AE0012723F?OpenDocument\n |title       = Rail system safety\n |work        = Department of Infrastructure website\n |accessdate  = 22 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090520043834/http://www.doi.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/0C6245228F9F50A3CA2570AE0012723F?OpenDocument\n |archivedate = 20 May 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The \"VICERS\" [[Dead-man's vigilance device|vigilance control]] and [[event recorder]] system is also being currently fitted to suburban trains to provide an additional level of safety.<ref name=\"safe\" />\n\n=== Train control ===\nThe main control room for the rail network is [[Metrol, Melbourne rail network|Metrol]]. Located in the Melbourne CBD, it controls [[railway signalling|signals]] in the inner suburbs, tracking the location of all trains, as well as the handling the distribution of real time passenger information, and manages disruptions to the timetable. Additional signal boxes are located throughout the network, and in direct communication with Metrol.\n\n===Terminology===\nThe railways in Melbourne generally use British-derived terminology. For example:\n* '''Up''' refers to the direction \"towards Melbourne\".\n* '''Down''' refers to the direction \"away from Melbourne\", or \"towards the country\".\n* '''Points''' refers to what are known as [[railroad switch]]es, or crossovers in American English.\n* '''Signal box''' refers to the signal control installation ('''tower''' in American terminology).\n* '''Gunzel''' termanology for a railway enthusiast\n\n==Suburban services==\n{{main|Metro Trains Melbourne}}\n\n{{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-lat=-37.8115\n|frame-long=144.9685\n|frame-width=800\n|frame-height=600\n|frame-align=center\n|text=Interactive map showing suburban lines of the Melbourne metropolitan rail network, including the under construction [[Metro Tunnel]] in grey.\n|zoom=12\n\n|type=line\n|id=Q4787948\n|stroke-colour=#7F7F7F\n|stroke-width=5\n|title=Metro Tunnel (under construction)\n\n|type2=line\n|id2=Q7567980\n|stroke-colour2=#E42B23\n|stroke-width2=5\n|title2=Mernda line\n\n|type3=line\n|id3=Q16927215\n|stroke-colour3=#E42B23\n|stroke-width3=5\n|title3=Hurstbridge line\n\n|type4=line\n|id4=Q6548623\n|stroke-colour4=#094B8D\n|stroke-width4=5\n|title4=Lilydale line\n\n|type5=line\n|id5=Q4705897\n|stroke-colour5=#094B8D\n|stroke-width5=5\n|title5=Alamein line\n\n|type6=line\n|id6=Q4882690\n|stroke-colour6=#094B8D\n|stroke-width6=5\n|title6=Belgrave line\n\n|type7=line\n|id7=Q5568092\n|stroke-colour7=#094B8D\n|stroke-width7=5\n|title7=Glen Waverley line\n\n|type8=line\n|id8=Q5492274\n|stroke-colour8=#149943\n|stroke-width8=5\n|title8=Frankston line\n\n|type9=line\n|id9=Q7125454\n|stroke-colour9=#16B4E8\n|stroke-width9=5\n|title9=Pakenham line\n\n|type10=line\n|id10=Q5181939\n|stroke-colour10=#16B4E8\n|stroke-width10=5\n|title10=Cranbourne line\n\n|type11=line\n|id11=Q7416840\n|stroke-colour11=#FC7EBB\n|stroke-width11=5\n|title11=Sandringham line\n\n|type12=line\n|id12=Q7983583\n|stroke-colour12=#149943\n|stroke-width12=5\n|title12=Werribee line\n\n|type13=line\n|id13=Q8021313\n|stroke-colour13=#149943\n|stroke-width13=5\n|title13=Williamstown line\n\n|type14=line\n|id14=Q7639008\n|stroke-colour14=#FFB531\n|stroke-width14=5\n|title14=Sunbury line\n\n|type15=line\n|id15=Q7898275\n|stroke-colour15=#FFB531\n|stroke-width15=5\n|title15=Upfield line\n\n|type16=line\n|id16=Q5181702\n|stroke-colour16=#FFB531\n|stroke-width16=5\n|title16=Craigieburn line\n\n}}\n\n===Operations===\nDespite initially being constructed and operated as private railways in the 1850s, following the establishment of the government-owned [[Victorian Railways]] in 1858 Melbourne's suburban railway system has been state operated for the majority of its existence. In the 1920s Victorian Railways was the operator of the world's busiest train station ([[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]]) and one of the world's busiest railway networks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4717137|title=WORLD'S BUSIEST STATION.|date=1922-01-11|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2018-04-28|pages=15}}</ref> Following several high-profile collisions in the early 20th century, a number of network safety processes were implemented by the operator to improve passenger safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museumsvictoria.com.au/railways/theme.aspx?lvl=2&IRN=508|title=Victorian Railways, Museum Victoria, Australia|last=Victoria|first=Museum|website=museumsvictoria.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe agency name was shortened to [[Victorian Railways|VicRail]] in the early 1980s and then, later in the decade, the metropolitan system became known as Metropolitan Transit ('[[Metlink|The Met]]') and the regional system became known as V/Line. In preparation for privatisation the suburban system was split into Bayside Trains and Hillside Trains by the [[Kennett Ministry]] in 1997. Privatisation was completed in 1999 and [[M-Train]] and [[Connex Melbourne]] won the tender to operate Bayside, and Hillside trains, respectively. Following M>Train's inability to renegotiate financial arrangements, in 2004 Connex Melbourne assumed responsibility for the entire network. Current operations are provided by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]], an [[MTR Corporation]] joint venture.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arhsvic.org.au/component/content/article/2-general/32-railway-history-in-victoria-1950-now|title=Victorian Railways History 1975 - 1999|date=2017|website=Australian Railway Historical Society Victorian Division Inc.|access-date=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Operator Timelines'''\n*'''1854\u20131860''' - Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company\n*'''1854\u20131878''' - Melbourne and Hobsons Bay Railway Company\n*'''1857\u20131862''' - Melbourne and Suburban Railway Company\n*'''1858\u20131983''' - [[Victorian Railways]] ('VicRail')\n*'''1983\u20131997''' - Metropolitan Transit ('The Met')\n*'''1997\u20131999''' - Bayside Trains (Caulfield and Northern groups) and Hillside Trains (Clifton Hill and Burnley groups, Showgrounds services)\n*'''1999\u20132004''' - [[M-Train|M>Train]] (formerly Bayside Trains) and [[Connex Melbourne]] (formerly Hillside Trains)\n*'''2004\u20132009''' - Connex Melbourne \n*'''2009\u2013present''' - [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]\n\n=== Fleet ===\n\n==== Current fleet ====\nThe majority of the current suburban train fleet in Melbourne is owned by [[VicTrack]], with the train operator (currently [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]) responsible for maintaining the fleet.<ref name=\"doiwho\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/B324F53A00F987B9CA2571F50007F1BB?OpenDocument|title=Department of Transport: Who's who in Victoria's public transport network|publisher=Department of Transport, State Government of Victoria, Australia|accessdate=14 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523081606/http://www.transport.vic.gov.au/DOI/Internet/transport.nsf/AllDocs/B324F53A00F987B9CA2571F50007F1BB?OpenDocument|archive-date=23 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> All trains on the Melbourne suburban network are electric and driver-only operated. Guards on suburban trains were discontinued between 1993 and 1995.<ref name=\"vrhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/history.html|title=VR History|publisher=victorianrailways.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530050949/http://www.victorianrailways.net/vr%20history/history.html|archivedate=30 May 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nAll trains are fitted with power-operated sliding doors which are closed by the driver, but opened by passengers. The doors of newer model [[X'Trapolis 100]] and Siemens trains are opened electronically with a button, whilst Comeng trains are slid manually using handles. Trains are fitted with air conditioning, closed-circuit cameras, and emergency intercom systems. Trains are fixed into three car units and may operate alone or in pairs.  All three train types in operation are unable to operate coupled to another type.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vicsig.net/suburban/fleet|title=VICSIG|website=vicsig.net|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref><gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Melboure Comeng 381M Metro.jpg|Comeng train\nFile:Siemens train in Metro Trains Melbourne Livery.jpg|Siemens train\nFile:Metro-liveried-XTrapolis-train-863M.jpg|X'Trapolis 100 train\n</gallery>\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n!Names\n!Alternate names\n!Entered service\n!Number built\n!Key information\n|-\n|[[Comeng (train)|Comeng]]\n|\n|1981-1988\n|95 (6 carriage)\n|Named as a 'Commonwealth Engineering' portmanteau. Refurbished 2000-2003 by [[EDI Rail]] and [[Alstom]]. Feature power operated doors that must be pulled open by hand but are closed automatically by the driver. First trains to feature air conditioning.\n|-\n|[[Siemens Nexas|Siemens]]\n|Siemens Nexas\n|2003-2006\n|72 (3 carriage)\n|Refurbished with seat removals and extra railings since 2016. The first and only openly articulated trains with passengers able to move between carriages without opening any doors. Frequent overrunning caused lawsuits and disruptions to fix alleged braking faults.\n|-\n|[[X'Trapolis 100|X'Trapolis]]\n|\n|2002-2004<br />2009\u2013present\n|180 (3 carriage)<br />+32 under construction\n|Body shells built in France, remaining assembled in Ballarat. Eight separate orders have been lodged for X'Trapolis trains. Remodelled since 2009 with 2+2 seat configurations to increase passenger capacity/flow.\n|-\n|[[High Capacity Metro Trains]]\n|\n|2019\n| +65 under construction\n|For use on Melbourne Metro Rail Project line. Built in [[Changchun]], [[China]] and Victoria using 60% local content. Currently in testing only, due to enter service mid-2020<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/new-2-billion-train-deal-to-create-1000-local-jobs-20160911-gre0wj.html|title=New $2 billion train deal to create 1000 local jobs|date=12 September 2016|newspaper=The Age}}</ref><ref>[http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/1100-jobs-with-65-new-trains-built-in-victoria-for-victoria/ 1,100 Jobs with 65 New Trains Built in Victoria, For Victoria] Premier of Victoria 12 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/evolution-rail-to-supply-melbourne-high-capacity-emus.html Evolution Rail to supply Melbourne high capacity EMUs] ''Railway Gazette International'' 12 September 2016</ref>\n|}\n\n==== Decommissioned fleet ====\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n!Name\n!Alternate names\n!Entered service\n!Retired service\n!Number built\n!Key information\n|-\n|[[Swing Door (train)|Swing Door]]\n|Dog Box\n|1887\n|c.1959-1970\n|294\n|Named after the outward swinging carriage doors. Converted to electric traction from 1917.\n|-\n|[[Tait (train)|Tait]]\n|Reds, Red Rattlers\n|1910\n|1974-1984\n|623\n|Named after [[Thomas James Tait|Sir Thomas James Tait]], Chairman of Commissioners of the Victorian Railways. Converted to electric traction from 1919. Banned from the City Loop due to the fire hazard of wooden frames.\n|-\n|[[Harris (train)|Harris]]\n|Blues\n|1956\n|1988-1994\n|436\n|Named after [[Norman Charles Harris]], Chairman of Commissioners of the Victorian Railways. Most contained asbestos and were buried in Clayton in the 1980s; 16 were refurbished, of those 10 were included in the conversion of 59 vehicles to [[V/Line H type carriage|H type carriages]] for shorter distance country services. Four motors preserved; one each original and refurbished as static exhibits at Newport Railway Museum, and two pending restoration at Newport Workshops.\n|-\n|[[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]]\n|Martin & King, Stainless Steel\n|1972\n|2003-2014\n|118&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;3 carriage sets\n|Named due to the design by Hitachi, despite no Hitachi components. The last Melbourne trains not to have air conditioning. Three Hitachi motor carriages form part of the restaurant Easey's in Collingwood.\n|}\n\n==== Classification and configuration ====\n{{Update|date=February 2018|updated=June 2014}}\n<!-- NOTE: The heading of this section is linked to in articles about the different train types, so should not be changed without updating those links.  -->\n\nSince shortly after the introduction of suburban electric trains in Melbourne, their carriages have been classified as follows. All fleet types have used these classifications, with different fleet types using different number ranges for the carriages.\n\n*'''M''' indicates a motorised carriage, with a driving compartment.\n*'''T''' indicates a trailer carriage.\n*'''D''' indicated a trailer carriage with a driving compartment. Only Swing-door, Tait, and Hitachi trains had these.\n*'''G''' indicated a trailer carriage fitted with both gas and electric lighting, for use on country services. Only Tait trains had these.\n*'''BT''' indicated a second class trailer carriage. Prior to the abolition of first class suburban travel in 1958, motorised carriage were generally second class and trailer carriages were generally first class.\n\nAn exception to the above classifications was the [[4D (train)|trial double-deck]] train, which used '''T''' to indicate a trailer carriage with a driving compartment, and '''M''' to indicate a motorised carriage without a driving compartment.\n\nCurrently, all trains are assembled into a symmetrical '''M-T-M''' arrangement. Trains comprise either one or two such units. All peak period services and some off-peak services comprise two units. The now retired [[Hitachi (Australian train)|Hitachi]] trains operated in fixed two-unit sets.\n\n=== Lines ===\nMelbourne's suburban network includes 16 electrified lines and 1 non-electrified line.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many lines have been lengthened over time, most notably the [[Mernda railway line|Mernda line]] from [[Epping railway station, Melbourne|Epping]] to [[South Morang railway station|South Morang]] in 2012 and again to [[Mernda railway station|Mernda]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://levelcrossings.vic.gov.au/projects/mernda-rail-extension-project|title=Mernda rail extension project {{!}} Level Crossing Removal Authority|website=levelcrossings.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Lines have also changed terminus or layout, including the forthcoming changes to the Cranbourne, Pakenham and Sunbury lines as part of the [[Melbourne Metro Rail Project]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/projects/rail-projects/Works-to-transform-the-Cranbourne-Pakenham-corridor/|title=Works to transform the Cranbourne Pakenham corridor|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Numerous [[Proposed Melbourne rail extensions|proposals for new lines or extensions]] not yet constructed have been made, including the long-outstanding [[Doncaster railway line]] and [[Melbourne Airport rail link]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/apr/12/turnbull-puts-up-5bn-for-melbourne-airport-rail-link|title=Turnbull puts up $5bn for Melbourne airport rail link|last=Davey|first=Melissa|date=2018-04-12|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Electrified lines ====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Alamein railway line]]\n*[[Belgrave railway line]]\n*[[Craigieburn railway line]]\n*[[Cranbourne railway line]]\n*[[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse/Showgrounds railway line]]\n*[[Frankston railway line]]\n*[[Glen Waverley railway line]]\n*[[Hurstbridge railway line]]\n*[[Lilydale railway line]]\n*[[Mernda railway line]]\n*[[Pakenham railway line]]\n*[[Sandringham railway line]]\n*[[Sunbury railway line]]\n*[[Upfield railway line]]\n*[[Werribee railway line]]\n*[[Williamstown railway line]]\n*[[City Loop]] (incorporated into several other lines)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Non-electrified lines ====\n*[[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line]] (non-electrified train service operated by V/Line)\n*[[Melton railway line]] (non-electrified train service operated by V/Line)\n*[[Stony Point railway line]] (non-electrified train service beyond Frankston)\n\n===== Stony Point line and metropolitan V/Line services =====\n[[Stony Point railway line|Stony Point]] line services operate as shuttles from [[Frankston railway station|Frankston]] station with passengers to and from [[Flinders Street railway station|Flinders Street]] required to change trains. It is the only non-electrified line operated by Metro Trains, with services being operated using [[V/Line Sprinter|Sprinter]] diesel multiple units leased from [[V/Line]].\n\n[[Melton railway line|Melton (Ballarat line)]] and [[Deer Park\u2013West Werribee railway line|Wyndham Vale (Geelong line)]] services are operated by [[V/Line]] and depart from [[Southern Cross railway station|Southern Cross]], but are within the metropolitan ticketing zone. Bacchus Marsh/Melton/Ballarat trains stop at Rockbank, Caroline Springs, Deer Park and Ardeer. Wyndham Vale/Geelong trains also stop at Ardeer and Deer Park, along with Tarneit. Only Wyndham Vale and Ballarat trains stop at Ardeer, not Geelong trains.\n\n5 morning peak and 3 afternoon peak trains operate to and from Wyndham Vale. One weekday morning service and numerous football services operate to Wyndham Vale.\n\nFrequent peak hour trains operate to and from Bacchus Marsh and Melton. Since 2015, weekday hourly trains have also operated to Bacchus Marsh. On top of Ballarat trains stopping here, Bacchus Marsh residents have half hourly services to the city.\n\nOn weekdays, Geelong and Ballarat trains run express after Tarneit and Melton respectively, with Wyndham Vale, Bacchus Marsh and Melton trains stopping between Rockbank and Sunshine. On weekends, these stations are serviced by Ballarat trains.\n\nSunbury services used to also be operated by V/Line until 2012 when the electrical network was extended to Sunbury and these trains also stopped at Diggers Rest; Sunbury passengers can still catch V/Line trains to or from Bendigo. The redundant carriages were moved onto Bacchus Marsh services instead. V/Line trains used to also operate to Donnybrook, stopping at Craigieburn but since the electrical network was extended to Craigieburn in 2007, trains have stopped terminating at Donnybrook.\n\n=== Service patterns ===\n{{main|Metro Trains Melbourne#Service patterns}}\nSuburban services are operated by [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]. Railway lines and service patterns are often classified into groups, which are:\n*Burnley group\n**[[Lilydale railway line|Lilydale]], [[Belgrave railway line|Belgrave]], [[Alamein railway line|Alamein]] and [[Glen Waverley railway line|Glen Waverley]] line (blue)\n*Caulfield group\n**[[Pakenham railway line|Pakenham]] and [[Cranbourne railway line|Cranbourne]] line (light blue)\n**[[Sandringham railway line|Sandringham]] line (pink)\n*Clifton Hill group\n**[[Mernda railway line|Mernda]] and [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge]] line (red)\n*Northern group\n**[[Sunbury railway line|Sunbury]], [[Craigieburn railway line|Craigieburn]] and [[Upfield railway line|Upfield]] line (yellow)\n*Cross-City group\n**[[Frankston railway line|Frankston]], [[Werribee railway line|Werribee]] and [[Williamstown railway line|Williamstown]] line (green)\n**[[Stony Point railway line|Stony Point]] line (non-electrified train service beyond Frankston)\n*Special event services\n**[[Flemington Racecourse railway line|Flemington Racecourse/Showgrounds]]\n\nMost of the above lines travel along the [[City Loop]], and as some trains change to service other lines at their terminus, others may run through the City Loop incidentally. The Frankston line does not travel along the City Loop on off-peak weekdays, but does so during the peak and weekends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/getting-around/maps/metropolitan-trains/view/6/|title=Metropolitan trains|website=www.ptv.vic.gov.au|language=English|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nMelbourne uses [[clock-face scheduling]] in off-peak periods, but generally not in [[rush hour]], due to the network operating near to infrastructure capacity and having to accommodate single-line sections, flat junctions, and regional diesel-hauled trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/metro-warns-of-capacity-crunch-within-two-years-on-some-train-lines-20170704-gx4giy.html|title=Metro warns of capacity crunch within two years on some train lines|last=Carey|first=Adam|date=2017-07-04|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> Frequencies vary according to time of day, day of week and by line. In some places, usually [[interchange station]]s, services on two lines combine to provide more frequent services on common sections of tracks. All services become 24-hour from Friday morning to Sunday evening, with at least one departure every hour after 12am.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlong with other Australian railways, Melbourne uses the British terminology of \"[[rail terminology#U|up]]\" and \"[[rail terminology#D|down]]\", with \"up\" being defined as toward Flinders Street station in the CBD.\n\n=== Fares and tickets ===\n{{main|myki}}\n\nThe [[myki]] [[smart card|smart-card]] ticketing system is the main ticketing system currently in use across Melbourne, introduced in 2010. Prior to December 2012 Melbourne also used a magnetic strip [[paper ticket]] system known as the [[Metcard]], first introduced to the railway network in 1996. On 29 December 2012 Metcard was no longer available for use on Melbourne's public transport and completely replaced by myki. Multi-modal tickets were first introduced in Melbourne in 1969 and prior to this train, tram and bus services all had separated ticketing systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/intro.htm|title=Melbourne's Multi-Modal Based Ticketing Systems 1969 to present|website=www.robx1.net|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Host stations and premium stations ===\nHost stations and premium stations are categories of railway stations on the suburban rail network. A premium station is staffed from first train to last, seven days a week, while a host station is staffed only during the morning peak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Melbourne Train Network |url=https://www.metrotrains.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/PTV_M_Train_Network-Map_A4P_JAN_2016_HR.pdf |publisher=Public Transport Victoria |accessdate=2019-12-01}}</ref> Of the 207 stations in [[Melbourne]]'s railway network, there are 82 premium stations, in addition to the five [[City Loop]] stations.\n\nAlthough plans for the premium station program were unveiled in 1991 (under the guise of 'Safe Stations'),<ref name=\"newsrailnov91\">{{cite magazine |date=November 1991 |title=General News |magazine=Newsrail |publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society |page=364}}</ref> the program was commenced in 1994 by the [[Public Transport Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/metcard/html/history.htm |title=Metcard - A brief history |publisher=robx1.net |accessdate=2008-03-27}}</ref> with [[Mount Waverley railway station|Mount Waverley]] being the first station given premium status.<ref name=\"Newsrail\">{{cite magazine |date=October 1997 |title=Upgrading Eltham to a Premium Station |magazine=Newsrail |publisher=Australian Railway Heritage Society (Victorian Division) |page=310}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mount Waverley |url=http://www.vicsig.net/index.php?page=infrastructure&name=Mount%20Waverley |work=VICSIG |accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref> By the end of 1995 the number of staffed stations increased from 35 to 51.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robx1.net/victkt/metcard/html/premium.htm |title=Metcard - Premium stations |publisher=robx1.net |accessdate=2008-03-27}}</ref> It was proposed to upgraded further stations to premium status in the future.\n\nThe host station program was introduced by the [[Government of Victoria (Australia)|Victorian Department of Transport]] in the early 2000s to ensure that over 80% of suburban rail passengers started their journey from a staffed (host or premium) station.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Regional services==\n{{Main|V/Line}}\n[[V/Line]] [[List of regional railway stations in Victoria|regional services]] share tracks with several suburban train lines from the outskirts of Melbourne to the regional railway terminus at Southern Cross station (with the [[Traralgon V/Line rail service]] terminating at Flinders Street station). The Pakenham line has the longest shared track section which is used by V/Line services to the [[Latrobe Valley]]. The Werribee, Sunbury and Craigieburn lines also share lesser sections of track with counterpart suburban lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/opinion/how-decades-of-neglect-ran-the-vline-network-off-the-rails-20160120-gm9td5.html|title=How decades of neglect ran the V/Line network off the rails|last=Morton|first=Tony|date=2016-01-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Regional Rail Link]] project aimed to separate suburban services from all regional trains, except those to the North-East and the Latrobe Valley. A ceremonial start of construction was held in August 2009 and the project was completed in June 2015.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.railgeelong.com/gallery/events/rrl-first-sod\n|title=Regional Rail Link - turning of the first sod\n|work=Rail Geelong - Gallery\n|publisher=railgeelong.com\n|accessdate=29 August 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/premier/construction-starts-on-the-$4.3-billion-regional-rail-link.html\n |title       = CONSTRUCTION STARTS ON THE $4.3 BILLION REGIONAL RAIL LINK\n |work        = Media Release: Premier of Victoria\n |publisher   = premier.vic.gov.au\n |date        = 27 August 2009\n |accessdate  = 29 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090904223051/http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/premier/construction-starts-on-the-$4.3-billion-regional-rail-link.html\n |archivedate = 4 September 2009\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n\n==Freight services==\n[[File:Melbourne-steel-terminal.jpg|thumb|[[NR class]] locomotive at the Melbourne Steel Terminal, off Footscray Road]]\n{{Main|Freight railways in Melbourne}}\n\nMelbourne also has an extensive network of railway lines and yards to serve freight traffic. The lines are of two gauges\u2014{{RailGauge|5ft3in}} [[Victorian broad gauge|broad gauge]] and {{RailGauge|ussg}} [[standard gauge]], and are not electrified. In the inner western suburbs of the city, freight trains operate on dedicated lines, but in other areas freight trains share tracks with the suburban [[Metro Trains Melbourne]] and regional [[V/Line]] passenger services. The majority of freight terminals are located in the inner suburbs around [[Port of Melbourne]], others are located between the Melbourne CBD and Footscray.\n\nUntil the 1980s a number of suburban stations had their own [[rail yard|goods yards]], with freight trains running over the suburban network, often with the [[Victorian Railways E class (electric)|E]] or [[Victorian Railways L class (electric)|L class]] [[electric locomotive]]s.\n\n== Legislation, governance and access ==\n\n=== Key statutes ===\n{{Main|Transport Integration Act}}\n{{See also|Director of Public Transport|V/Line|VicTrack|Transport Act 1983|Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983}}\nThe prime rail statute in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] is the [[Transport Integration Act]].  The Act establishes the [[Department of Transport (Victoria, 2008\u201313)|Department of Transport]] as the integration agency for Victoria's transport system.  The Act also establishes and sets the charters of the state agencies charged with providing public transport rail services and managing network access for freight services, namely the [[Director of Public Transport]] and [[V/Line]].  In addition, the Act creates [[VicTrack]] which owns the public rail network and associated infrastructure.  Another important statute is the Rail Management Act 1996<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt3.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/742548D962C75039CA257761002C52FD/$FILE/96-79a050.pdf Rail Management Act 1996<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which confers powers on rail operators and provides for a rail access scheme for the state's rail network.\n\n=== Safety ===\n\n==== Regulation ====\n{{Main|Rail Safety Act}}\n{{See also|Director, Transport Safety}}\nThe safety of rail operations in [[Melbourne]] is regulated by the [[Rail Safety Act|Rail Safety Act 2006]] which applies to all commercial passenger and freight operations as well as tourist and heritage railways.<ref>Official copy of the [[Rail Safety Act]] from the Victorian Government legislation web site - http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt3.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/6D4190C62DE6207FCA257761002C568A/$FILE/06-9a016.pdf</ref> The Act creates a framework containing safety duties for all rail industry participants and requires rail operators who manage infrastructure and rolling stock to obtain accreditation prior to commencing operations.  Accredited rail operators are also required to have a [[Safety Management Systems|safety management system]] to guide their operations.\n\n[[Sanctions (law)|Sanctions]] applying to the safety scheme established under the [[Rail Safety Act]] are contained in the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983.<ref>See Part 7 of the Act.  Official copy of the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983 from the official Victorian Government legislation site - http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt5.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/7BB774D3E0245B77CA2577CE00030B90/$FILE/83-9921a153.pdf</ref> The safety [[regulatory agency|regulator]] for the rail system in [[Melbourne]] is the [[Director, Transport Safety]] (trading as [[Director, Transport Safety|Transport Safety Victoria]]) whose office is established under the [[Transport Integration Act|Transport Integration Act 2010]].\n\n==== Investigation ====\n{{Main|Chief Investigator, Transport Safety}}\nRail operators in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] can also be the subject of no blame investigations conducted by the [[Chief Investigator, Transport Safety]] or the [[Australian Transport Safety Bureau]](ATSB).  The Chief Investigator is charged by the [[Transport Integration Act]]<ref>[[Transport Integration Act 2010]], Part 7.</ref> with conducting investigations into rail safety matters including incidents and trends.  ATSB, on the other hand, has jusridiction over the same matters where they occur on the Defined Interstate Rail Network.\n\n=== Ticketing and conduct ===\nTicketing requirements for public transport in [[Melbourne]] are mainly contained in the Transport (Ticketing) Regulations 2006<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/LTObjSt5.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/C6D777772BB02CD3CA2577A5007CB77B/$FILE/06-86sr004.pdf Transport (Ticketing) Regulations 2006<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the Victorian Fares and Ticketing Manual.<ref>[http://www.metlinkmelbourne.com.au/fares-tickets/victorian-fares-and-ticketing-manual Victorian Fares and Ticketing Manual - Metlink - Your guide to public transport in Melbourne and Victoria<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514122346/http://www.metlinkmelbourne.com.au/fares-tickets/victorian-fares-and-ticketing-manual/ |date=14 May 2011 }}</ref> Rules about safe and fair conduct on trains and trams in [[Melbourne]] are generally contained in the [[Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983]]<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubLawToday.nsf/a12f6f60fbd56800ca256de500201e54/6ff43affd338ea35ca2577c60082b59c!OpenDocument Victorian Law Today Act<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the Transport (Conduct) Regulations 2005.<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubLawToday.nsf/b12e276826f7c27fca256de50022686b/2e01dcbed2e5778cca2574e20017da2c!OpenDocument Victorian Law Today Statutory Rule<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> If Metro does not reach its Punctuality and Delivery goals they will give out compensation to eligible customers. In the month of December 2014, Metro Trains had a delivery rate of 98.5%, and a Punctuality rate of 93.60%.<ref>http://www.metrotrains.com.au/metro-performance/</ref> In 2014, Metro Trains were accused of not stopping at underpopulated suburbs' stations in order to arrive on time, this practise has been condemned by the general public and the media. They have offered compensation to affected passengers.\n\n=== Tourist and heritage railways ===\n{{Main|Tourist and Heritage Railways Act}}\nTourist and Heritage Railways in [[Melbourne]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] are currently governed by provisions in the Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983.  In future, they will be regulated by the recently enacted [[Tourist and Heritage Railways Act|Tourist and Heritage Railways Act 2010]],<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/Domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/PubStatbook.nsf/f932b66241ecf1b7ca256e92000e23be/e2cbeabed816bbcdca2577c1001d6f7a!OpenDocument Victorian Statute Book Act<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which commenced in October 2011.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Metro Trains Melbourne]]\n* [[V/Line]]\n* [[Freight railways in Melbourne]]\n* [[Rail transport in Victoria]]\n* [[Transport Integration Act]]\n* [[Director of Public Transport]]\n* [[Tourist and Heritage Railways Act]]\n* [[Rail Safety Act]]\n* [[Director, Transport Safety]]\n* [[Chief Investigator, Transport Safety]]\n* [[Transport Act 1983]]\n* [[Transport (Compliance and Miscellaneous) Act 1983]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading and reviews==\n* ''A review of Melbourne's Rail Franchising reforms'' Currie, Graham (2009) Journeys, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110815213035/http://www.ltaacademy.gov.sg/doc/J09Nov-p36Currie_RailFranchising.pdf Singapore Land Transit Authority Academy]\n* ''Refranchising Melbourne's metropolitan train and tram networks'' Deloitte Touche Thomatsu (2007), [https://web.archive.org/web/20100403021226/http://www.abp.unimelb.edu.au/gamut/pdf/value-assesment.pdf Department of Infrastructure]\n* ''The reliability of Melbourne's trains 1993-2007'' Mees, Dr. Paul (2007); [https://web.archive.org/web/20100403021220/http://www.abp.unimelb.edu.au/gamut/pdf/train-reliability.pdf University of Melbourne Urban Planning Program paper]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/ Public Transport Victoria] - official website of Melbourne's public transport authority\n* [http://www.vicsig.net/ Vicsig] - Victorian railways enthusiast website\n* [http://www.railpage.com.au/ Railpage Australia] - enthusiast website\n* [http://www.vlinecars.com/ V/LineCars.com] - Comprehensive V/Line carriage information & enthusiast website\n\n{{Australian rail}}\n{{MelbournePublicTransport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Railways in Melbourne}}\n[[Category:Public transport in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Victoria (Australia)|Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHost stations and premium stations:Typo fixing, replaced: to upgraded \u2192 to upgrade", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Railways_in_Melbourne"}
{"title_page": "Jabberwocks", "text_new": "{{About|the a cappella group||Jabberwocky (disambiguation){{!}}Jabberwocky}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = The Jabberwocks\n| image            = Jabberwocks_of_Brown_University_logo.jpg\n| caption          = <!-- The Jabberwocks of Brown University logo -->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = The Jabberwocks of Brown University logo\n| landscape        = no\n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = <!-- The Jabberwocks -->\n| origin           = [[Brown University]], [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], [[United States]]\n| genre            = [[Collegiate a cappella]]\n| years_active     = 1949\u2013present\n| label            = \n| website          = [http://www.jabberwocks.com Official Site]}}\nThe '''Jabberwocks''' is the oldest [[Collegiate a cappella|a cappella]] group at [[Brown University]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:WocksHongKong.jpg|thumb|The Jabberwocks tour Hong Kong (2015)]]\nIt began in 1949 as an offshoot of the traditional Men's [[Glee Club]] when four members decided to start their own independent singing group. In 1956, Brown Music Department chair Arlan Coolidge, frustrated that the group was getting bookings that would otherwise have gone to the Glee Club, referred to the Jabberwocks as \"a misguided small group of students whose product is a type of vaudeville.\"<ref name=bam>{{cite web\n| url =  http://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/content/view/1625/40/\n| title = Blue Blazers in a Paisley World\n| date = November\u2013December 1999\n| accessdate = July 9, 2012\n | work = Brown Alumni Magazine\n}}</ref>\nThe original Jabberwocks, a double quartet, \"wore grey flannel suits, white button-down oxford shirts, striped ties and white buck shoes, and travelled to out-of-town concerts in a 1928 [[Rolls-Royce Limited|Rolls Royce]].\"<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=M0460\n| title = Encyclopedia Brunoniana\n| author = Martha Mitchell\n| year = 1993\n| accessdate = July 9, 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nThe group temporarily disappeared in 1975, was resurrected in 1980, and survived a brief period in the mid-1980s when some singers tried to take the group professional. Over the decades the group's repertoire has ranged from 1950s [[doo-wop]], to [[Motown#Motown Sound|Motown]] to contemporary [[Popular music|pop]].<ref name=\"bam\" />\n\nThough originally conceived as an all-male ensemble (with a brief co-ed period in the 1970s), the Jabberwocks affirm that gender is socially constructed and encourage any tenor/bass singer to audition, regardless of gender identity or expression.\n\n[[File:Wocks2017CaliTour.jpg|thumb|The Jabberwocks tour California (2017)]]\n[[File:Wocks2017WinterTour.jpg|thumb|The Jabberwocks tour the NorthEastern United States (2017)]]\n[[File:Wocks2014EuroTour.jpg|thumb|The Jabberwocks, and soloist Stephen Bozier '17, kick off their 2014 European tour with a gig for [[Digitas]][[LBi]] UK]]\n\n==Awards==\n*1993, ''Freedom '90'' (song), Runner up, Best Male Collegiate Song<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.casa.org/cara1993w\n| title = 1993 Contemporary A Cappella Recording Award Winners\n| accessdate = July 9, 2012\n | work = CASA The Contemporary A Cappella Society\n}}</ref>\n*2006, International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella regional quarterfinals, second place<ref>{{cite web\n| url =  http://www.browndailyherald.com/arts-culture/wocks-take-second-at-a-cappella-competition-1.1678052\n|title = Wocks take second at a cappella competition\n| work = The Brown Daily Herald\n| date =  March 5, 2006\n}}</ref>\n*2010, International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella's Northeast semifinals, second place<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.browndailyherald.com/news/jabberwocks-higher-keys-compete-at-mit-1.2197198\n|title = Jabberwocks, Higher Keys compete at MIT\n| work = The Brown Daily Herald\n| date = March 21, 2010\n}}</ref>\n*2010, ''Breaking & Entering'' (album) nominated for the 2010 Contemporary A cappella Recording Awards in three categories.<ref>{{cite web\n| url =   http://www.casa.org/cara2010n\n| title = 2010 Contemporary A Cappella Recording Award Nominees\n| accessdate = July 9, 2012\n | work = CASA The Contemporary A Cappella Society\n}}</ref>\n*2017, \"Taking the Fall\" (album) nominated for the 2017 Contemporary A cappella Recording Awards in three categories.<ref>{{cite web\n| url =   http://www.casa.org/cara2017n\n| title = 2017 Contemporary A Cappella Recording Award Nominees\n| accessdate = July 20, 2017\n | work = CASA The Contemporary A Cappella Society\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Keith Barbour]], American singer-songwriter\n* [[Kid Beyond]], a singer, beat boxer and live looper based in the San Francisco area\n* [[Harrison Chad]], American theater, film, and television actor.\n* [[Michael Weisman]], actor, known for The Glee Project (2011), A.N.T. Farm (2011) and Hot in Cleveland (2010).\n* Brian Cross, actor, known for originating the role of Arnold Gaesling in \"The Snow Geese\" on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] (2013).\n* [[David Gockley]], general director, [[San Francisco Opera]]\n* [[James Naughton]], American director, theater, film and television actor\n* [[Andy Suzuki & The Method|Andy Suzuki]], American singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite web|title=Ne-Yo - Sexy Love (The Brown University Jabberwocks w/ Andy Suzuki A Cappella Cover)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SIi6Ei9t9L4|accessdate=18 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n'''The Jabberwocks of 1953'''<ref>{{cite web\n| title = The Jabberwocks of 1953\n| url = http://library.brown.edu/find/Record/b4939876\n| accessdate = July 9, 2012\n| type = 1 sound disc : analog, 33 1/3 rpm, stereo. ; 12 in.\n}}</ref>\n#''Old rockin' chair''\n#''How high the moon''\n# ''Mood indigo''\n# ''Hello, young lovers''\n# ''[[Wade in the water]]''\n# ''Aba da